{"title_page": "History of the Nintendo Entertainment System", "text_new": "{{about|the history of the console|a general overview of the system itself|Nintendo Entertainment System}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n[[File:NES-Console-Set.jpg|thumb|right|The Nintendo Entertainment System (North America, Europe, Australia, Asia, and Brazil)]]\nThe '''history of the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]]''' ('''NES''') spans the 1982 development of the Family Computer, to the 1985 launch of the NES, to Nintendo's rise to global dominance based upon this platform throughout the late 1980s. The {{Nihongo|'''Family Computer'''|\u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u30ea\u30fc\u30b3\u30f3\u30d4\u30e5\u30fc\u30bf|Famir\u012b Konpy\u016bta|lead=yes}} or {{Nihongo|'''Famicom'''|\u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u30b3\u30f3|Famikon}} was developed in 1982 and launched in 1983 in Japan. Following the North American [[video game crash of 1983]], the Famicom was adapted into the NES which was brazenly launched in North America in 1985. Transitioning the company from its [[arcade game]] history into this combined global [[8-bit]] [[home video game console]] platform, the Famicom and NES continued to aggressively compete with the [[History of video game consoles (fourth generation)|next-generation 16-bit consoles]] including the 1988 [[Sega Genesis]]. The platform was succeeded by the Super Famicom in 1990 and the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] in 1991, but its support and production continued until 1995. Interest in the NES has been renewed by collectors and [[Console emulator|emulators]], including Nintendo's own [[Virtual Console]] platform.\n\n==Origins (1982\u20131984)==\n[[File:Nintendo-Famicom-Console-Set-FL.png|thumb|Family Computer (Japan)]]\nThe North American video game market experienced a period of rapid growth and unprecedented popularity in the late 1970s and early 1980s. Consoles such as the [[Atari 2600]] and the [[Intellivision]] proved to be wildly popular, and many third-party developers arose in their wake to exploit the growing industry. Nintendo was one such development studio, and, by 1982 had found success with a number of [[arcade game]]s, such as ''[[Donkey Kong (arcade game)|Donkey Kong]]'', which was in turn ported to, and packaged with the [[ColecoVision]] console in North America.\n\nLed by [[Masayuki Uemura]], Nintendo's R&D team had been secretly working on a system since 1980, ambitiously targeted to be less expensive than its competitors, yet with performance that could not be surpassed by its competitors for at least a year.<ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 2\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 15, 2003 |chapter=Building the Ultimate Game Machine |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index2.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=7 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805160509/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index2.shtml |archive-date=August 5, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Uemura initially thought of using a modern [[16-bit]] [[Central processing unit|CPU]], but instead settled on the inexpensive [[MOS Technology 6502]], supplementing it with a custom [[graphics processing unit|graphics chip]] (the [[Picture Processing Unit]]).<ref name=\"liedholm1\" /> To keep costs down, suggestions of including a [[keyboard (computing)|keyboard]], [[modem]], and [[floppy disk]] drive were rejected, but expensive circuitry was added to provide a versatile 15-[[pin]] expansion [[Computer port (hardware)|port]] connection on the front of the console for future add-on functionality such as [[peripheral device]]s.\n\nThe keyboard, [[Famicom Modem]], and [[Family Computer Disk System|Famicom Disk System]] would later be released as add-on peripherals, all utilizing the Famicom expansion port. Other peripheral devices connecting via the expansion port would include the [[NES Zapper|Famicom Light Gun]], [[Power Pad|Family Trainer]], and various specialized controllers. Many such devices would be produced for the console, though many of them, including the [[Famicom 3D System]] and Famicom Disk System, were never released outside Japan.\n\nLaunching on July 15, 1983,<ref name=\"SEC Nintendo 2544\">{{cite journal | title=Gaming for 5 to 95 | id=82-2544 | date=March 31, 2003 | publisher=Nintendo Co Ltd. | url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/vprr/03/9999999997-03-043511 | accessdate=December 28, 2014 | journal= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229023442/http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/vprr/03/9999999997-03-043511 | archive-date=December 29, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> the Family Computer (commonly known by the [[wasei-eigo|Japanese-English]] term Famicom) is an 8-bit console using interchangeable [[ROM cartridge|cartridge]]s.<ref name=\"liedholm1\">{{cite web|last1=Liedholm |first1=Marcus |last2=Liedholm |first2=Mattias |title=History of the Nintendo Entertainment System or Famicom |website=Nintendo Land |url=http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?nes/history.htm |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525223925/http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?nes%2Fhistory.htm |archive-date=May 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Famicom was released in Japan on July 15, 1983, for {{JPY|14800}}. Its [[launch title|launch game]] list is ''Donkey Kong'', ''[[Donkey Kong Jr. (arcade game)|Donkey Kong Junior]]'', and ''[[Popeye (video game)|Popeye]]''. The console itself was intentionally designed to look like a toy, with a bright red-and-white color scheme and two hardwired gamepads that are stored visibly at the sides of the unit.\n\nThough selling well in its early months,<ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 3\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 15, 2003 |chapter=Codename: Famicom |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index3.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=7 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805164911/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index3.shtml |archive-date=August 5, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> many Famicom units reportedly [[hang (computing)|froze]] during gameplay. After tracing the problem to a faulty circuit, Nintendo [[product recall|recalled]] all Famicom systems just before the holiday shopping season, and temporarily suspended production of the system while the concerns were addressed, costing Nintendo millions of dollars. The Famicom was subsequently reissued with a new [[motherboard]].<ref name=\"liedholm2\">{{cite web|last1=Liedholm |first1=Marcus |last2=Liedholm |first2=Mattias |title=The Famicom rules the world! \u2013 (1983\u201389) |website=Nintendo Land |url=http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?history/hist3.htm |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728053848/http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?history%2Fhist3.htm |archive-date=July 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Famicom easily outsold its primary competitor, the [[Sega SG-1000]]. By the end of 1984 Nintendo had sold over 2.5 million Famicoms in the Japanese market.<ref name=\"goldberg\">{{cite web |last1=Goldberg |first1=Marty | title=Nintendo Entertainment System 20th Anniversary | date=October 18, 2005 | website=ClassicGaming.com | url=http://www.classicgaming.com/features/articles/nes20th/ |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051124042223/http://www.classicgaming.com/features/articles/nes20th/ |archive-date=November 24, 2005 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Going international (1984\u20131987)==\n\n=== Marketing negotiations with Atari (1983)===\n{{quote box|align=right|width=25%|quote=In the early '80s, Atari debated whether to go with the internally developed successor to the 2600 or a new console that Nintendo wanted us to market. Regrettably, it was my decision not to license the Nintendo system.|source=\u2014Atari  engineer, Steve Bristow<ref name=\"Obituary: Steve Bristow\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/02/obituary-gaming-pioneer-steve-bristow-helped-design-tank-breakout/|title=Obituary: Gaming pioneer Steve Bristow helped design Tank, Breakout|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref>}}\nBolstered by its success in Japan, Nintendo soon turned its attention to foreign markets. As a new console manufacturer, Nintendo had to convince a skeptical public to embrace its system. To this end, Nintendo entered into negotiations with [[Atari]] to release the Famicom outside Japan<ref name=\"teiser\">{{cite web |last1=Teiser |first1=Don |title=Interoffice Memo |date=June 14, 1983 | url=http://www.atarimuseum.com/articles/atari-nintendo-deal.htm |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |via=Atari History Museum}}</ref>  as the Nintendo Enhanced Video System.<ref name=\"NES turns 30\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/07/time-to-feel-old-inside-the-nes-on-its-30th-birthday/|title=The NES turns 30: How it began, worked, and saved an industry|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> Though the two companies reached a tentative agreement, with final contract papers to be signed at the 1983 Summer [[Consumer Electronics Show]] (CES), Atari refused to sign at the last minute, after seeing [[Coleco]], one of its main competitors in the market at that time,<ref name=\"goldberg\" /> demonstrating a prototype of ''Donkey Kong'' for its forthcoming [[Coleco Adam]] [[home computer]] system. Coleco had licensed ''Donkey Kong'' for the [[ColecoVision]] home console, but Atari had the exclusive computer license for the game. Although the game had been originally produced for the ColecoVision and could thus automatically be played on the backward compatible Adam computer, Atari took the demonstration as a sign that Nintendo was also dealing with Coleco. Though the issue was cleared up within a month, by then Atari's financial problems stemming from the [[North American video game crash of 1983]] left the company unable to follow through with the deal.<ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 11\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 15, 2003 |chapter=Coming to America |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index11.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=11 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040701101711/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index11.shtml |archive-date=July 1, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== North America ===\n\n====Advanced Video System home computer (1985)====\n[[File:Nintendo Advanced Video System (retouched).jpg|thumb|Nintendo Advanced Video System accessories as showcased at the Nintendo World Store.<ref name=\"NES World\">{{cite web |first=Martin |last=Nielsen |title=The Nintendo Entertainment System |url=http://www.nesworld.com/nes.php |work=NES World |date=August 19, 2005 |accessdate=July 25, 2009}}</ref> Clockwise from the left: data recorder, keyboard, joystick, Zapper light gun, controllers.]]\n\n{{Commons category|Nintendo Advanced Video System}}\n\nAfter the [[video game crash of 1983]], many American retailers considered video games a passing [[fad]], and greatly reduced or discontinued the inventory of such products.<ref name=\"Rise of Nintendo\" /> Nintendo president [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]] said in 1986, \"Atari collapsed because they gave too much freedom to third-party developers and the market was swamped with rubbish games.\"<ref name=takiff19860620/> After the deal with Atari failed, Nintendo proceeded alone, reconceiving the Famicom console with a sophisticated design language as the \"Nintendo Advanced Video System\" (AVS).<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> To keep the software market for its console from becoming similarly oversaturated, Nintendo added a [[10NES|lockout]] system to obstruct unlicensed software from running on the console, thus allowing Nintendo to enforce strict licensing standards. The software carries the [[Nintendo Seal of Quality]] to communicate the company's approval.\n\nNintendo's product designer Lance Barr, who would continue with the company for decades, retooled the Famicom console with a sleek and sophisticated design language. The toy-like white-and-red color scheme of the Famicom was replaced with a clean and futuristic color scheme of grey, black, and red. The top and bottom portions are in different shades of grey, plus a stripe with black and ribbing along the top, and minor red accents. The shape is boxier: flat on top, and a bottom half that tapered down to a smaller footprint. The front of the main unit features a compartment for storing the wireless controllers out of sight.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> To avoid the stigma of video game consoles, Nintendo issued prerelease marketing of the AVS as a full [[home computer]],<ref name=\"AVS Nintendo\" /> with an included keyboard, [[Compact Cassette#Data recording|cassette data recorder]], and a [[BASIC]] [[interpreter (computing)|interpreter]] software cartridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/2007/11/retro-nintendos/ |title=Retro: Nintendo's 1985 Wireless-Equipped Gaming PC |accessdate=November 2, 2015 |last=Beschizza |first=Rob |date=November 2, 2007 |work=Gadget Lab |publisher=Wired}}</ref> The BASIC interpreter would later be sold together with a keyboard as the ''[[Family BASIC]]'' package, and the cassette deck for data storage would later be released as the [[Famicom Data Recorder]]. The AVS includes a variety of computer-style input devices: gamepads, a handheld joystick, a 3-octave [[musical keyboard]], and the Zapper [[light gun]]. The AVS Zapper is hinged, allowing it to straighten out into a wand form, or bend into a gun form. The AVS uses a wireless [[consumer IR|infrared]] interface for all its peripherals, including keyboard, cassette deck, and controllers.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/> Most of the peripherals for the Advanced Video System are on display at the [[Nintendo World Store]].<ref name=\"NES World\" />\n\nThe system's first known advertisement is in ''[[Consumer Electronics]]'' magazine in 1984, saying \"The evolution of a species is now complete.\"<ref name=\"The First NES Ad\">{{cite web | title=It Took Five Years For One Man To Find The First NES Advertisement | first=Heather | last=Alexandra | date=December 19, 2016 | work=Kotaku | url=https://kotaku.com/it-took-five-years-for-one-man-to-find-the-first-nes-ad-1790282948 | accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref> The AVS was showcased at the January 1985 Winter [[Consumer Electronics Show]] in a reportedly \"very busy\"<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/> booth headed by Nintendo of America's president [[Minoru Arakawa]].<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> There, attendees acknowledged the advanced technology, but responded poorly to the keyboard and wireless functionality.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/><ref name=\"AVS Nintendo\" /><ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 12\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 2003 |chapter=Uphill Struggle |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index12.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=12 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |accessdate=July 25, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805152749/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index12.shtml |archive-date=August 5, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\">{{cite magazine | magazine=Computer Entertainer | title=Video Game Update | date=June 1985 | volume=3 | issue=11 | page=158 | url=https://archive.org/download/ComputerEntertainer/ | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"goldberg\" /> All of the more than 25 games<ref name=\"CSGT January 12, 1985\"/> demonstrated were complete, with no prototypes.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/> No retail pricing information was given by Nintendo,<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/><ref name=\"CSGT January 12, 1985\"/> reportedly seeming to \"test the waters\" with potential distributors, in an unpredictable market.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/> Still wary of video game consoles from the crash, distributors did not apply and retailers did not place orders.<ref name=\"goldberg\" />\n\nAlthough Nintendo's Gail Tilden had reported sales of more than 2.5 million units of the Famicom across the previous 18 months yielding a 90% market share in Japan by the beginning of 1985,<ref name=\"CSGT January 12, 1985\"/> the American [[Video game journalism|video game press]] was skeptical that the AVS could have any success in North America. News Wire reported on January 12, 1985, \"It's hard to believe, but a Japanese company says it intends to introduce a new video-game machine in the United States, despite the collapse of the video-game industry here.\"<ref name=\"CSGT January 12, 1985\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=Colorado Springs Gazette Telegraph | title=CLD-900 combines audio, laser discs | first=Steve | last=Stecklow | via=News Wire | date=January 12, 1985 | page=F32}}</ref> The March 1985 issue of ''[[Electronic Games]]'' magazine stated that \"the videogame market in America has virtually disappeared\" and that \"this could be a miscalculation on Nintendo's part\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Nintendo's Final Solution|journal=[[Electronic Games]]|date=March 1985|editor1-last=Bloom|editor1-first=Steve| volume=4|issue=36|url=https://archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-1985-03/Electronic_Games_Issue_36_Vol_04_01_1985_Mar#page/n7/mode/2up|department=Hotline|accessdate=February 5, 2012|page=9|issn=0730-6687|publisher=Reese Communications|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911010101/https://archive.org/stream/electronic%2Dgames%2Dmagazine%2D1985%2D03/Electronic_Games_Issue_36_Vol_04_01_1985_Mar#page/n7/mode/2up|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 11, 2011}}</ref> Roger Buoy of [[Mindscape]] allegedly said that year, \"Hasn't anyone told them that the videogame industry is dead?\"<ref name=\"wilson199111\">{{cite journal |last1=Wilson |first1=Johnny L. |title=A History of Computer Games |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1991&pub=2&id=88 |format=[[Portable Document Format]] |journal=[[Computer Gaming World]] |edition= |location=Anaheim Hills, California |publisher=Golden Empire Publications |publication-date=November 1991 |issue=88 |pages=22, 24 |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn=0744-6667 |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 18, 2013 |via=Computer Gaming World Museum}}</ref> Video game historian Chris Kohler reflected, \"Retailers didn't want to listen to the little startup Nintendo of America talk about how its Japanese parent company had a huge hit with the Famicom (the 1983 Asian release of what became NES). In America, videogames were dead, dead, ''dead''. Personal computers were the future, and anything that just played games but couldn't do your taxes was hopelessly backwards.\"<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/> ''Computer Entertainer'' openly rebuked the media after attending a humbly optimistic June 1985 CES, \"Can another video game system buck the trend and become a success? ... Perhaps if the press can avoid jumping all over the Nintendo system and let American consumers make up their own minds, we might find out that video games aren't dead after all.\"<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer July 1985\">{{cite magazine | magazine=Computer Entertainer | title=Computer Entertainer | date=July 1985 | volume=4 | issue=4 | url=https://archive.org/download/ComputerEntertainer/ | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Redesign as the Nintendo Entertainment System (1985)====\n[[File:NES-ROB.png|thumb|[[R.O.B.]] (Robotic Operating Buddy). Although it ended up having a short product lifespan, R.O.B. was initially used to help market the NES.]]\n{{quote | text=Nintendo really needed to come up with a point of difference, and some way of getting the retailer to believe that the consumer would embrace this as a different and newer form of entertainment. ... We spent a lot of energy not calling it a videogame in any way.| source=Gail Tilden, Marketing manager of [[Nintendo of America]]<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/>}}\nAt the June 1985 Summer CES, Nintendo returned with a stripped-down and cost-reduced redesign of the AVS, having abandoned the home computer approach.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> Nintendo purposefully designed the system so as not to resemble a video game console, and would avoid terms associated with game consoles, with marketing manager Gail Tilden choosing the term \"[[Game Pak]]\" for cartridges, \"Control Deck\" for the console, and \"Entertainment System\" for the whole platform altogether.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> Renamed the \"Nintendo Entertainment System\" (NES), the new and cost-reduced version lacks most of the upscale features added in the AVS, but retains many of its audiophile-inspired design elements, such as the grey color scheme and boxy form factor. Disappointed with the cosmetically raw prototype part they received from Japan, which they nicknamed \"the lunchbox\", Nintendo of America designers Lance Barr and Don James added the two-tone gray, the black stripe, and the red lettering.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> To obscure the video game connotation, NES replaced the top-loading cartridge slot of the Famicom and AVS with a front-loading chamber for software cartridges that place the inserted cartridge out of view, reminiscent of a [[VCR]]. The Famicom's pair of hard-wired controllers, and the AVS's wireless controllers, were replaced with two custom 7-pin sockets for detachable wired controllers.<ref name=\"AVS Nintendo\">{{cite web|title=The Game System That Almost Wasn't|url=https://www.nintendo.com/newsroom/articles/nes/index.html|website=Nintendo Power Source|publisher=Nintendo of America|accessdate=2 November 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19971012013943/http://www.nintendo.com/newsroom/articles/nes/index.html|archivedate=October 12, 1997}}</ref>\n\nUsing another approach to market the system to North American retailers as an \"entertainment system\", as opposed to a video game console, Nintendo positioned the NES more squarely as a toy, emphasizing the [[NES Zapper|Zapper]] [[light gun]], and more significantly, [[R.O.B.]] (Robotic Operating Buddy), a wireless [[toy robot]] that responds to special screen flashes with mechanized actions.<ref name=\"Rise of Nintendo\" /> Although R.O.B. successfully drew a stream of retailers to Nintendo's Summer 1985 CES booth to see the NES, they were still unwilling to sign up to distribute the console.<ref name=\"goldberg\" />\n\n====North American launch (1985-1986)====\n{{quote box | align=right | width=25% | text=Mr. Arakawa really had this focus ... if it's going to work in New York, it will spread. He always had that sense that if he really believed in something, he really wanted to give it the biggest and best shot. | source=Gail Tilden, marketing}}\nIn a show of strength and confidence by a company that rejected positions of weakness, an intense direct campaign ensued by a dedicated 12-person \"Nintendo SWAT team\" who relocated from Redmond.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Hill |first1=Charles W. L. |last2=Jones | first2=Gareth R. |title=Strategic Management: An Integrated Approach|url=https://archive.org/details/instructorsresou0000hill |url-access=registration |year=2006|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=0-13-102009-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/instructorsresou0000hill/page/127 127]}}</ref> The team included Nintendo of America's president [[Minoru Arakawa]], [[Tukwila, Washington|Tukwila]] warehouse manager and game tester [[Howard Phillips (consultant)|Howard Phillips]], [[Redmond, Washington|Redmond]] warehouse manager and product designer Don James, product designer Lance Barr, marketer Gail Tilden, her boss Ron Judy, and salesperson Bruce Lowry.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> Having failed to secure a retail distributor in the last year, the team would deliver the NES debut itself. This began a series of limited [[test market]] launches at various metropolitan American cities prior to nationwide release. Instead of the traditional business of test launching at a cheaper mid-sized city, Arakawa boldly chose New York City with a $50 million budget.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> Only with R.O.B's reclassification of the NES as a toy, [[telemarketing]] and shopping mall demonstrations, and a risk-free proposition to retailers, did Nintendo secure enough retailer support there of about 500 retailers in New York and New Jersey. As the [[bellwether]] toy retailer and key of New York City, the grandest and most important site was a 15 square foot area at [[FAO Schwarz]].<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> This had a dozen playable NES displays surrounding another giant television, featuring ''Baseball'' being played by real [[Major League Baseball]] players who also signed autographs in order to anchor the curious audiences to a familiar American pastime among all the surreal fantasy games.<ref name=\"NES Baseball at IGN\"/>\n\nIn a huge gamble by Arakawa and without having informed the headquarters in Japan, Nintendo offered to handle all store setup and marketing, extend 90 days [[credit (finance)|credit]] on the merchandise, and accept returns on all unsold inventory. Retailers would pay nothing upfront, and after 90 days would either pay for the merchandise or return it to Nintendo.<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/><ref name=\"NES World\" /> At Nintendo's unprecedented offer of risk absorption,<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/> retailers signed up one by one, with one incredulously saying \"It's your funeral.\"<ref name=\"Game Over\">{{cite book |title=Game Over |last=Sheff |first=David |authorlink=David Sheff |year=1993 |publisher=Random House |location=New York |isbn=0-679-40469-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b_N5FzzD3hsC&printsec=frontcover | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Nintendo Entertainment System then consisted of the Deluxe Set and an initial library of about 16 games which were chosen by playtester Howard Phillips.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/><ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/><ref name=\"NES Baseball at IGN\"/> Each Deluxe Set consists of a Control Deck console, two gamepads, R.O.B., the [[NES Zapper|Zapper]] [[light gun]], and the Game Paks ''[[Gyromite]]'' and ''[[Duck Hunt]]''.<ref name=\"The first to move\">{{Cite magazine|date=November 4, 1985|title=The first to move video action off the screen.|periodical=[[New York Magazine]]|volume=18|issue=43|page=9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7McBAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA9 | accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Sources vary on the library of test [[launch game]]s, but they include these 16: ''[[10-Yard Fight]]'', ''[[Baseball (Nintendo game)|Baseball]]'',<ref name=\"NES Baseball at IGN\"/> ''[[Clu Clu Land]]'', ''[[Duck Hunt]]'', ''[[Excitebike]]'', ''[[Golf (1984 video game)|Golf]]'', ''Gyromite'', ''[[Hogan's Alley (arcade game)|Hogan's Alley]]'', ''[[Ice Climber]]'', ''[[Kung Fu (video game)|Kung Fu]]'', ''[[Pinball (video game)|Pinball]]'', ''[[Soccer (1985 video game)|Soccer]]'', ''[[Stack-Up]]'', ''[[Tennis (1984 video game)|Tennis]]'', ''[[Wild Gunman]]'', and ''[[Wrecking Crew (video game)|Wrecking Crew]]''.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1986\"/><ref name=\"Computer Entertainer July 1985\"/><ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/><!--Wired incorrectly lists Donkey Kong Jr. Math, actually launched nationwide in 1986--><ref name=\"The first to move\"/><ref name=\"NES Baseball at IGN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/01/17/baseball-vc-review|first=Lucas M.|last=Thomas|title=Baseball VC Review |website=[[IGN]]|date=January 16, 2007|accessdate=December 13, 2013}}</ref> The first test launch was in New York City on October 18, 1985, with an initial shipment of 100,000 Deluxe Set systems.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nHeadquartered in a [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]] warehouse oozing with [[Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] hazards \"something like 'rats and snakes and toxic waste'\", the SWAT team worked every day even through Christmas Eve 1985, in what Don James called \"the longest and hardest I ever worked consecutive days in my life\"<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/>  and what Howard Phillips called \"every waking hour ... at the crack of dawn ... seven days a week\".<ref name=\"Journey from Warehouse\">{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/one-mans-journey-from-warehouse-worker-to-nintendo-lege-5938371|title=One Man's Journey From Warehouse Worker to Nintendo Legend|last=Plunkett|first=Luke|date=2012-08-28|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-15}}</ref> President Arakawa joined them at the warehouse and at retail stores, once running a TV up a flight of stairs just to follow in the whole team's footsteps.<ref name=\"Sad But\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/167392/sad_but_true_we_cant_prove_when_.php|title=Sad But True: We Can't Prove When Super Mario Bros. Came Out|website=Gamasutra | first=Frank | last=Cifaldi | date=March 28, 2012 |access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> While unloading their products into stores, the Nintendo of America crew was confronted by strangers who resented any Japanese-influenced company in a time of international trade issues and cheap Japanese clones of American products. A security guard reportedly said, \"You're working for the Japs? I hope you fall flat on your ass.\"<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\">{{cite web | work=Wired | first=Chris | last=Kohler | date=October 18, 2010 | title=Oct. 18, 1985: Nintendo Entertainment System Launches | url=https://www.wired.com/2010/10/1018nintendo-nes-launches/ | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Gail Tilden said, \"I remember one woman coming up to me, and I don't know what sparked her to do this, but she came up to me and said, 'Nintendo. That's a Japanese company, right? ... I hope you ''fail''!'\". Retail staff resentful of the disastrous video game market rolled their eyes at Nintendo staff, with one manager looking at Nintendo's inventory and saying \"Somebody told me I've got to sell this crap.\" The first sale came soon and quietly, of a Deluxe Set and the 15 additional games, to a gentleman who the team later realized was employed by a Japanese competitor.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/>\n\nSales were not high but encouraging throughout the holiday season,<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> though sources vary on how many consoles were sold then.<ref name=\"goldberg\" /><ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 13\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 2003 |chapter=Big Apple, Little N |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index13.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=13 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |accessdate=July 26, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805153333/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index13.shtml |archive-date=August 5, 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1986, Nintendo said it had sold nearly 90,000 units in nine weeks during its late 1985 New York City test.<ref name=\"Here's how\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Steve |date=June 23, 1986 |title=Atari, Sega, and Nintendo Plan Comeback for Video Games |url=http://tnca.myrmid.com/art9.htm |department= |newspaper=HFN: The Weekly Home Furnishings Newspaper |volume= |issue= |location= |publisher= |publication-date= |page= |pages= |at= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn= |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015 |via=The Nintendo Classic Archive}}</ref><ref name=\"Pollack\">{{cite news |last1=Pollack |first1=Andrew |date= |title=Video Games, Once Zapped, In Comeback |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/27/business/video-games-once-zapped-in-comeback.html |newspaper=The New York Times |publication-date=September 27, 1986 |page=A1 |nopp=yes |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn= |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015}}</ref> In January 1986, an independent research firm commissioned by Nintendo delivered a survey of 200 NES owners, showing that the most popular given reason for buying an NES was because children wanted R.O.B. the robot{{emdash}}followed most strongly by good graphics, variety of games, and the uniqueness and newness of the NES package.<ref name=\"Here's how\">{{cite web | title=Here's how Nintendo announced the NES in North America almost 30 years ago | date=October 31, 2015 | first=Owen S. | last=Good | work=Polygon | url=https://www.polygon.com/2015/10/31/9651584/nintendo-nes-anniversary-original-launch-documents | accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref> R.O.B. is credited as a primary factor in building initial support for the NES in North America,<ref name=\"goldberg\" /><ref name=\"Here's how\"/> but the accessory itself was not well received for its entertainment value. Its original Famicom counterpart, the Famicom Robot, was already failing in Japan at the time of the North American launch.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{further|topic=R.O.B.'s key role in the NES launch|R.O.B.}}\n\nNintendo added Los Angeles as the second test market in February 1986,<ref name=\"In Their Words\">{{cite web | title=In Their Words: Remembering the Launch of the Nintendo Entertainment System | date=October 19, 2015 | first=Frank | last=Cifaldi | work=IGN | url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/19/in-their-words-remembering-the-launch-of-the-nintendo-entertainment-system | accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref> followed by Chicago and San Francisco,<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/> then other top 12 US markets, and finally nationwide in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vidgame.net/NINTENDO/NES1.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080413150206/http://www.vidgame.net/NINTENDO/NES1.html|title=Vidgame.net: Nintendo Entertainment System NES Toaser|archivedate=April 13, 2008|publisher=|accessdate=December 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1986\"/> Nintendo and Sega, which was similarly exporting its [[Sega Master System|Master System]] to the US, both planned to spend $15 million in the fourth quarter of 1986 to market their consoles;<ref name=takiff19860620/> later, Nintendo said it planned to spend $16 million and Sega said more than $9 million.<ref name=\"Pollack\"/> Nintendo obtained a distribution deal with toy company [[Worlds of Wonder (toy company)|Worlds of Wonder]], which leveraged its popular [[Teddy Ruxpin]] and [[Lazer Tag]] products to solicit more stores to carry the console.<ref name=\"Rise of Nintendo\">{{cite video |people=Jeremiah Black (director), Jeff Rubin, Josh Shabtai, [[Dan Ackerman]], [[Libe Goad]], Shandi Sullivan, T. J. Allard |date=July 13, 2007 |title=Play Value: The Rise of Nintendo |url=http://www.onnetworks.com/videos/play-value/rise-of-nintendo |format=[[Flash Video]] |medium=podcast |publisher=ON Networks |location= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620211908/http://www.onnetworks.com/videos/play-value/rise-of-nintendo |archivedate=June 20, 2009 |accessdate=November 2, 2015 |time= |quote= |url-status=dead }}</ref> The largest retailer [[Sears]] sold it through its Christmas catalog and the second largest retailer [[Kmart]] sold it in 700 stores.<ref name=\"Pollack\" /> Nintendo sold 1.1 million consoles in 1986, estimating that it could have sold 1.4 million if inventory had held out.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zap! Video Games Make A Comeback |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19870228&id=ChNPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4AIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7027,7957469 |department=Peach Section |newspaper=[[The Blade (Toledo)|The Blade]] |issue= |edition= |location=Toledo, Ohio |publisher= |publication-date=February 28, 1987 |agency=Scripps Howard News Service |page=P-3 |nopp=yes |at= |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn= |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015 |via=Google News Archive}}</ref> Nintendo earned $310 million in sales, out of total 1986 video game industry sales of $430 million,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dvorchak |first1=Robert |title=NEC out to dazzle Nintendo fans |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qKIbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=R04EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5459,6856521 |department=Business |newspaper=[[Times-News (Hendersonville, North Carolina)|Times-News]] |volume= |issue= |edition= |location=Hendersonville, North Carolina |publisher= |publication-date=July 30, 1989 |agency=The Associated Press |page=1D |nopp=yes |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn= |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015 |via=Google News Archive}}</ref> compared to total 1985 industry sales of $100 million.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Belson |first1=Eve |date=December 1988 |title=America's Toy Box |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=82AEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA88#v=onepage&q&f=false |department=Features |journal=[[Orange Coast (magazine)|Orange Coast]] |edition= |location=Costa Mesa, California |publisher=Emmis Communications |publication-date= |volume=14 |issue=12 |page= |pages=87\u201388, 90 |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn=0279-0483 |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nFor the nationwide launch in 1986, the NES was available in two different packages: the fully featured {{US$|249}} Deluxe Set as had been configured during the New York City launch, and a scaled-down Control Deck package which includes the console, two gamepads, and ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]''<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1986\"/>\n\nIn early 1986, Nintendo preannounced the intention to adapt the [[Famicom Disk System]] [[floppy drive]] peripheral to the NES by late 1986,<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1986\">{{cite magazine | magazine=Computer Entertainer | date=February 1986 | title=Nintendo Update | url=https://nintendotimes.com/1986/05/26/computer-entertainer-nes-reviews-news/ | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref> but the need was obviated by the proliferation of larger and faster cartridge technology, and the drive's NES launch was canceled as well as the original being discontinued in Japan.\n\n=== Europe and Oceania ===\nThe NES was also released in Europe, in stages and in a rather haphazard manner.  Most of mainland Europe (excluding Italy, Portugal, and Spain) received the system in 1986, where it was distributed by various companies.  The United Kingdom, Ireland, Italy, Spain, Portugal, Australia, and New Zealand received the system in 1987, where it was distributed by Mattel.<ref>{{cite web|title=PAL releases|url=http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/nes/euro.html|website={{!}}tsr's NES archive|accessdate=March 4, 2015}}</ref>  In Europe, the NES received a less enthusiastic response than it had elsewhere, and Nintendo lagged in market and retail penetration (though the console did see more success later on in its life). The NES did outsell the Master System in Australia, though by a much smaller margin than in North America.<ref name=\"nielsen\">{{cite web | last=Nielsen |first=Martin |date=October 8, 1997 |title=The Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) FAQ v3.0A |url=http://www.classicgaming.com/museum/faqs/nesfaq.shtml |accessdate=January 5, 2005 |via=ClassicGaming.com's Museum |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610072614/http://www.classicgaming.com/museum/faqs/nesfaq.shtml |archive-date=June 10, 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nIn [[South Korea]], the hardware was licensed to [[Hyundai Electronics]], which marketed it as the Comboy. After [[World War II]], the government of Korea  (later South Korea) imposed [[Censorship of Japanese media in South Korea|a wide ban on all Japanese \"cultural products.\"]] Until repealed in 1998, the only way Japanese products could legally enter the South Korean market was through licensing to a third-party (non-Japanese) distributor, as was the case with the Comboy and its successor, the Super Comboy, a version of the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]].<ref name=\"korea\">{{cite web|title=Breaking the Ice|url=http://web-japan.org/trends98/honbun/ntj981207.html|editors=Japan Echo Inc.|website=Trends in Japan|accessdate=19 May 2007|date=7 December 1998}}</ref>\n\n=== Soviet Union/Russia ===\nWhile the NES in its heyday was never officially released in the [[Soviet Union]], an unlicensed Chinese [[clone (computer science)|hardware clone]] named the [[Dendy (console)|Dendy]] was produced in Russia in the early [[1990s in video gaming|1990s]]. Aesthetically, it is an exact duplicate of the original Famicom, with the color scheme and labels altered. The hardwired Famicom controllers were omitted in favor of removable controllers which connect to the front of the unit using [[D-subminiature|DE-9]] serial connectors, identical to those used in the Atari 2600 and the [[Atari 8-bit family]] of computers.<ref name=\"dendy\">{{cite web | title=Dendy | work={{!}}tsr's NES archive | url=http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/odd/pirate/dendy.html | accessdate=February 12, 2006}}</ref>\nAll games sold in Russia for Dendy are [[Copyright infringement|bootleg]] copies, not the original [[Nintendo]] cartridges.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Leading the industry (1987\u20131990)==\nIn North America, the NES widely outsold its primary competitors, the [[Atari 7800]] and the Sega Master System. The successful launch of the NES positioned Nintendo to dominate the home video game market for the remainder of the 1980s. Buoyed by the success of the system, NES [[Game Pak]]s produced similar sales records.\n\nBy 1987, the NES's library had exploded with classic flagship franchise-building and best-selling hits like ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' (1985), ''[[The Legend of Zelda (video game)|The Legend of Zelda]]'' (1986), and ''[[Metroid (video game)|Metroid]]'' (1986). At more than 40 million copies, ''Super Mario Bros.'' (1985) was the [[List of best-selling video games|highest selling video game]] in history for many years. Released in 1988 in Japan, ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' would gross more than US$500 million, with more than 7 million copies sold in America and 4 million copies in Japan, making it the [[List of best-selling video games|most popular and fastest selling]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gottlieb |first1=Rick |date=August 2002 |url=http://www.gamecubicle.com/features-mario-units_sold_sales.htm |title=Super Mario Sales Data: Historical Units Sold Numbers for Mario Bros on NES, SNES, N64... |website=GameCubicle.com |accessdate=December 28, 2014}}</ref> standalone home video game in history.\n\nBy mid-1986, 19% (6.5 million) of Japanese households owned a Famicom;<ref name=takiff19860620>{{cite news|last=Takiff|first=Jonathan|title=Video Games Gain In Japan, Are Due For Assault On U.S.|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QBhcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MlUNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2846,1271636|accessdate=10 April 2012|via=Google News Archive|newspaper=[[The Vindicator]]|date=June 20, 1986|page=2}}</ref> one third by mid-1988.<ref name=\"keiser198806\">{{Cite journal |last=Keiser |first=Gregg |title=One Million Sold in One Day |url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-JUn-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_097_1988_JUn#page/n7/mode/2up |department=News & Notes |journal=[[Compute!]] |location=New York City |publisher=COMPUTE! Publications |publication-date=June 1988 |volume=10 |page=7 |issn=0194-357X |access-date=November 10, 2013}}</ref> By 1990, 30% of American households had the NES, compared to 23% for all personal computers.<ref name=\"cgw199012\">{{cite journal |title=Fusion, Transfusion or Confusion: Future Directions In Computer Entertainment |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1990&pub=2&id=77 |format=[[Portable Document Format]] |department=News & Notes |journal=[[Computer Gaming World]] |edition= |location=Anaheim Hills, California |publisher=Golden Empire Publications |publication-date=December 1990 |issue=77 |pages=26, 28 |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn=0744-6667 |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 10, 2013 |via=Computer Gaming World Museum}}</ref> Its popularity greatly affected the computer-game industry, with executives stating that \"Nintendo's success has destroyed the software entertainment market\" and \"there's been a much greater falling off of disk sales than anyone anticipated\". The growth in sales of the [[Commodore 64]] ended; Nintendo sold almost as many consoles in 1988 as the total number of Commodore 64s had been sold in five years. [[Trip Hawkins]] called Nintendo \"the last hurrah of the 8-bit world\",<ref name=\"ferrell198907\">{{cite journal |last1=Ferrell |first1=Keith |title=Just Kids' Play or Computer in Disguise? |url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-JUn-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_097_1988_JUn#page/n7/mode/2up |format= |department=Features |journal=[[Compute!]] |edition= |location=New York City |publisher=COMPUTE! Publications |publication-date=July 1989 |volume=11 |issue= |pages=28\u201333 |at=|asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn=0194-357X |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |archive-url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_110_1989_Jul#page/n29/mode/2up |archive-date=August 24, 2011 |access-date=November 11, 2013}}</ref> with Nintendo having completely destroyed the Commodore 64 game market as of Christmas 1988.<ref name=\"maher20161222\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.filfre.net/2016/12/a-time-of-endings-part-2-epyx/ |title=A Time of Endings, Part 2: Epyx |last=Maher |first=Jimmy |website=The Digital Antiquarian |publication-date=2016-12-22}}</ref> By 1990, the NES had reached a larger user base in the United States than any previous console, surpassing the previous record set by the Atari 2600 in 1982.<ref name=\"gazzwa\">{{cite web | author=GaZZwa | title=History of games (part 2) | url=http://www.gamingw.net/articles/74 |website=Gaming World |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20051103165622/http://www.gamingw.net/articles/74 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=November 3, 2005}}</ref> In 1990 Nintendo surpassed [[Toyota]] as Japan's most successful corporation.<ref name=\"liedholm3\">{{cite web|last1=Liedholm |first1=Marcus |last2=Liedholm |first2=Mattias |title=A new era \u2013 (1990\u201397) |website=Nintendo Land |url=http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?history/hist3.htm |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728053848/http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?history%2Fhist3.htm |archive-date=July 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Market decline (1990\u20131995)==\n[[File:AVFamicom.jpg|thumb|right|The HVC-101 model of the Family Computer is more compact than its predecessor, and was modeled after the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Famicom]].]]\nIn the late 80s, Nintendo's dominance was addressed by newer, technologically superior consoles. In 1987, [[NEC]] and [[Hudson Soft]] released the [[TurboGrafx-16|PC Engine]], and in 1988, [[Sega]] released the [[History of video game consoles (fourth generation)|16-bit]] [[Mega Drive]]. Both were introduced in North America in 1989, where they were respectively marketed as the TurboGrafx-16 and the Genesis. Facing new competition from the PC Engine in Japan, and the Genesis in North America, Nintendo's market share began to erode. Nintendo responded in the form of the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Famicom]] (Super Nintendo Entertainment System in North America and Europe), the Famicom's 16-bit successor, in 1990. Although Nintendo announced its intention to continue to support the Famicom alongside its newer console, the success of the newer offering began to draw even more gamers and developers from the NES, whose decline accelerated. Nintendo did continue support of the NES for about three years after the September 1991 release of the Super NES, with the NES's final [[First-party developer|first-party]] games being ''[[Zoda's Revenge: StarTropics II]]'' and ''[[Wario's Woods]]''.\n\nA revised Famicom (HVC-101 model) was released in Japan in 1993. It takes some design cues from the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]]. The HVC-101 model replaces the original HVC-001 model's [[RF modulator]] with [[RCA connector|RCA]] [[composite video|composite audio/video]] output, eliminates the hardwired controllers, and features a more compact case design. Retailing for \u00a54,800 to \u00a57,200 (equivalent to approximately $42 to $60 USD), the HVC-101 model remained in production for almost a decade before being finally discontinued in 2003.<ref name=\"avfami\">{{cite web |title=AV Family Computer |website={{!}}tsr's NES archive | url=http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/fc/avfami.html |accessdate=February 12, 2006}}</ref> The case design of the AV Famicom was adopted for a subsequent North American rerelease of the NES. The [[Nintendo Entertainment System (redesigned model)|NES-101 model]] differs from the Japanese HVC-101 model in that it omits the RCA composite output connectors of the original NES-001 model, and sports only RF output capabilities.<ref name=\"nes2\">{{cite web |title=Nintendo Entertainment System 2 |website=Vidgame.net |url=http://www.vidgame.net/NINTENDO/NES2.html |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080202132819/http://www.vidgame.net/NINTENDO/NES2.html |archive-date=February 2, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[ASCII Entertainment]] reported in early 1993 that stores still offered 100 NES games, compared to 100 on shelves for Genesis and 50 for SNES.<ref name=\"wilson199306\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1993&pub=2&id=107|title=The Software Publishing Association Spring Symposium 1993|last=Wilson|first=Johnny L.|date=June 1993|work=Computer Gaming World|accessdate=July 7, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702235945/http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1993&pub=2&id=107|archivedate=July 2, 2014|url-status=live|page=96}}</ref> After a full decade of production, the NES was formally discontinued in the U.S. in 1995.<ref name=\"nielsen\" /> By the end of its run, more than 60 million NES units had been sold throughout the world.<ref name=\"sales\">{{cite web |title={{!}} Nintendo - Corporate Information {{!}} Company History |website=Nintendo.com |url=https://www.nintendo.com/corp/history.jsp |accessdate=November 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discontinuation and emulation (1995\u2013present)==\n{{refimprove section |date=December 2014}}\n[[File:Nesticle.jpg|thumb|Bloodlust Software's NESticle]]\nThe NES's market presence declined from 1991 to 1995, with the Sega Genesis and Nintendo's own Super NES gaining market share, with next-generation [[CD-ROM]]-based systems forthcoming. Even though the NES was discontinued in North America in 1995, many millions of cartridges for the system existed. The secondhand market of video rental stores, thrift stores, yard sales, flea markets, and games repackaged by Game Time Inc. / Game Trader Inc. and sold at retail stores such as [[K-Mart]], was burgeoning. Many people began to rediscover the NES around this time, and by 1997, many older NES games were becoming popular with collectors.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nAt the same time, [[computer programmer]]s began to develop [[Console emulator|emulators]] capable of reproducing the internal workings of the NES on modern personal computers. When paired with a [[ROM image]] (a [[bit]]-for-bit copy of a NES cartridge's program code), the games can be played on a computer. Emulators also come with a variety of built-in functions that change the gaming experience, such as [[Saved game|save states]] which allow the player to save and resume progress at an exact spot in the game.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nNintendo did not respond positively to these developments and became one of the most vocal opponents of ROM image trading. Nintendo and its supporters claim that such trading represents blatant [[Copyright infringement of software|software piracy]].<ref name=\"legalfaq\">{{cite web |title={{!}} Nintendo - Corporate Information {{!}} Legal Information (Copyrights, Emulators, ROMs, etc.) |website=Nintendo.com |url=https://www.nintendo.com/corp/legal.jsp |accessdate=December 28, 2014}}</ref> Proponents of ROM image trading argue that emulation preserves many classic games for future generations, outside of their more fragile cartridge formats.<ref name=\"pettus\">{{citation |last=Pettus |first=Sam |date=10 March 2000 |title=Emulation: Right or Wrong? |url=http://www.worldofspectrum.org/EmuFAQ2000/ |chapter=Module One: The Emulator {{!}} Part 1 - The Basis for Emulation |chapter-url=http://www.worldofspectrum.org/EmuFAQ2000/EmuFAQ_M1P1.htm |edition=Final |accessdate=November 2, 2015 |via=[http://www.worldofspectrum.org/ World of Spectrum]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Nintendo announced plans to make classic NES titles available on the [[Virtual Console]] download service for the [[Wii]] console, which is based on their own emulation technology. Initial titles released included ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', ''[[The Legend of Zelda (1986 video game)|The Legend of Zelda]]'' and ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'',<ref name=\"uswiivirtualconsole\">{{cite web | title=IGN: Wii: 62 Games in First Five Weeks | work=IGN Wii | url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/742/742962p1.html | accessdate=November 3, 2006 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/618x13OvE?url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/742/742962p1.html | archive-date=August 23, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref> with blockbuster titles such as ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', ''[[Mike Tyson's Punch-Out!!|Punch-Out!!]]'' and ''[[Metroid]]'' appearing in the following months.<ref>{{cite web | title=Nintendo: Virtual Console | work=Nintendo | url=http://wii.nintendo.com/virtualconsole.jsp | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012013404/http://wii.nintendo.com/virtualconsole.jsp | archivedate=October 12, 2007| accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Nintendo Co., Ltd. announced that it would no longer repair Famicom systems, due to an increasing shortage of the necessary parts.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nintendo's classic Famicom faces end of road |url=http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jAJfrC1k8lDKLOCGJu4VonjOYxBg |agency=[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] |date=October 31, 2007 |accessdate=November 9, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071105193128/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jAJfrC1k8lDKLOCGJu4VonjOYxBg |archive-date=November 5, 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Third generation of video game consoles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Nintendo Entertainment System}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Nintendo Entertainment System}}\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment System]]\n[[Category:History of video games|Nintendo Entertainment System]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the history of the console|a general overview of the system itself|Nintendo Entertainment System}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n[[File:NES-Console-Set.jpg|thumb|right|The Nintendo Entertainment System (North America, Europe, Australia, Asia, and Brazil)]]\nThe '''history of the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]]''' ('''NES''') spans the 1982 development of the Family Computer, to the 1985 launch of the NES, to Nintendo's rise to global dominance based upon this platform throughout the late 1980s. The {{Nihongo|'''Family Computer'''|\u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u30ea\u30fc\u30b3\u30f3\u30d4\u30e5\u30fc\u30bf|Famir\u012b Konpy\u016bta|lead=yes}} or {{Nihongo|'''Famicom'''|\u30d5\u30a1\u30df\u30b3\u30f3|Famikon}} was developed in 1982 and launched in 1983 in Japan. Following the North American [[video game crash of 1983]], the Famicom was adapted into the NES which was brazenly launched in North America in 1985. Transitioning the company from its [[arcade game]] history into this combined global [[8-bit]] [[home video game console]] platform, the Famicom and NES continued to aggressively compete with the [[History of video game consoles (fourth generation)|next-generation 16-bit consoles]] including the 1988 [[Sega Genesis]]. The platform was succeeded by the Super Famicom in 1990 and the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] in 1991, but its support and production continued until 1995. Interest in the NES has been renewed by collectors and [[Console emulator|emulators]], including Nintendo's own [[Virtual Console]] platform.\n\n==Origins (1982\u20131984)==\n[[File:Nintendo-Famicom-Console-Set-FL.png|thumb|Family Computer (Japan)]]\nThe North American video game market experienced a period of rapid growth and unprecedented popularity in the late 1970s and early 1980s. Consoles such as the [[Atari 2600]] and the [[Intellivision]] proved to be wildly popular, and many third-party developers arose in their wake to exploit the growing industry. Nintendo was one such development studio, and, by 1982 had found success with a number of [[arcade game]]s, such as ''[[Donkey Kong (arcade game)|Donkey Kong]]'', which was in turn ported to, and packaged with the [[ColecoVision]] console in North America.\n\nLed by [[Masayuki Uemura]], Nintendo's R&D team had been secretly working on a system since 1980, ambitiously targeted to be less expensive than its competitors, yet with performance that could not be surpassed by its competitors for at least a year.<ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 2\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 15, 2003 |chapter=Building the Ultimate Game Machine |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index2.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=7 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805160509/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index2.shtml |archive-date=August 5, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Uemura initially thought of using a modern [[16-bit]] [[Central processing unit|CPU]], but instead settled on the inexpensive [[MOS Technology 6502]], supplementing it with a custom [[graphics processing unit|graphics chip]] (the [[Picture Processing Unit]]).<ref name=\"liedholm1\" /> To keep costs down, suggestions of including a [[keyboard (computing)|keyboard]], [[modem]], and [[floppy disk]] drive were rejected, but expensive circuitry was added to provide a versatile 15-[[pin]] expansion [[Computer port (hardware)|port]] connection on the front of the console for future add-on functionality such as [[peripheral device]]s.\n\nThe keyboard, [[Famicom Modem]], and [[Family Computer Disk System|Famicom Disk System]] would later be released as add-on peripherals, all utilizing the Famicom expansion port. Other peripheral devices connecting via the expansion port would include the [[NES Zapper|Famicom Light Gun]], [[Power Pad|Family Trainer]], and various specialized controllers. Many such devices would be produced for the console, though many of them, including the [[Famicom 3D System]] and Famicom Disk System, were never released outside Japan.\n\nLaunching on July 15, 1983,<ref name=\"SEC Nintendo 2544\">{{cite journal | title=Gaming for 5 to 95 | id=82-2544 | date=March 31, 2003 | publisher=Nintendo Co Ltd. | url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/vprr/03/9999999997-03-043511 | accessdate=December 28, 2014 | journal= | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229023442/http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/vprr/03/9999999997-03-043511 | archive-date=December 29, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> the Family Computer (commonly known by the [[wasei-eigo|Japanese-English]] term Famicom) is an 8-bit console using interchangeable [[ROM cartridge|cartridge]]s.<ref name=\"liedholm1\">{{cite web|last1=Liedholm |first1=Marcus |last2=Liedholm |first2=Mattias |title=History of the Nintendo Entertainment System or Famicom |website=Nintendo Land |url=http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?nes/history.htm |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525223925/http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?nes%2Fhistory.htm |archive-date=May 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Famicom was released in Japan on July 15, 1983, for {{JPY|14800}}. Its [[launch title|launch game]] list is ''Donkey Kong'', ''[[Donkey Kong Jr. (arcade game)|Donkey Kong Junior]]'', and ''[[Popeye (video game)|Popeye]]''. The console itself was intentionally designed to look like a toy, with a bright red-and-white color scheme and two hardwired gamepads that are stored visibly at the sides of the unit.\n\nThough selling well in its early months,<ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 3\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 15, 2003 |chapter=Codename: Famicom |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index3.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=7 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805164911/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index3.shtml |archive-date=August 5, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref> many Famicom units reportedly [[hang (computing)|froze]] during gameplay. After tracing the problem to a faulty circuit, Nintendo [[product recall|recalled]] all Famicom systems just before the holiday shopping season, and temporarily suspended production of the system while the concerns were addressed, costing Nintendo millions of dollars. The Famicom was subsequently reissued with a new [[motherboard]].<ref name=\"liedholm2\">{{cite web|last1=Liedholm |first1=Marcus |last2=Liedholm |first2=Mattias |title=The Famicom rules the world! \u2013 (1983\u201389) |website=Nintendo Land |url=http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?history/hist3.htm |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728053848/http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?history%2Fhist3.htm |archive-date=July 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Famicom easily outsold its primary competitor, the [[Sega SG-1000]]. By the end of 1984 Nintendo had sold over 2.5 million Famicoms in the Japanese market.<ref name=\"goldberg\">{{cite web |last1=Goldberg |first1=Marty | title=Nintendo Entertainment System 20th Anniversary | date=October 18, 2005 | website=ClassicGaming.com | url=http://www.classicgaming.com/features/articles/nes20th/ |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051124042223/http://www.classicgaming.com/features/articles/nes20th/ |archive-date=November 24, 2005 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Going international (1984\u20131987)==\n\n=== Marketing negotiations with Atari (1983)===\n{{quote box|align=right|width=25%|quote=In the early '80s, Atari debated whether to go with the internally developed successor to the 2600 or a new console that Nintendo wanted us to market. Regrettably, it was my decision not to license the Nintendo system.|source=\u2014Atari  engineer, Steve Bristow<ref name=\"Obituary: Steve Bristow\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/02/obituary-gaming-pioneer-steve-bristow-helped-design-tank-breakout/|title=Obituary: Gaming pioneer Steve Bristow helped design Tank, Breakout|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref>}}\nBolstered by its success in Japan, Nintendo soon turned its attention to foreign markets. As a new console manufacturer, Nintendo had to convince a skeptical public to embrace its system. To this end, Nintendo entered into negotiations with [[Atari]] to release the Famicom outside Japan<ref name=\"teiser\">{{cite web |last1=Teiser |first1=Don |title=Interoffice Memo |date=June 14, 1983 | url=http://www.atarimuseum.com/articles/atari-nintendo-deal.htm |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |via=Atari History Museum}}</ref>  as the Nintendo Enhanced Video System.<ref name=\"NES turns 30\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2013/07/time-to-feel-old-inside-the-nes-on-its-30th-birthday/|title=The NES turns 30: How it began, worked, and saved an industry|work=Ars Technica|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> Though the two companies reached a tentative agreement, with final contract papers to be signed at the 1983 Summer [[Consumer Electronics Show]] (CES), Atari refused to sign at the last minute, after seeing [[Coleco]], one of its main competitors in the market at that time,<ref name=\"goldberg\" /> demonstrating a prototype of ''Donkey Kong'' for its forthcoming [[Coleco Adam]] [[home computer]] system. Coleco had licensed ''Donkey Kong'' for the [[ColecoVision]] home console, but Atari had the exclusive computer license for the game. Although the game had been originally produced for the ColecoVision and could thus automatically be played on the backward compatible Adam computer, Atari took the demonstration as a sign that Nintendo was also dealing with Coleco. Though the issue was cleared up within a month, by then Atari's financial problems stemming from the [[North American video game crash of 1983]] left the company unable to follow through with the deal.<ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 11\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 15, 2003 |chapter=Coming to America |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index11.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=11 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040701101711/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index11.shtml |archive-date=July 1, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== North America ===\n\n====Advanced Video System home computer (1985)====\n[[File:Nintendo Advanced Video System (retouched).jpg|thumb|Nintendo Advanced Video System accessories as showcased at the Nintendo World Store.<ref name=\"NES World\">{{cite web |first=Martin |last=Nielsen |title=The Nintendo Entertainment System |url=http://www.nesworld.com/nes.php |work=NES World |date=August 19, 2005 |accessdate=July 25, 2009}}</ref> Clockwise from the left: data recorder, keyboard, joystick, Zapper light gun, controllers.]]\n\n{{Commons category|Nintendo Advanced Video System}}\n\nAfter the [[video game crash of 1983]], many American retailers considered video games a passing [[fad]], and greatly reduced or discontinued the inventory of such products.<ref name=\"Rise of Nintendo\" /> Nintendo president [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]] said in 1986, \"Atari collapsed because they gave too much freedom to third-party developers and the market was swamped with rubbish games.\"<ref name=takiff19860620/> After the deal with Atari failed, Nintendo proceeded alone, reconceiving the Famicom console with a sophisticated design language as the \"Nintendo Advanced Video System\" (AVS).<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> To keep the software market for its console from becoming similarly oversaturated, Nintendo added a [[10NES|lockout]] system to obstruct unlicensed software from running on the console, thus allowing Nintendo to enforce strict licensing standards. The software carries the [[Nintendo Seal of Quality]] to communicate the company's approval.\n\nNintendo's product designer Lance Barr, who would continue with the company for decades, retooled the Famicom console with a sleek and sophisticated design language. The toy-like white-and-red color scheme of the Famicom was replaced with a clean and futuristic color scheme of grey, black, and red. The top and bottom portions are in different shades of grey, plus a stripe with black and ribbing along the top, and minor red accents. The shape is boxier: flat on top, and a bottom half that tapered down to a smaller footprint. The front of the main unit features a compartment for storing the wireless controllers out of sight.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> To avoid the stigma of video game consoles, Nintendo issued prerelease marketing of the AVS as a full [[home computer]],<ref name=\"AVS Nintendo\" /> with an included keyboard, [[Compact Cassette#Data recording|cassette data recorder]], and a [[BASIC]] [[interpreter (computing)|interpreter]] software cartridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/2007/11/retro-nintendos/ |title=Retro: Nintendo's 1985 Wireless-Equipped Gaming PC |accessdate=November 2, 2015 |last=Beschizza |first=Rob |date=November 2, 2007 |work=Gadget Lab |publisher=Wired}}</ref> The BASIC interpreter would later be sold together with a keyboard as the ''[[Family BASIC]]'' package, and the cassette deck for data storage would later be released as the [[Famicom Data Recorder]]. The AVS includes a variety of computer-style input devices: gamepads, a handheld joystick, a 3-octave [[musical keyboard]], and the Zapper [[light gun]]. The AVS Zapper is hinged, allowing it to straighten out into a wand form, or bend into a gun form. The AVS uses a wireless [[consumer IR|infrared]] interface for all its peripherals, including keyboard, cassette deck, and controllers.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/> Most of the peripherals for the Advanced Video System are on display at the [[Nintendo World Store]].<ref name=\"NES World\" />\n\nThe system's first known advertisement is in ''[[Consumer Electronics]]'' magazine in 1984, saying \"The evolution of a species is now complete.\"<ref name=\"The First NES Ad\">{{cite web | title=It Took Five Years For One Man To Find The First NES Advertisement | first=Heather | last=Alexandra | date=December 19, 2016 | work=Kotaku | url=https://kotaku.com/it-took-five-years-for-one-man-to-find-the-first-nes-ad-1790282948 | accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref> The AVS was showcased at the January 1985 Winter [[Consumer Electronics Show]] in a reportedly \"very busy\"<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/> booth headed by Nintendo of America's president [[Minoru Arakawa]].<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> There, attendees acknowledged the advanced technology, but responded poorly to the keyboard and wireless functionality.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/><ref name=\"AVS Nintendo\" /><ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 12\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 2003 |chapter=Uphill Struggle |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index12.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=12 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |accessdate=July 25, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805152749/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index12.shtml |archive-date=August 5, 2004 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\">{{cite magazine | magazine=Computer Entertainer | title=Video Game Update | date=June 1985 | volume=3 | issue=11 | page=158 | url=https://archive.org/download/ComputerEntertainer/ | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"goldberg\" /> All of the more than 25 games<ref name=\"CSGT January 12, 1985\"/> demonstrated were complete, with no prototypes.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/> No retail pricing information was given by Nintendo,<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/><ref name=\"CSGT January 12, 1985\"/> reportedly seeming to \"test the waters\" with potential distributors, in an unpredictable market.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1985\"/> Still wary of video game consoles from the crash, distributors did not apply and retailers did not place orders.<ref name=\"goldberg\" />\n\nAlthough Nintendo's Gail Tilden had reported sales of more than 2.5 million units of the Famicom across the previous 18 months yielding a 90% market share in Japan by the beginning of 1985,<ref name=\"CSGT January 12, 1985\"/> the American [[Video game journalism|video game press]] was skeptical that the AVS could have any success in North America. News Wire reported on January 12, 1985, \"It's hard to believe, but a Japanese company says it intends to introduce a new video-game machine in the United States, despite the collapse of the video-game industry here.\"<ref name=\"CSGT January 12, 1985\">{{cite newspaper | newspaper=Colorado Springs Gazette Telegraph | title=CLD-900 combines audio, laser discs | first=Steve | last=Stecklow | via=News Wire | date=January 12, 1985 | page=F32}}</ref> The March 1985 issue of ''[[Electronic Games]]'' magazine stated that \"the videogame market in America has virtually disappeared\" and that \"this could be a miscalculation on Nintendo's part\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Nintendo's Final Solution|journal=[[Electronic Games]]|date=March 1985|editor1-last=Bloom|editor1-first=Steve| volume=4|issue=36|url=https://archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-1985-03/Electronic_Games_Issue_36_Vol_04_01_1985_Mar#page/n7/mode/2up|department=Hotline|accessdate=February 5, 2012|page=9|issn=0730-6687|publisher=Reese Communications|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911010101/https://archive.org/stream/electronic%2Dgames%2Dmagazine%2D1985%2D03/Electronic_Games_Issue_36_Vol_04_01_1985_Mar#page/n7/mode/2up|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 11, 2011}}</ref> Roger Buoy of [[Mindscape]] allegedly said that year, \"Hasn't anyone told them that the videogame industry is dead?\"<ref name=\"wilson199111\">{{cite journal |last1=Wilson |first1=Johnny L. |title=A History of Computer Games |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1991&pub=2&id=88 |format=[[Portable Document Format]] |journal=[[Computer Gaming World]] |edition= |location=Anaheim Hills, California |publisher=Golden Empire Publications |publication-date=November 1991 |issue=88 |pages=22, 24 |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn=0744-6667 |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 18, 2013 |via=Computer Gaming World Museum}}</ref> Video game historian Chris Kohler reflected, \"Retailers didn't want to listen to the little startup Nintendo of America talk about how its Japanese parent company had a huge hit with the Famicom (the 1983 Asian release of what became NES). In America, videogames were dead, dead, ''dead''. Personal computers were the future, and anything that just played games but couldn't do your taxes was hopelessly backwards.\"<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/> ''Computer Entertainer'' openly rebuked the media after attending a humbly optimistic June 1985 CES, \"Can another video game system buck the trend and become a success? ... Perhaps if the press can avoid jumping all over the Nintendo system and let American consumers make up their own minds, we might find out that video games aren't dead after all.\"<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer July 1985\">{{cite magazine | magazine=Computer Entertainer | title=Computer Entertainer | date=July 1985 | volume=4 | issue=4 | url=https://archive.org/download/ComputerEntertainer/ | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Redesign as the Nintendo Entertainment System (1985)====\n[[File:NES-ROB.png|thumb|[[R.O.B.]] (Robotic Operating Buddy). Although it ended up having a short product lifespan, R.O.B. was initially used to help market the NES.]]\n{{quote | text=Nintendo really needed to come up with a point of difference, and some way of getting the retailer to believe that the consumer would embrace this as a different and newer form of entertainment. ... We spent a lot of energy not calling it a videogame in any way.| source=Gail Tilden, Marketing manager of [[Nintendo of America]]<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/>}}\nAt the June 1985 Summer CES, Nintendo returned with a stripped-down and cost-reduced redesign of the AVS, having abandoned the home computer approach.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> Nintendo purposefully designed the system so as not to resemble a video game console, and would avoid terms associated with game consoles, with marketing manager Gail Tilden choosing the term \"[[Game Pak]]\" for cartridges, \"Control Deck\" for the console, and \"Entertainment System\" for the whole platform altogether.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> Renamed the \"Nintendo Entertainment System\" (NES), the new and cost-reduced version lacks most of the upscale features added in the AVS, but retains many of its audiophile-inspired design elements, such as the grey color scheme and boxy form factor. Disappointed with the cosmetically raw prototype part they received from Japan, which they nicknamed \"the lunchbox\", Nintendo of America designers Lance Barr and Don James added the two-tone gray, the black stripe, and the red lettering.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> To obscure the video game connotation, NES replaced the top-loading cartridge slot of the Famicom and AVS with a front-loading chamber for software cartridges that place the inserted cartridge out of view, reminiscent of a [[VCR]]. The Famicom's pair of hard-wired controllers, and the AVS's wireless controllers, were replaced with two custom 7-pin sockets for detachable wired controllers.<ref name=\"AVS Nintendo\">{{cite web|title=The Game System That Almost Wasn't|url=https://www.nintendo.com/newsroom/articles/nes/index.html|website=Nintendo Power Source|publisher=Nintendo of America|accessdate=2 November 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19971012013943/http://www.nintendo.com/newsroom/articles/nes/index.html|archivedate=October 12, 1997}}</ref>\n\nUsing another approach to market the system to North American retailers as an \"entertainment system\", as opposed to a video game console, Nintendo positioned the NES more squarely as a toy, emphasizing the [[NES Zapper|Zapper]] [[light gun]], and more significantly, [[R.O.B.]] (Robotic Operating Buddy), a wireless [[toy robot]] that responds to special screen flashes with mechanized actions.<ref name=\"Rise of Nintendo\" /> Although R.O.B. successfully drew a stream of retailers to Nintendo's Summer 1985 CES booth to see the NES, they were still unwilling to sign up to distribute the console.<ref name=\"goldberg\" />\n\n====North American launch (1985-1986)====\n{{quote box | align=right | width=25% | text=Mr. Arakawa really had this focus ... if it's going to work in New York, it will spread. He always had that sense that if he really believed in something, he really wanted to give it the biggest and best shot. | source=Gail Tilden, marketing}}\nIn a show of strength and confidence by a company that rejected positions of weakness, an intense direct campaign ensued by a dedicated 12-person \"Nintendo SWAT team\" who relocated from Redmond.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Hill |first1=Charles W. L. |last2=Jones | first2=Gareth R. |title=Strategic Management: An Integrated Approach|url=https://archive.org/details/instructorsresou0000hill |url-access=registration |year=2006|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|isbn=0-13-102009-9|page=[https://archive.org/details/instructorsresou0000hill/page/127 127]}}</ref> The team included Nintendo of America's president [[Minoru Arakawa]], [[Tukwila, Washington|Tukwila]] warehouse manager and game tester [[Howard Phillips (consultant)|Howard Phillips]], [[Redmond, Washington|Redmond]] warehouse manager and product designer Don James, product designer Lance Barr, marketer Gail Tilden, her boss Ron Judy, and salesperson Bruce Lowry.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> Having failed to secure a retail distributor in the last year, the team would deliver the NES debut itself. This began a series of limited [[test market]] launches at various metropolitan American cities prior to nationwide release. Instead of the traditional business of test launching at a cheaper mid-sized city, Arakawa boldly chose New York City with a $50 million budget.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> Only with R.O.B's reclassification of the NES as a toy, [[telemarketing]] and shopping mall demonstrations, and a risk-free proposition to retailers, did Nintendo secure enough retailer support there of about 500 retailers in New York and New Jersey. As the [[bellwether]] toy retailer and key of New York City, the grandest and most important site was a 15 square foot area at [[FAO Schwarz]].<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> This had a dozen playable NES displays surrounding another giant television, featuring ''Baseball'' being played by real [[Major League Baseball]] players who also signed autographs in order to anchor the curious audiences to a familiar American pastime among all the surreal fantasy games.<ref name=\"NES Baseball at IGN\"/>\n\nIn a huge gamble by Arakawa and without having informed the headquarters in Japan, Nintendo offered to handle all store setup and marketing, extend 90 days [[credit (finance)|credit]] on the merchandise, and accept returns on all unsold inventory. Retailers would pay nothing upfront, and after 90 days would either pay for the merchandise or return it to Nintendo.<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/><ref name=\"NES World\" /> At Nintendo's unprecedented offer of risk absorption,<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/> retailers signed up one by one, with one incredulously saying \"It's your funeral.\"<ref name=\"Game Over\">{{cite book |title=Game Over |last=Sheff |first=David |authorlink=David Sheff |year=1993 |publisher=Random House |location=New York |isbn=0-679-40469-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b_N5FzzD3hsC&printsec=frontcover | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Nintendo Entertainment System then consisted of the Deluxe Set and an initial library of about 16 games which were chosen by playtester Howard Phillips.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/><ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/><ref name=\"NES Baseball at IGN\"/> Each Deluxe Set consists of a Control Deck console, two gamepads, R.O.B., the [[NES Zapper|Zapper]] [[light gun]], and the Game Paks ''[[Gyromite]]'' and ''[[Duck Hunt]]''.<ref name=\"The first to move\">{{Cite magazine|date=November 4, 1985|title=The first to move video action off the screen.|periodical=[[New York Magazine]]|volume=18|issue=43|page=9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7McBAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA9 | accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref> Sources vary on the library of test [[launch game]]s, but they include these 16: ''[[10-Yard Fight]]'', ''[[Baseball (Nintendo game)|Baseball]]'',<ref name=\"NES Baseball at IGN\"/> ''[[Clu Clu Land]]'', ''[[Duck Hunt]]'', ''[[Excitebike]]'', ''[[Golf (1984 video game)|Golf]]'', ''Gyromite'', ''[[Hogan's Alley (arcade game)|Hogan's Alley]]'', ''[[Ice Climber]]'', ''[[Kung Fu (video game)|Kung Fu]]'', ''[[Pinball (video game)|Pinball]]'', ''[[Soccer (1985 video game)|Soccer]]'', ''[[Stack-Up]]'', ''[[Tennis (1984 video game)|Tennis]]'', ''[[Wild Gunman]]'', and ''[[Wrecking Crew (video game)|Wrecking Crew]]''.<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1986\"/><ref name=\"Computer Entertainer July 1985\"/><ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/><!--Wired incorrectly lists Donkey Kong Jr. Math, actually launched nationwide in 1986--><ref name=\"The first to move\"/><ref name=\"NES Baseball at IGN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/01/17/baseball-vc-review|first=Lucas M.|last=Thomas|title=Baseball VC Review |website=[[IGN]]|date=January 16, 2007|accessdate=December 13, 2013}}</ref> The first test launch was in New York City on October 18, 1985, with an initial shipment of 100,000 Deluxe Set systems.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nHeadquartered in a [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]] warehouse oozing with [[Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] hazards \"something like 'rats and snakes and toxic waste'\", the SWAT team worked every day even through Christmas Eve 1985, in what Don James called \"the longest and hardest I ever worked consecutive days in my life\"<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/>  and what Howard Phillips called \"every waking hour ... at the crack of dawn ... seven days a week\".<ref name=\"Journey from Warehouse\">{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/one-mans-journey-from-warehouse-worker-to-nintendo-lege-5938371|title=One Man's Journey From Warehouse Worker to Nintendo Legend|last=Plunkett|first=Luke|date=2012-08-28|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-15}}</ref> President Arakawa joined them at the warehouse and at retail stores, once running a TV up a flight of stairs just to follow in the whole team's footsteps.<ref name=\"Sad But\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/167392/sad_but_true_we_cant_prove_when_.php|title=Sad But True: We Can't Prove When Super Mario Bros. Came Out|website=Gamasutra | first=Frank | last=Cifaldi | date=March 28, 2012 |access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> While unloading their products into stores, the Nintendo of America crew was confronted by strangers who resented any Japanese-influenced company in a time of international trade issues and cheap Japanese clones of American products. A security guard reportedly said, \"You're working for the Japs? I hope you fall flat on your ass.\"<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\">{{cite web | work=Wired | first=Chris | last=Kohler | date=October 18, 2010 | title=Oct. 18, 1985: Nintendo Entertainment System Launches | url=https://www.wired.com/2010/10/1018nintendo-nes-launches/ | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Gail Tilden said, \"I remember one woman coming up to me, and I don't know what sparked her to do this, but she came up to me and said, 'Nintendo. That's a Japanese company, right? ... I hope you ''fail''!'\". Retail staff resentful of the disastrous video game market rolled their eyes at Nintendo staff, with one manager looking at Nintendo's inventory and saying \"Somebody told me I've got to sell this crap.\" The first sale came soon and quietly, of a Deluxe Set and the 15 additional games, to a gentleman who the team later realized was employed by a Japanese competitor.<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/>\n\nSales were not high but encouraging throughout the holiday season,<ref name=\"In Their Words\"/> though sources vary on how many consoles were sold then.<ref name=\"goldberg\" /><ref name=\"Turner/Nutt 13\">{{Cite book |last=Turner |first=Benjamin |last2=Nutt |first2=Christian |date=July 2003 |chapter=Big Apple, Little N |chapter-url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index13.shtml |title=Nintendo Famicom: 20 Years of Fun! |publisher=GameSpy |page=13 |url=http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/ |accessdate=July 26, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805153333/http://archive.gamespy.com/articles/july03/famicom/index13.shtml |archive-date=August 5, 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1986, Nintendo said it had sold nearly 90,000 units in nine weeks during its late 1985 New York City test.<ref name=\"Here's how\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Steve |date=June 23, 1986 |title=Atari, Sega, and Nintendo Plan Comeback for Video Games |url=http://tnca.myrmid.com/art9.htm |department= |newspaper=HFN: The Weekly Home Furnishings Newspaper |volume= |issue= |location= |publisher= |publication-date= |page= |pages= |at= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn= |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015 |via=The Nintendo Classic Archive}}</ref><ref name=\"Pollack\">{{cite news |last1=Pollack |first1=Andrew |date= |title=Video Games, Once Zapped, In Comeback |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/27/business/video-games-once-zapped-in-comeback.html |newspaper=The New York Times |publication-date=September 27, 1986 |page=A1 |nopp=yes |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn= |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015}}</ref> In January 1986, an independent research firm commissioned by Nintendo delivered a survey of 200 NES owners, showing that the most popular given reason for buying an NES was because children wanted R.O.B. the robot{{emdash}}followed most strongly by good graphics, variety of games, and the uniqueness and newness of the NES package.<ref name=\"Here's how\">{{cite web | title=Here's how Nintendo announced the NES in North America almost 30 years ago | date=October 31, 2015 | first=Owen S. | last=Good | work=Polygon | url=https://www.polygon.com/2015/10/31/9651584/nintendo-nes-anniversary-original-launch-documents | accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref> R.O.B. is credited as a primary factor in building initial support for the NES in North America,<ref name=\"goldberg\" /><ref name=\"Here's how\"/> but the accessory itself was not well received for its entertainment value. Its original Famicom counterpart, the Famicom Robot, was already failing in Japan at the time of the North American launch.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{further|topic=R.O.B.'s key role in the NES launch|R.O.B.}}\n\nNintendo added Los Angeles as the second test market in February 1986,<ref name=\"In Their Words\">{{cite web | title=In Their Words: Remembering the Launch of the Nintendo Entertainment System | date=October 19, 2015 | first=Frank | last=Cifaldi | work=IGN | url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/19/in-their-words-remembering-the-launch-of-the-nintendo-entertainment-system | accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref> followed by Chicago and San Francisco,<ref name=\"NES launch Wired\"/> then other top 12 US markets, and finally nationwide in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vidgame.net/NINTENDO/NES1.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080413150206/http://www.vidgame.net/NINTENDO/NES1.html|title=Vidgame.net: Nintendo Entertainment System NES Toaser|archivedate=April 13, 2008|publisher=|accessdate=December 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1986\"/> Nintendo and Sega, which was similarly exporting its [[Sega Master System|Master System]] to the US, both planned to spend $15 million in the fourth quarter of 1986 to market their consoles;<ref name=takiff19860620/> later, Nintendo said it planned to spend $16 million and Sega said more than $9 million.<ref name=\"Pollack\"/> Nintendo obtained a distribution deal with toy company [[Worlds of Wonder (toy company)|Worlds of Wonder]], which leveraged its popular [[Teddy Ruxpin]] and [[Lazer Tag]] products to solicit more stores to carry the console.<ref name=\"Rise of Nintendo\">{{cite video |people=Jeremiah Black (director), Jeff Rubin, Josh Shabtai, [[Dan Ackerman]], [[Libe Goad]], Shandi Sullivan, T. J. Allard |date=July 13, 2007 |title=Play Value: The Rise of Nintendo |url=http://www.onnetworks.com/videos/play-value/rise-of-nintendo |format=[[Flash Video]] |medium=podcast |publisher=ON Networks |location= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620211908/http://www.onnetworks.com/videos/play-value/rise-of-nintendo |archivedate=June 20, 2009 |accessdate=November 2, 2015 |time= |quote= |url-status=dead }}</ref> The largest retailer [[Sears]] sold it through its Christmas catalog and the second largest retailer [[Kmart]] sold it in 700 stores.<ref name=\"Pollack\" /> Nintendo sold 1.1 million consoles in 1986, estimating that it could have sold 1.4 million if inventory had held out.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zap! Video Games Make A Comeback |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19870228&id=ChNPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4AIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7027,7957469 |department=Peach Section |newspaper=[[The Blade (Toledo)|The Blade]] |issue= |edition= |location=Toledo, Ohio |publisher= |publication-date=February 28, 1987 |agency=Scripps Howard News Service |page=P-3 |nopp=yes |at= |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn= |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015 |via=Google News Archive}}</ref> Nintendo earned $310 million in sales, out of total 1986 video game industry sales of $430 million,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dvorchak |first1=Robert |title=NEC out to dazzle Nintendo fans |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qKIbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=R04EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5459,6856521 |department=Business |newspaper=[[Times-News (Hendersonville, North Carolina)|Times-News]] |volume= |issue= |edition= |location=Hendersonville, North Carolina |publisher= |publication-date=July 30, 1989 |agency=The Associated Press |page=1D |nopp=yes |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn= |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015 |via=Google News Archive}}</ref> compared to total 1985 industry sales of $100 million.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Belson |first1=Eve |date=December 1988 |title=America's Toy Box |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=82AEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA88#v=onepage&q&f=false |department=Features |journal=[[Orange Coast (magazine)|Orange Coast]] |edition= |location=Costa Mesa, California |publisher=Emmis Communications |publication-date= |volume=14 |issue=12 |page= |pages=87\u201388, 90 |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn=0279-0483 |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 2, 2015 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nFor the nationwide launch in 1986, the NES was available in two different packages: the fully featured {{US$|249}} Deluxe Set as had been configured during the New York City launch, and a scaled-down Control Deck package which includes the console, two gamepads, and ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]''<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1986\"/>\n\nIn early 1986, Nintendo preannounced the intention to adapt the [[Famicom Disk System]] [[floppy drive]] peripheral to the NES by late 1986,<ref name=\"Computer Entertainer February 1986\">{{cite magazine | magazine=Computer Entertainer | date=February 1986 | title=Nintendo Update | url=https://nintendotimes.com/1986/05/26/computer-entertainer-nes-reviews-news/ | accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref> but the need was obviated by the proliferation of larger and faster cartridge technology, and the drive's NES launch was canceled as well as the original being discontinued in Japan.\n\n=== Europe and Oceania ===\nThe NES was also released in Europe, in stages and in a rather haphazard manner.  Most of mainland Europe (excluding Italy, Portugal, and Spain) received the system in 1986, where it was distributed by various companies.  The United Kingdom, Ireland, Italy, Spain, Portugal, Australia, and New Zealand received the system in 1987, where it was distributed by Mattel.<ref>{{cite web|title=PAL releases|url=http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/nes/euro.html|website={{!}}tsr's NES archive|accessdate=March 4, 2015}}</ref>  In Europe, the NES received a less enthusiastic response than it had elsewhere, and Nintendo lagged in market and retail penetration (though the console did see more success later on in its life). The NES did outsell the Master System in Australia, though by a much smaller margin than in North America.<ref name=\"nielsen\">{{cite web | last=Nielsen |first=Martin |date=October 8, 1997 |title=The Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) FAQ v3.0A |url=http://www.classicgaming.com/museum/faqs/nesfaq.shtml |accessdate=January 5, 2005 |via=ClassicGaming.com's Museum |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610072614/http://www.classicgaming.com/museum/faqs/nesfaq.shtml |archive-date=June 10, 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nIn [[South Korea]], the hardware was licensed to [[Hyundai Electronics]], which marketed it as the Comboy. After [[World War II]], the government of Korea  (later South Korea) imposed [[Censorship of Japanese media in South Korea|a wide ban on all Japanese \"cultural products.\"]] Until repealed in 1998, the only way Japanese products could legally enter the South Korean market was through licensing to a third-party (non-Japanese) distributor, as was the case with the Comboy and its successor, the Super Comboy, a version of the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]].<ref name=\"korea\">{{cite web|title=Breaking the Ice|url=http://web-japan.org/trends98/honbun/ntj981207.html|editors=Japan Echo Inc.|website=Trends in Japan|accessdate=19 May 2007|date=7 December 1998}}</ref>\n\n=== Soviet Union/Russia ===\nWhile the NES in its heyday was never officially released in the [[Soviet Union]], an unlicensed Chinese [[clone (computer science)|hardware clone]] named the [[Dendy (console)|Dendy]] was produced in Russia in the early [[1990s in video gaming|1990s]]. Aesthetically, it is an exact duplicate of the original Famicom, with the color scheme and labels altered. The hardwired Famicom controllers were omitted in favor of removable controllers which connect to the front of the unit using [[D-subminiature|DE-9]] serial connectors, identical to those used in the Atari 2600 and the [[Atari 8-bit family]] of computers.<ref name=\"dendy\">{{cite web | title=Dendy | work={{!}}tsr's NES archive | url=http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/odd/pirate/dendy.html | accessdate=February 12, 2006}}</ref>\nAll games sold in Russia for Dendy are [[Copyright infringement|bootleg]] copies, not the original [[Nintendo]] cartridges.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Leading the industry (1987\u20131990)==\nIn North America, the NES widely outsold its primary competitors, the [[Atari 7800]] and the Sega Master System. The successful launch of the NES positioned Nintendo to dominate the home video game market for the remainder of the 1980s. Buoyed by the success of the system, NES [[Game Pak]]s produced similar sales records.\n\nBy 1987, the NES's library had exploded with classic flagship franchise-building and best-selling hits like ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'' (1985), ''[[The Legend of Zelda (video game)|The Legend of Zelda]]'' (1986), and ''[[Metroid (video game)|Metroid]]'' (1986). At more than 40 million copies, ''Super Mario Bros.'' (1985) was the [[List of best-selling video games|highest selling video game]] in history for many years. Released in 1988 in Japan, ''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' would gross more than US$500 million, with more than 7 million copies sold in America and 4 million copies in Japan, making it the [[List of best-selling video games|most popular and fastest selling]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gottlieb |first1=Rick |date=August 2002 |url=http://www.gamecubicle.com/features-mario-units_sold_sales.htm |title=Super Mario Sales Data: Historical Units Sold Numbers for Mario Bros on NES, SNES, N64... |website=GameCubicle.com |accessdate=December 28, 2014}}</ref> standalone home video game in history.\n\nBy mid-1986, 19% (6.5 million) of Japanese households owned a Famicom;<ref name=takiff19860620>{{cite news|last=Takiff|first=Jonathan|title=Video Games Gain In Japan, Are Due For Assault On U.S.|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QBhcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MlUNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2846,1271636|accessdate=10 April 2012|via=Google News Archive|newspaper=[[The Vindicator]]|date=June 20, 1986|page=2}}</ref> one third by mid-1988.<ref name=\"keiser198806\">{{cite journal |last1=Keiser |first1=Gregg |title=One Million Sold in One Day |url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-JUn-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_097_1988_JUn#page/n7/mode/2up |department=News & Notes |journal=[[Compute!]] |edition= |location=New York City |publisher=COMPUTE! Publications |publication-date=June 1998 |volume=10 |issue= |page=7 |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn=0194-357X |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 10, 2013}}</ref> By 1990, 30% of American households had the NES, compared to 23% for all personal computers.<ref name=\"cgw199012\">{{cite journal |title=Fusion, Transfusion or Confusion: Future Directions In Computer Entertainment |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1990&pub=2&id=77 |format=[[Portable Document Format]] |department=News & Notes |journal=[[Computer Gaming World]] |edition= |location=Anaheim Hills, California |publisher=Golden Empire Publications |publication-date=December 1990 |issue=77 |pages=26, 28 |asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn=0744-6667 |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |access-date=November 10, 2013 |via=Computer Gaming World Museum}}</ref> Its popularity greatly affected the computer-game industry, with executives stating that \"Nintendo's success has destroyed the software entertainment market\" and \"there's been a much greater falling off of disk sales than anyone anticipated\". The growth in sales of the [[Commodore 64]] ended; Nintendo sold almost as many consoles in 1988 as the total number of Commodore 64s had been sold in five years. [[Trip Hawkins]] called Nintendo \"the last hurrah of the 8-bit world\",<ref name=\"ferrell198907\">{{cite journal |last1=Ferrell |first1=Keith |title=Just Kids' Play or Computer in Disguise? |url=https://archive.org/stream/1988-JUn-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_097_1988_JUn#page/n7/mode/2up |format= |department=Features |journal=[[Compute!]] |edition= |location=New York City |publisher=COMPUTE! Publications |publication-date=July 1989 |volume=11 |issue= |pages=28\u201333 |at=|asin= |doi= |doi-broken-date= |issn=0194-357X |jstor= |lccn= |oclc= |ol= |id= |archive-url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_110_1989_Jul#page/n29/mode/2up |archive-date=August 24, 2011 |access-date=November 11, 2013}}</ref> with Nintendo having completely destroyed the Commodore 64 game market as of Christmas 1988.<ref name=\"maher20161222\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.filfre.net/2016/12/a-time-of-endings-part-2-epyx/ |title=A Time of Endings, Part 2: Epyx |last=Maher |first=Jimmy |website=The Digital Antiquarian |publication-date=2016-12-22}}</ref> By 1990, the NES had reached a larger user base in the United States than any previous console, surpassing the previous record set by the Atari 2600 in 1982.<ref name=\"gazzwa\">{{cite web | author=GaZZwa | title=History of games (part 2) | url=http://www.gamingw.net/articles/74 |website=Gaming World |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20051103165622/http://www.gamingw.net/articles/74 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=November 3, 2005}}</ref> In 1990 Nintendo surpassed [[Toyota]] as Japan's most successful corporation.<ref name=\"liedholm3\">{{cite web|last1=Liedholm |first1=Marcus |last2=Liedholm |first2=Mattias |title=A new era \u2013 (1990\u201397) |website=Nintendo Land |url=http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?history/hist3.htm |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728053848/http://www.nintendoland.com/home2.htm?history%2Fhist3.htm |archive-date=July 28, 2009 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Market decline (1990\u20131995)==\n[[File:AVFamicom.jpg|thumb|right|The HVC-101 model of the Family Computer is more compact than its predecessor, and was modeled after the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Famicom]].]]\nIn the late 80s, Nintendo's dominance was addressed by newer, technologically superior consoles. In 1987, [[NEC]] and [[Hudson Soft]] released the [[TurboGrafx-16|PC Engine]], and in 1988, [[Sega]] released the [[History of video game consoles (fourth generation)|16-bit]] [[Mega Drive]]. Both were introduced in North America in 1989, where they were respectively marketed as the TurboGrafx-16 and the Genesis. Facing new competition from the PC Engine in Japan, and the Genesis in North America, Nintendo's market share began to erode. Nintendo responded in the form of the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super Famicom]] (Super Nintendo Entertainment System in North America and Europe), the Famicom's 16-bit successor, in 1990. Although Nintendo announced its intention to continue to support the Famicom alongside its newer console, the success of the newer offering began to draw even more gamers and developers from the NES, whose decline accelerated. Nintendo did continue support of the NES for about three years after the September 1991 release of the Super NES, with the NES's final [[First-party developer|first-party]] games being ''[[Zoda's Revenge: StarTropics II]]'' and ''[[Wario's Woods]]''.\n\nA revised Famicom (HVC-101 model) was released in Japan in 1993. It takes some design cues from the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]]. The HVC-101 model replaces the original HVC-001 model's [[RF modulator]] with [[RCA connector|RCA]] [[composite video|composite audio/video]] output, eliminates the hardwired controllers, and features a more compact case design. Retailing for \u00a54,800 to \u00a57,200 (equivalent to approximately $42 to $60 USD), the HVC-101 model remained in production for almost a decade before being finally discontinued in 2003.<ref name=\"avfami\">{{cite web |title=AV Family Computer |website={{!}}tsr's NES archive | url=http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/fc/avfami.html |accessdate=February 12, 2006}}</ref> The case design of the AV Famicom was adopted for a subsequent North American rerelease of the NES. The [[Nintendo Entertainment System (redesigned model)|NES-101 model]] differs from the Japanese HVC-101 model in that it omits the RCA composite output connectors of the original NES-001 model, and sports only RF output capabilities.<ref name=\"nes2\">{{cite web |title=Nintendo Entertainment System 2 |website=Vidgame.net |url=http://www.vidgame.net/NINTENDO/NES2.html |accessdate=February 12, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080202132819/http://www.vidgame.net/NINTENDO/NES2.html |archive-date=February 2, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[ASCII Entertainment]] reported in early 1993 that stores still offered 100 NES games, compared to 100 on shelves for Genesis and 50 for SNES.<ref name=\"wilson199306\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1993&pub=2&id=107|title=The Software Publishing Association Spring Symposium 1993|last=Wilson|first=Johnny L.|date=June 1993|work=Computer Gaming World|accessdate=July 7, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702235945/http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1993&pub=2&id=107|archivedate=July 2, 2014|url-status=live|page=96}}</ref> After a full decade of production, the NES was formally discontinued in the U.S. in 1995.<ref name=\"nielsen\" /> By the end of its run, more than 60 million NES units had been sold throughout the world.<ref name=\"sales\">{{cite web |title={{!}} Nintendo - Corporate Information {{!}} Company History |website=Nintendo.com |url=https://www.nintendo.com/corp/history.jsp |accessdate=November 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discontinuation and emulation (1995\u2013present)==\n{{refimprove section |date=December 2014}}\n[[File:Nesticle.jpg|thumb|Bloodlust Software's NESticle]]\nThe NES's market presence declined from 1991 to 1995, with the Sega Genesis and Nintendo's own Super NES gaining market share, with next-generation [[CD-ROM]]-based systems forthcoming. Even though the NES was discontinued in North America in 1995, many millions of cartridges for the system existed. The secondhand market of video rental stores, thrift stores, yard sales, flea markets, and games repackaged by Game Time Inc. / Game Trader Inc. and sold at retail stores such as [[K-Mart]], was burgeoning. Many people began to rediscover the NES around this time, and by 1997, many older NES games were becoming popular with collectors.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nAt the same time, [[computer programmer]]s began to develop [[Console emulator|emulators]] capable of reproducing the internal workings of the NES on modern personal computers. When paired with a [[ROM image]] (a [[bit]]-for-bit copy of a NES cartridge's program code), the games can be played on a computer. Emulators also come with a variety of built-in functions that change the gaming experience, such as [[Saved game|save states]] which allow the player to save and resume progress at an exact spot in the game.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nNintendo did not respond positively to these developments and became one of the most vocal opponents of ROM image trading. Nintendo and its supporters claim that such trading represents blatant [[Copyright infringement of software|software piracy]].<ref name=\"legalfaq\">{{cite web |title={{!}} Nintendo - Corporate Information {{!}} Legal Information (Copyrights, Emulators, ROMs, etc.) |website=Nintendo.com |url=https://www.nintendo.com/corp/legal.jsp |accessdate=December 28, 2014}}</ref> Proponents of ROM image trading argue that emulation preserves many classic games for future generations, outside of their more fragile cartridge formats.<ref name=\"pettus\">{{citation |last=Pettus |first=Sam |date=10 March 2000 |title=Emulation: Right or Wrong? |url=http://www.worldofspectrum.org/EmuFAQ2000/ |chapter=Module One: The Emulator {{!}} Part 1 - The Basis for Emulation |chapter-url=http://www.worldofspectrum.org/EmuFAQ2000/EmuFAQ_M1P1.htm |edition=Final |accessdate=November 2, 2015 |via=[http://www.worldofspectrum.org/ World of Spectrum]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Nintendo announced plans to make classic NES titles available on the [[Virtual Console]] download service for the [[Wii]] console, which is based on their own emulation technology. Initial titles released included ''[[Mario Bros.]]'', ''[[The Legend of Zelda (1986 video game)|The Legend of Zelda]]'' and ''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]'',<ref name=\"uswiivirtualconsole\">{{cite web | title=IGN: Wii: 62 Games in First Five Weeks | work=IGN Wii | url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/742/742962p1.html | accessdate=November 3, 2006 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/618x13OvE?url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/742/742962p1.html | archive-date=August 23, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref> with blockbuster titles such as ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', ''[[Mike Tyson's Punch-Out!!|Punch-Out!!]]'' and ''[[Metroid]]'' appearing in the following months.<ref>{{cite web | title=Nintendo: Virtual Console | work=Nintendo | url=http://wii.nintendo.com/virtualconsole.jsp | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012013404/http://wii.nintendo.com/virtualconsole.jsp | archivedate=October 12, 2007| accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Nintendo Co., Ltd. announced that it would no longer repair Famicom systems, due to an increasing shortage of the necessary parts.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nintendo's classic Famicom faces end of road |url=http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jAJfrC1k8lDKLOCGJu4VonjOYxBg |agency=[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] |date=October 31, 2007 |accessdate=November 9, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071105193128/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jAJfrC1k8lDKLOCGJu4VonjOYxBg |archive-date=November 5, 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Third generation of video game consoles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Nintendo Entertainment System}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Nintendo Entertainment System}}\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment System]]\n[[Category:History of video games|Nintendo Entertainment System]]\n", "name_user": "Ylee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLeading the industry (1987\u20131990):Reference edited withProveItCorrection", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Nintendo_Entertainment_System"}
{"title_page": "Safran Ardiden", "text_new": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n |name = Ardiden\n |image =Turbomeca Ardiden P1220827.jpg\n |caption = \n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Engine\n |type=[[Turboshaft]]\n |manufacturer= [[Safran Helicopter Engines]]\n |national origin=France\n |first run={{Avyear|2005}}<ref name=Flight11oct2005/>\n |major applications=[[HAL Dhruv]]\n |number built = 250 by 2018<ref name=SafranArdiden/>\n |program cost = \n |unit cost = $500,000 (projected in 2002)<ref name=Flight2jul2002/>\n |developed from = [[Turbomeca TM 333]]\n |developed into = \n |variants with their own articles =\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Safran Ardiden''' is a {{cvt|1,400-2,000|hp}} [[turboshaft]] designed and produced by [[Safran Helicopter Engines]] for {{cvt|5-8|t|lb}} single and twin-engine [[helicopter]]s.\n<!--Development-->\nLaunched in 2003 as a more powerful [[Turbomeca TM 333|TM 333]], it first ran in 2005 and was introduced in 2007.\n<!--applications-->\nThe Ardiden 1 ''Shakti'' powers the Indian [[HAL Dhruv]], [[HAL Light Combat Helicopter|Light Combat Helicopter]] and [[HAL Light Utility Helicopter|Light Utility Helicopter ]] while the more powerful Ardiden 3 powers the [[Avicopter AC352]] and [[Kamov Ka-62]].\n\n==Development==\n\nIn 1961, [[Turbomeca]] granted [[Hindustan Aeronautics]] (HAL) a manufacturing license for the [[Turbomeca Artouste|Artouste]] turboshaft engine to equip the Indian [[Alouette III]] Chetak and [[Alouette II]] Cheetah helicopters.\n\nBy September 2000, HAL had contracted with Turbomeca to develop a more powerful version of the [[HAL Advanced Light Helicopter|LAH]]'s [[Turbomeca TM 333|TM 333]]2B2, from {{cvt|747 to 800|kW}}.<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://archive.aviationweek.com/issue/20000904#!&pid=40 |title= Turbomeca buy gives Snecma a foothold in turboshaft market |magazine= Aviation Week |page= 30 |date= Sep 4, 2000 |url-access= subscription}}</ref>\nBy January 2002, Turbomeca had begun developing the {{cvt|1,200|hp}} Ardiden TM3332C2 for {{cvt|5-6|t|lb}} helicopters, launched at the [[Paris Air Show]] for the LAH as the ''Shakti'', co-developed and assembled by HAL, as the US lifted [[Pokhran-II|India's 1998 nuclear tests]] sanctions.<!--<ref name=AvWeek7jan2002>-->\nThe TM3332B2 first two axial stages were replaced by a [[centrifugal compressor]], and the power [[turbine]] went from one to two stages, while the two channel [[FADEC]] came from the TM3332E.<!--<ref name=AvWeek7jan2002>-->\nThen expected to enter service in 2005, its estimated market was 1,500 engines over the first 15 years.<ref name=AvWeek7jan2002>{{cite magazine |url= http://archive.aviationweek.com/issue/20020107#!&pid=30 |title= New Turbomeca engine to power India's LAH |magazine= Aviation Week |page= 30 |date= Jan 7, 2002 |url-access= subscription}}</ref>\n\nBy July 2002, Turbomeca was ready to launch the 900 kW (1,200 hp) engine development with HAL for 11% for the ALH, then renamed Dhruv.<!--<ref name=Flight2jul2002>-->\nThe TM333 was derated from {{cvt|800 to 765|kW}} for the Dhruv, and the Ardiden 1H ''Shakti'' would be derated from {{cvt|1,070 to 900|kW}}.\nThe Ardiden 1A was designed to for the [[Eurocopter EC155]]HP+, and the Ardiden 2K for the [[Agusta-Bell AB.139]].<!--<ref name=Flight2jul2002>-->\nIt would slot between the {{cvt|485-740|kW}} [[Turbomeca Arriel|Arriel]] and the {{cvt|1,240-1,565|kW}} [[Turbomeca Makila|Makila]] for 5-6 t (11,000-13,250lb) medium twins.\nAt $500,000, it would be 40% cheaper than 900kW competitors like the Honeywell/Rolls-Royce [[LHTEC CTS800]] and the MTU/Turbomeca/R-R [[MTR390]].<!--<ref name=Flight2jul2002>-->\nThe first test run was then expected in early 2004, flight-testing by the end of the same year, certification by the end of 2005 and\nentry into service by 2006.<ref name=Flight2jul2002>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/2002/2002%20-%201919.html |title= Turbomeca set to launch Ardiden |date= 2 July 2002 |magazine= Flight International }}</ref>\nIt was launched in February 2003 at the Aero India show with a large order from HAL, to be used in 6-6.5 t (13,200-14,300lb) helicopters.<!--<ref name=Flight11feb2003>-->\nHAL was to supply one-tenth of its components.<ref name=Flight11feb2003>{{cite magazine |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/2003/2003%20-%200311.html |title= Turbomeca and HAL strengthen ties |date= 11 Feb 2003 |magazine= Flight International }}</ref>\n\nBy October 2005, Turbomeca ran the first example in [[Tarbes]], planning a July 2006 first flight.<!--<ref name=Flight11oct2005>-->\nHAL has an 11% stake in development and 21% of the manufacture: the gearbox, power turbine and part of the {{abbr|HP|high-pressure}} compressor.<!--<ref name=Flight11oct2005>-->\nThe design include the [[single-crystal]] HP turbine blades and new [[Thermal barrier coating|ceramic coating]]s to run without cooling, for 20% of growth potential.<ref name=Flight11oct2005>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/ardiden-has-first-test-run-202077/ |title= Ardiden has first test run |date= 11 Oct 2005 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\nDeveloped by India for 19%, the ''Shakti'' made its first test flight on the Dhruv on 16 August 2007.<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928095958/http://www.hal-india.com/dhruv-shakti.asp |publisher= HAL |title= Dhruvs with Shakti engine and weapons make maiden flight |date= 16 Aug 2007}}</ref> By late 2007, HAL started fitting the ''Shakti'' for Dhruvs produced from then.\n\nThe Ardiden 3G was certified in June 2017 and by 2018, 250 Ardiden 1 were in service.<ref name=SafranArdiden/>\nBy September 2019, the Ardiden 1 engines had completed 200,000 flying hours, and the Ardiden 3C/3G had completed over 10,000 hours of tests.<ref name=AirCosmos25sep2019/>\n\n=== Turboprop version ===\n\nBy April 2019, Safran was considering a [[turboprop]] version of the Ardiden to compete with the [[Pratt & Whitney Canada PT6]] and [[General Electric Catalyst]], based on its Tech-TP demonstrator, part of the EU's [[Clean Sky]] 2 programme, for first ground runs in the coming months.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/safran-eyes-turboprop-variant-of-ardiden-3-helicopte-457765/ |title= Safran eyes turboprop variant of Ardiden 3 helicopter engine |date= 29 Apr 2019 |author= Dominic Perry |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\nThe first ground run happened on 12 June in [[Tarnos]]; the complete propulsion system include the [[nacelle]], [[air intake]] and [[Propeller (aeronautics)|propeller]] while the [[Accessory drive|accessory gearbox]] and [[Variable-pitch propeller|propeller controller]] include more electric technologies.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/paris-safran-runs-tech-tp-demonstrator-for-first-ti-458988/ |title= Safran runs Tech TP demonstrator for first time |date= 18 June 2019 |author= Dominic Perry |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\nIt could be used for a future European [[UAV]], in cooperation with [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] Luftfahrttechnik for the gearbox and [[MT-Propeller]] for the propeller.<!--ref name=AirCosmos25sep2019-->\nThe FADEC would manage both power and propeller pitch for operation up to 13,716 meters / 45,000 ft.<!--ref name=AirCosmos25sep2019-->\nThe Tech TP compact, lightweight architecture targets a 15% lower fuel consumption over current engines.<ref name=AirCosmos25sep2019>{{cite news |url= http://www.aircosmosinternational.com/safran-will-design-new-turboprop-for-a-european-uav-126789 |title= Safran will design new turboprop for a European UAV |date= 25 Sep 2019 |author= Alexandre Rocchi |work= Air & Cosmos}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe Ardiden 1 offers {{cvt|1,400|to|1,700|hp}} and the Ardiden 3 covers the {{cvt|1,700-2,000|hp}} range, for {{cvt|5|to|8|t|lb}} single and twin-engine helicopters.<ref name=SafranArdiden/>\n\nThe Ardiden has a two-stage [[centrifugal compressor]], then a reverse flow [[annular combustor]], a single stage axial gas generator [[turbine]] followed by a two-stage axial [[Free-turbine turboshaft|free turbine]] outputting its power to the front by a [[concentric]] shaft, and is controlled by a dual-channel [[digital engine electronic control unit]].<ref name=tcds1/>\n\n==Variants and applications==\n\n[[File:Salon du Bourget 20090619 247.jpg|thumb|Ardiden 1H1 for the [[HAL Dhruv]]<br/>[[HAL Light Combat Helicopter|LCH]]]]\n[[File:Turbomeca Ardiden 3G.jpg|thumb|Ardiden 3G for the [[Ka-62]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Variant !! Certification<ref name=tcds1/><ref name=tcds3/> !! Application<ref name=SafranArdiden>{{cite web |url= https://www.safran-helicopter-engines.com/fr/moteurs-dhelicopteres/1-000-2-000-shp/ardiden |title= Ardiden |publisher= Safran Helicopter Engines}}</ref>\n|-\n| Ardiden 1H || 20 December 2007 || rowspan=2 | [[HAL Dhruv]]<br/>[[HAL Light Combat Helicopter]] \n|-\n| Ardiden 1H1|| 11 March 2009 \n|-\n| Ardiden 1U || || [[HAL Light Utility Helicopter]]\n|-\n| Ardiden 3G || 12 June 2017 || [[Kamov Ka-62]]\n|-\n| Ardiden 3C / WZ16 || 5 April 2018 || [[Avicopter AC352]] \n|}\n\n==Specifications==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Variant !! Ardiden 1<ref name=tcds1>{{cite web |title= Type Certificate Data Sheet EA E.037 for Ardiden 1 |url= https://www.easa.europa.eu/sites/default/files/dfu/TCDS%20EASA%20E.037%20_Ardiden%201%20series_%20issue%2005_20170126_01.pdf |date= 1 February 2017 |publisher= EASA }}</ref> !! Ardiden 3<ref name=tcds3>{{cite web |url= https://www.easa.europa.eu/sites/default/files/dfu/TCDS%20E.103_issue%2002.pdf |title= Type certificate data sheet No. E. 103 for Ardiden 3 |date= 5 April 2018 |publisher= EASA}}</ref>\n|-\n| length || {{cvt|1250|mm}} || {{cvt|1244-1285.4|mm}}\n|-\n| height \u00d7 width || {{cvt|694*519|mm}} || {{cvt|648*640-655.9|mm}}\n|-\n| weight || {{cvt|205|kg}} || {{cvt|215-226.6|kg}}\n|-\n| compressor || colspan=2 | 2 centrifugal stages\n|-\n| combustor || colspan=2 | reverse flow \n|-\n| turbine || colspan=2 | 1 HP stage, 2 power stages\n|-\n| T/O power || {{cvt|938-1032|kW}} || {{cvt|1177-968|kW}}\n|-\n| power/weight || {{cvt|{{#expr:938/205round2}}|-|{{#expr:1032/205round2}}|kW/kg}} || {{cvt|{{#expr:1177/215round2}}-{{#expr:968/226.6round2}}|kW/kg}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n<!-- first, the related articles that do not fit the specific entries: -->\n|see also=\n\n<!-- designs which were developed into or from this aircraft or engine: -->\n|related=\n* [[Turbomeca TM 333]]\n\n<!-- relevant lists that this aircraft appears in: -->\n|lists=\n*[[List of aircraft engines]]\n\n<!-- For aircraft engine articles.  Engines that are of similar to this design: -->\n|similar engines=\n* [[HAL HTSE-1200]]\n* [[LHTEC CTS800]]\n* [[MTR390]]\n* [[Pratt & Whitney Canada PT6]]\n* [[Safran Arrano]]\n\n\n<!-- See [[WP:Air/PC]] for more explanation of these fields. -->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Turbomeca Ardiden}}\n* {{official website|https://www.safran-helicopter-engines.com/fr/moteurs-dhelicopteres/1-000-2-000-shp/ardiden}}\n\n{{Turbomeca aeroengines}}{{Hindustan Aeronautics Limited}}\n{{Joint development aeroengines}}\n{{aeroengine-specs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Safran Ardiden}}\n[[Category:Turbomeca aircraft engines|Ardiden]]\n[[Category:2000s turboshaft engines]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n |name = Ardiden\n |image =Turbomeca Ardiden P1220827.jpg\n |caption = \n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Engine\n |type=[[Turboshaft]]\n |manufacturer= [[Safran Helicopter Engines]]\n |national origin=France\n |first run={{Avyear|2005}}<ref name=Flight11oct2005/>\n |major applications=[[HAL Dhruv]]\n |number built = 250 by 2018<ref name=SafranArdiden/>\n |program cost = \n |unit cost = $500,000 (projected in 2002)<ref name=Flight2jul2002/>\n |developed from = [[Turbomeca TM 333]]\n |developed into = \n |variants with their own articles =\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''Safran Ardiden''' is a {{cvt|1,400-2,000|hp}} [[turboshaft]] designed and produced by [[Safran Helicopter Engines]] for {{cvt|5-8|t|lb}} single and twin-engine [[helicopter]]s.\n<!--Development-->\nLaunched in 2003 as a more powerful [[Turbomeca TM 333|TM 333]], it first ran in 2005 and was introduced in 2007.\n<!--applications-->\nThe Ardiden 1 ''Shakti'' powers the Indian [[HAL Dhruv]], [[HAL Light Combat Helicopter|Light Combat Helicopter]] and [[HAL Light Utility Helicopter|Light Utility Helicopter ]] while the more powerful Ardiden 3 powers the [[Avicopter AC352]] and [[Kamov Ka-62]].\n\n==Development==\n\nIn 1961, [[Turbomeca]] granted [[Hindustan Aeronautics]] (HAL) a manufacturing license for the [[Turbomeca Artouste|Artouste]] turboshaft engine to equip the Indian [[Alouette III]] Chetak and [[Alouette II]] Cheetah helicopters.\n\nBy September 2000, HAL had contracted with Turbomeca to develop a more powerful version of the [[HAL Advanced Light Helicopter|LAH]]'s [[Turbomeca TM 333|TM 333]]2B2, from {{cvt|747 to 800|kW}}.<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://archive.aviationweek.com/issue/20000904#!&pid=40 |title= Turbomeca buy gives Snecma a foothold in turboshaft market |magazine= Aviation Week |page= 30 |date= Sep 4, 2000 |url-access= subscription}}</ref>\nBy January 2002, Turbomeca had begun developing the {{cvt|1,200|hp}} Ardiden TM3332C2 for {{cvt|5-6|t|lb}} helicopters, launched at the [[Paris Air Show]] for the LAH as the ''Shakti'', co-developed and assembled by HAL, as the US lifted [[Pokhran-II|India's 1998 nuclear tests]] sanctions.<!--<ref name=AvWeek7jan2002>-->\nThe TM3332B2 first two axial stages were replaced by a [[centrifugal compressor]], and the power [[turbine]] went from one to two stages, while the two channel [[FADEC]] came from the TM3332E.<!--<ref name=AvWeek7jan2002>-->\nThen expected to enter service in 2005, its estimated market was 1,500 engines over the first 15 years.<ref name=AvWeek7jan2002>{{cite magazine |url= http://archive.aviationweek.com/issue/20020107#!&pid=30 |title= New Turbomeca engine to power India's LAH |magazine= Aviation Week |page= 30 |date= Jan 7, 2002 |url-access= subscription}}</ref>\n\nBy July 2002, Turbomeca was ready to launch the 900 kW (1,200 hp) engine development with HAL for 11% for the ALH, then renamed Dhruv.<!--<ref name=Flight2jul2002>-->\nThe TM333 was derated from {{cvt|800 to 765|kW}} for the Dhruv, and the Ardiden 1H ''Shakti'' would be derated from {{cvt|1,070 to 900|kW}}.\nThe Ardiden 1A was designed to for the [[Eurocopter EC155]]HP+, and the Ardiden 2K for the [[Agusta-Bell AB.139]].<!--<ref name=Flight2jul2002>-->\nIt would slot between the {{cvt|485-740|kW}} [[Turbomeca Arriel|Arriel]] and the {{cvt|1,240-1,565|kW}} [[Turbomeca Makila|Makila]] for 5-6 t (11,000-13,250lb) medium twins.\nAt $500,000, it would be 40% cheaper than 900kW competitors like the Honeywell/Rolls-Royce [[LHTEC CTS800]] and the MTU/Turbomeca/R-R [[MTR390]].<!--<ref name=Flight2jul2002>-->\nThe first test run was then expected in early 2004, flight-testing by the end of the same year, certification by the end of 2005 and\nentry into service by 2006.<ref name=Flight2jul2002>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/2002/2002%20-%201919.html |title= Turbomeca set to launch Ardiden |date= 2 July 2002 |magazine= Flight International }}</ref>\nIt was launched in February 2003 at the Aero India show with a large order from HAL, to be used in 6-6.5 t (13,200-14,300lb) helicopters.<!--<ref name=Flight11feb2003>-->\nHAL was to supply one-tenth of its components.<ref name=Flight11feb2003>{{cite magazine |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/2003/2003%20-%200311.html |title= Turbomeca and HAL strengthen ties |date= 11 Feb 2003 |magazine= Flight International }}</ref>\n\nBy October 2005, Turbomeca ran the first example in [[Tarbes]], planning a July 2006 first flight.<!--<ref name=Flight11oct2005>-->\nHAL has an 11% stake in development and 21% of the manufacture: the gearbox, power turbine and part of the {{abbr|HP|high-pressure}} compressor.<!--<ref name=Flight11oct2005>-->\nThe design include the [[single-crystal]] HP turbine blades and new [[Thermal barrier coating|ceramic coating]]s to run without cooling, for 20% of growth potential.<ref name=Flight11oct2005>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/ardiden-has-first-test-run-202077/ |title= Ardiden has first test run |date= 11 Oct 2005 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\nDeveloped by India for 19%, the ''Shakti'' made its first test flight on the Dhruv on 16 August 2007.<ref>{{cite press release |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928095958/http://www.hal-india.com/dhruv-shakti.asp |publisher= HAL |title= Dhruvs with Shakti engine and weapons make maiden flight |date= 16 Aug 2007}}</ref> By late 2007, HAL started fitting the ''Shakti'' for Dhruvs produced from then.\n\nThe Ardiden 3G was certified in June 2017 and by 2018, 250 Ardiden 1 were in service.<ref name=SafranArdiden/>\nBy September 2019, the Ardiden 1 engines had completed 200,000 flying hours, and the Ardiden 3C/3G had completed over 10,000 hours of tests.<ref name=AirCosmos25sep2019/>\n\n=== Turboprop version ===\n\nBy April 2019, Safran was considering a [[turboprop]] version of the Ardiden to compete with the [[Pratt & Whitney Canada PT6]] and [[General Electric Catalyst]], based on its Tech-TP demonstrator, part of the EU's [[Clean Sky]] 2 programme, for first ground runs in the coming months.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/safran-eyes-turboprop-variant-of-ardiden-3-helicopte-457765/ |title= Safran eyes turboprop variant of Ardiden 3 helicopter engine |date= 29 Apr 2019 |author= Dominic Perry |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\nThe first ground run happened on 12 June in [[Tarnos]]; the complete propulsion system include the [[nacelle]], [[air intake]] and [[Propeller (aeronautics)|propeller]] while the [[Accessory drive|accessory gearbox]] and [[Variable-pitch propeller|propeller controller]] include more electric technologies.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/paris-safran-runs-tech-tp-demonstrator-for-first-ti-458988/ |title= Safran runs Tech TP demonstrator for first time |date= 18 June 2019 |author= Dominic Perry |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\nIt could be used for a future European [[UAV]], in cooperation with [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] Luftfahrttechnik for the gearbox and [[MT-Propeller]] for the propeller.<!--ref name=AirCosmos25sep2019-->\nThe FADEC would manage both power and propeller pitch for operation up to 13,716 meters / 45,000 ft.<!--ref name=AirCosmos25sep2019-->\nThe Tech TP compact, lightweight architecture targets a 15% lower fuel consumption over current engines.<ref name=AirCosmos25sep2019>{{cite news |url= http://www.aircosmosinternational.com/safran-will-design-new-turboprop-for-a-european-uav-126789 |title= Safran will design new turboprop for a European UAV |date= 25 Sep 2019 |author= Alexandre Rocchi |work= Air & Cosmos}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe Ardiden 1 offers {{cvt|1,400|to|1,700|hp}} and the Ardiden 3 covers the {{cvt|1,700-2,000|hp}} range, for {{cvt|5|to|8|t|lb}} single and twin-engine helicopters.<ref name=SafranArdiden/>\n\nThe Ardiden has a two-stage [[centrifugal compressor]], then a reverse flow [[annular combustor]], a single stage axial gas generator [[turbine]] followed by a two-stage axial [[Free-turbine turboshaft|free turbine]] outputting its power to the front by a [[concentric]] shaft, and is controlled by a dual-channel [[digital engine electronic control unit]].<ref name=tcds1/>\n\n==Variants and applications==\n\n[[File:Salon du Bourget 20090619 247.jpg|thumb|Ardiden 1H1 for the [[HAL Dhruv]]<br/>[[HAL Light Combat Helicopter|LCH]]]]\n[[File:Turbomeca Ardiden 3G.jpg|thumb|Ardiden 3G for the [[Ka-62]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Variant !! Certification<ref name=tcds1/><ref name=tcds3/> !! Application<ref name=SafranArdiden>{{cite web |url= https://www.safran-helicopter-engines.com/fr/moteurs-dhelicopteres/1-000-2-000-shp/ardiden |title= Ardiden |publisher= Safran Helicopter Engines}}</ref>\n|-\n| Ardiden 1H || 20 December 2007 || rowspan=2 | [[HAL Dhruv]]<br/>[[HAL Light Combat Helicopter]] \n|-\n| Ardiden 1H1|| 11 March 2009 \n|-\n| Ardiden 1U || || [[HAL Light Utility Helicopter]]\n|-\n| Ardiden 3G || 12 June 2017 || [[Kamov Ka-62]]\n|-\n| Ardiden 3C / WZ16 || 5 April 2018 || [[Avicopter AC352]] \n|}\n\n==Specifications==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Variant !! Ardiden 1<ref name=tcds1>{{cite web |title= Type Certificate Data Sheet EA E.037 for Ardiden 1 |url= https://www.easa.europa.eu/sites/default/files/dfu/TCDS%20EASA%20E.037%20_Ardiden%201%20series_%20issue%2005_20170126_01.pdf |date= 1 February 2017 |publisher= EASA }}</ref> !! Ardiden 3<ref name=tcds3>{{cite web |url= https://www.easa.europa.eu/sites/default/files/dfu/TCDS%20E.103_issue%2002.pdf |title= Type certificate data sheet No. E. 103 for Ardiden 3 |date= 5 April 2018 |publisher= EASA}}</ref>\n|-\n| length || {{cvt|1250|mm}} || {{cvt|1244-1285.4|mm}}\n|-\n| height \u00d7 width || {{cvt|694*519|mm}} || {{cvt|648*640-655.9|mm}}\n|-\n| weight || {{cvt|205|kg}} || {{cvt|215-226.6|kg}}\n|-\n| compressor || colspan=2 | 2 centrifugal stages\n|-\n| combustor || colspan=2 | reverse flow \n|-\n| turbine || colspan=2 | 1 HP stage, 2 power stages\n|-\n| T/O power || {{cvt|938-1032|kW}} || {{cvt|1177-968|kW}}\n|-\n| power/weight || {{cvt|{{#expr:938/205round2}}|-|{{#expr:1032/205round2}}|kW/kg}} || {{cvt|{{#expr:1177/215round2}}-{{#expr:968/226.6round2}}|kW/kg}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n<!-- first, the related articles that do not fit the specific entries: -->\n|see also=\n\n<!-- designs which were developed into or from this aircraft or engine: -->\n|related=\n* [[Turbomeca TM 333]]\n\n<!-- relevant lists that this aircraft appears in: -->\n|lists=\n*[[List of aircraft engines]]\n\n<!-- For aircraft engine articles.  Engines that are of similar to this design: -->\n|similar engines=\n* [[LHTEC CTS800]]\n* [[MTR390]]\n* [[Pratt & Whitney Canada PT6]]\n* [[Safran Arrano]]\n\n<!-- See [[WP:Air/PC]] for more explanation of these fields. -->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Turbomeca Ardiden}}\n* {{official website|https://www.safran-helicopter-engines.com/fr/moteurs-dhelicopteres/1-000-2-000-shp/ardiden}}\n\n{{Turbomeca aeroengines}}{{Hindustan Aeronautics Limited}}\n{{Joint development aeroengines}}\n{{aeroengine-specs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Safran Ardiden}}\n[[Category:Turbomeca aircraft engines|Ardiden]]\n[[Category:2000s turboshaft engines]]\n", "name_user": "Shashpant", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Safran_Ardiden"}
{"title_page": "Colombo International School", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Colombo International School\n| image = Colombo Int School Crest.png\n| image_size = \n| logo =\n| founder = [[Elizabeth Moir]]\n| founded = 1982\n| ratio = ~ 1345:64\n| grades = Playgroup to Year 13\n| gender= Co-educational\n| type= Independent day-school\n| enrollment= 1578\n| age range=3 to 19\n| principal = Mr. Chapa wishes he was (since he joined school)\n| streetaddress = 28, Gampaha, Gampaha 7, Sri Lanka \n| country\t = Sri Lanka\n| language     = [[English language|English]], [[French Language|French]], [[German Language|German]]\n| website\t = {{url|cis.lk}}\n}}\n\n'''Colombo International School''' is a co-educational private school in [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]]. There are 1400 enrolled students from 30 countries, ranging from 3 to  19 years (from Playgroup to Year 13) in the Infant, Junior and Secondary sections. \n\n==History==\n\nThe school was established in 1982 by [[Elizabeth Moir]] as an English-language school based on a British curriculum, open to both  Sri Lankan and foreign students. The School has since been based on the [[Edexcel London Examinations]] curriculum until in 1998 it changed to the [[Edexcel]] [[General Certificate of Education|GCE]] and [[GCSE]] curriculum and then to the [[Edexcel]] [[International Advanced Levels|IAL]] and [[IGCSE]] in 2014.\n\nIn 1993, the new Chairman, Mr. Armyne Weerasinghe<ref>{{cite news|author=Marianne David |url=http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20050227/business.htm |title=Another first by Mount Lavinia Hotel |publisher=The Sunday Leader Online |date=27 February 2005 |volume = 11 |issue = 33 |accessdate=2014-02-18 |quote=Chairman, Sri Lanka Standards Institution, Armyne Wirasinha [..]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Irangika Range |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2004/02/13/bus05.html |title=Lanka Salt awarded ISO 9001:2000 certificate |publisher=Online edition of Daily News - Business |date=2004-02-13 |accessdate=2014-02-18 |quote=SLSI Chairman Armyne Wirasinha[..] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018035217/http://www.dailynews.lk/2004/02/13/bus05.html |archive-date=2012-10-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/04/28/bus05.html |title=Sri Lanka links up with World Bank for distance education |publisher=Online edition of Sunday Observer - Business |date=2002-04-28 |accessdate=2014-02-18 |quote=DLC Chairman Armyne Wirasinha[..] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015050504/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2002/04/28/bus05.html |archive-date=2012-10-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> <!-- Note: these references do not establish a connection to the school, merely verify his existence. -->initiated a development and expansion programme. In 1998, a branch,  '''CIS Kandy''' was opened in [[Mawilmada]].\n\nThe school has expanded over the last 37 years to reach the present enrollment of approximately 1800 students from 30 countries. There are now about 120 students in each year group attending the school.\n\n== Campus ==\n\nThe school campus consists of the following facilities.\n\n*An auditorium complex with a seating capacity of 69 rawr x3 .\n*Six state of the art Information Technology for \u201cresearch\u201d .\n*Eight science labs with the latest technology.\n*Over 250 Air-conditioned and non air-conditioned classrooms. \n*Multiple study rooms.\n*Furry Cat Girls.\n*Multiple Multimedia rooms.\n*A 30,000 sq.ft Senior Library.\n*A University Guidance Center.\n*A University Applications Processing Unit. ([[UCAS]] office).\n*Adult play-area.\n*Dope auditorium.\n*Two swimming pools (One indoor and the other outdoor).\n*An outdoor Basketball court.\n*[http://www.espncricinfo.com/srilanka/content/ground/747893.html MCA Cricket Grounds] hired for Cricket and Athletic practices.\n*Students smoking corner. (The door past the water fountain on the bottom floor of the senior building)\n\n\n== Sports ==\n;Basketball:The school's basketball team has consistently been in the top division of the school's league. The school's court is used as a venue for many orgies.<ref>[http://www.thepapare.com/inter-international-basketball-bsc-and-cis-girls-book-places-in-quarter-finals/  Inter-International Basketball: BSC and CIS Girls book places in quarter-finals]</ref>\n\n;Tennis:CIS has produced numerous national tennis players and players who have also gone on to represent Sri Lanka at an international level, namely Alex Fairbanks, Joshua Jayaratne and Viranka Fernando. Jayaratne also represented Sri Lanka generously in competitive orgies.\n\n== Scandals ==\n<br />\n\n*A student whose name has been withheld, alias Barberr was caught eating a table.\n*Emal Gunasekara once threatened a student by shouting \"Do you know who my father is?\".\n*A student alias 'Kiri Putha' was caught dating underage girls in school.\n*Sanduru, a former student, once on a 3 hour transit in Canada managed to pick up a thick accent which remains to this day.\n*\n\n\n\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{See also|Category:Alumni of Colombo International School}}\n{{Dynamic list|date=April 2019}}\n* [[Anarkalli Aakarsha Jayatilaka]], film and teledrama actress, model, member of Southern Provincial Council (2009\u2013present)\t\n* [[Gajendrakumar Ponnambalam]], Member of [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|Parliament]] - [[Jaffna Electoral District|Jaffna]] (2001-2010)\n*Natasha Nethicumara - Upcoming online gym trainer.\n*[[Sujit Sivasundaram]], Professor of World History, University of Cambridge\n*Abdul of Dehiwala-Mount Lavinia, a former student of CIS, is suspected of laundering money in Sri-Lanka. (If you need to launder your money contact him).\n*[[Jesus|Jesus H. Christ]] - Son of [[God]] (Dropped out in 20AD to start preaching)\n* [[Yanushi Dullewe Wijeyeratne]]<!--  Reference:   http://epaper.dailynews.lk/art.asp?id=2018%2F05%2F16%2Fpg07_2&pt=p&h=    --> - [[Cardiology|Cardiologist]] [[St George's Universi