 Abu Tiraas'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | |002|002='''Tuma I Kamal al-Din'''<br />{{nowrap|Naqib al-Hair}}<br />{{nowrap|Custodian of Husayn & Abbas shrines'}}<br/>{{nowrap|1423 \u2013 1442}}<br/>}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | |002|002='''Sharaf al-Din'''<br />{{nowrap|Naqib al-Hair}}<br />{{nowrap|Custodian of Husayn & Abbas shrines'}}<br/>{{nowrap|1442 \u2013 1493}}/}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | |001| | | |002| | | | | |003|001='''Yahya'''<br />{{nowrap|Naqib al-Hair}}<br />{{nowrap|Custodian of Husayn & Abbas shrines'}}<br/>{{nowrap|1493 \u2013 1536}}|002='''Tuma II'''|003='''Msaid'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | |!| | | | | |)|-|-|-|.| | | |!|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | |001| | | |002| |004| |003| |001='''Dhiya al-Din'''<br />{{nowrap|Grandfather of House Dhiya al-Din}}<br />|002='''Alam al-Din'''<br />{{nowrap|Minister of Charitable Endowments of Karbala}}<br/>{{nowrap|1573 - 1597}}<br/>|004='''Jafar'''|003='''Muhammad'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|v|-|-|-|(| | | |!| | | |!|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | |001| |005| |002| |004| |003| | |001='''Tuma III'''<br />{{nowrap|Grandfather of House Tuma}}<br />|005='''Hassan'''|002='''Jameel'''|004='''Musa'''|003='''Msaid'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |!| | | |!|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | |005| |002| |004| |003| | |005='''Kadhim'''|002='''Yunis'''<br />{{nowrap|'''(Owner of ''Maal Yunis'')'''}}|004='''Isa'''|003='''Musa'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |!| | | |!|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | |005| |002| |004| |003| | |005='''Ali'''|002='''Ali'''|004='''Hassan'''|003='''Salman'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |!| | | |!|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | |005| |002| |004| |003| | |005='''Muhammad-Amin'''<br />{{nowrap|Grandfather of House Sayyid Amin}}<br />|002='''Husayn'''|004='''Abu al-Hasan'''|003='''Mohammed-Daud'''}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |!|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | | | | |002| |004| |003| | |002='''[[Nasrallah al-Haeri|Nasrallah]]'''<br />{{nowrap|Grandfather of House Nasrallah}}<br />|004='''Ali al-Tajir'''<br />{{nowrap|Grandfather of House Tajir}}<br />|003='''Muhsin Ouj'''<br />{{nowrap|Grandfather of House Ouj}}<br />}}\n{{chart/end}}<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}<!--Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations.-->\n\n[[Category:History of Karbala]]\n[[Category:Arab dynasties]]\n[[Category:Iraqi families]]\n[[Category:Iraqi noble families]]\n", "name_user": "Sourceofgrace", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typos + info corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Faiz_Family"}
{"title_page": "Jeff Trepagnier", "text_new": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Jeff Trepagnier\n| image =\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 200\n| league = \n| team = \n| number = \n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1979|7|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]\n| high_school = [[Compton High School|Compton]] ([[Compton, California]])\n| college = [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC]] (1997\u20132001)\n| draft_year = 2001\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 35\n| draft_team = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| career_start = 2001\n| career_end   = 2013\n| years1  = {{nbay|2001|full=y}}\n| team1   = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| years2  = 2002\u20132003\n| team2   = [[Oklahoma City Blue|Asheville Altitude]]\n| years3  = {{nbay|2002|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2003|end}}\n| team3   = [[Denver Nuggets]] \n| years4  = 2004\u20132005\n| team4   = [[Basket Napoli]]\n| years5  = 2005\u20132006\n| team5   = [[\u00dclkerspor]]\n| years6  = 2006\u20132007\n| team6   = Basket Napoli\n| years7  = 2008\n| team7   = [[\u00c9lan B\u00e9arnais Pau-Orthez|Pau-Orthez]]\n| years8  = 2008\u20132009\n| team8   = [[Bakersfield Jam]]\n| years9  = 2009\n| team9   = [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]]\n| years10 = 2009\n| team10  = [[Hollywood Jammers]]\n| years11 = 2009\u20132010\n| team11  = [[Iowa Energy]]\n| years12 = 2010\u20132011\n| team12  = [[Scaligera Verona]]\n| years13 = 2012\n| team13  = [[Liga Sorocabana de Basquete|Liga Sorocabana]]\n| years14 = 2012\u20132013\n| team14  = [[Los Angeles Slam]]\n| highlights = \n'''[[EuroLeague records since the 2000\u201301 season]]'''\n* Most steals in a game\n| bbr = trepaje01\n}}\n\n'''Jeffery Trepagnier''' (born July 11, 1979) is an American former professional [[basketball]] player.\n\n==High school==\nTrepagnier played basketball at [[Compton High School]], in [[Compton, California]].\n\n==College career==\nTrepagnier played [[college basketball]] for the [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC Trojans]].  He also took second place at the 2000 [[Pacific-10 Conference|Pac-10]] Championships for the second year in a row with a [[high jump]] of 7-foot-1, tying for the fifth-best jump in USC school history.\n\n==Professional career==\nTrepagnier was a second round draft pick of the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] in the [[2001 NBA draft]]. At 6'4\", Trepagnier was considered by some scouts to be undersized for the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] [[shooting guard]] position, his natural spot. In three seasons for the Cavaliers and the [[Denver Nuggets]], Trepagnier averaged 2.8 points per game.\n\nHe spent the 2004\u201305 season for [[Serie A (basketball)|Italian]] club [[Basket Napoli|Eldo Napoli]].\nHe signed with the Knights on June 25, 2006.\n\nTrepagnier signed a contract with [[French basketball clubs in international competitions|French club]] [[\u00c9lan B\u00e9arnais Pau-Orthez]] in December 2007.\n\nIn 2009, Trepagnier was playing for the [[Iowa Energy]] of the NBA D-League.\n\nIn 2010, he joined [[Scaligera Verona]] of the Italian second league.\n\nIn 2011, he signed to play in Brazil.<ref>[http://www.atribuna.com.br/noticias.asp?idnoticia=129617&idDepartamento=2&idCategoria=0 Liga Sorocabana contrata Jeff Trepagnier, ex-atleta do Denver] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407093959/http://www.atribuna.com.br/noticias.asp?idnoticia=129617&idDepartamento=2&idCategoria=0 |date=2012-04-07 }}</ref>\n\nHe later joined the [[Los Angeles Slam]] of the ABA.<ref>[http://www.prlog.org/12054552-ubc-tv-network-broadcasts-aba-basketball-in-los-angeles-with-star-studded-line-up.html UBC-TV Network Broadcasts ABA Basketball in Los Angeles with a Star Studded Line Up]</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nBorn in [[Los Angeles]], Trepagnier is of African-American descent. <ref>[http://espn.go.com/magazine/curry_20010323.html Treat me like a fool ...] ''[[ESPN Magazine]]'', March 23, 2001</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nba.com/playerfile/jeff_trepagnier/index.html Jeff Trepagnier NBA player profile] @ NBA.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050404195406/http://www.nba.com/nbdl/players/jeff_trepagnier.html Jeff Trepagnier NBA D-League player profile] @ NBA.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090803181352/http://217.13.116.51/plantillas/jugador.jsp?id=KDU player profile] @ Euroleague.net\n*[http://195.56.77.208/player/?id=TRE-JEF-79&year=2006&team=1126 Player profile] @ Legabasket.it\n\n{{2001 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trepagnier, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Brazil]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in France]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Italy]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Turkey]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American people of Creole descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Asheville Altitude players]]\n[[Category:Bakersfield Jam players]]\n[[Category:Basket Napoli players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from California]]\n[[Category:Charlotte Bobcats expansion draft picks]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Cavaliers draft picks]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Cavaliers players]]\n[[Category:Compton High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Denver Nuggets players]]\n[[Category:\u00c9lan B\u00e9arnais players]]\n[[Category:Iowa Energy players]]\n[[Category:Rio Grande Valley Vipers players]]\n[[Category:Scaligera Basket Verona players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:\u00dclker G.S.K. basketball players]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans men's track and field athletes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Jeff Trepagnier\n| image =\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 200\n| league = \n| team = \n| number = \n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1979|7|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]]\n| high_school = [[Compton High School|Compton]] ([[Compton, California]])\n| college = [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC]] (1997\u20132001)\n| draft_year = 2001\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 35\n| draft_team = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| career_start = 2001\n| career_end   = 2013\n| years1  = {{nbay|2001|full=y}}\n| team1   = [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n| years2  = 2002\u20132003\n| team2   = [[Oklahoma City Blue|Asheville Altitude]]\n| years3  = {{nbay|2002|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2003|end}}\n| team3   = [[Denver Nuggets]] \n| years4  = 2004\u20132005\n| team4   = [[Basket Napoli]]\n| years5  = 2005\u20132006\n| team5   = [[\u00dclkerspor]]\n| years6  = 2006\u20132007\n| team6   = Basket Napoli\n| years7  = 2008\n| team7   = [[\u00c9lan B\u00e9arnais Pau-Orthez|Pau-Orthez]]\n| years8  = 2008\u20132009\n| team8   = [[Bakersfield Jam]]\n| years9  = 2009\n| team9   = [[Rio Grande Valley Vipers]]\n| years10 = 2009\n| team10  = [[Hollywood Jammers]]\n| years11 = 2009\u20132010\n| team11  = [[Iowa Energy]]\n| years12 = 2010\u20132011\n| team12  = [[Scaligera Verona]]\n| years13 = 2012\n| team13  = [[Liga Sorocabana de Basquete|Liga Sorocabana]]\n| years14 = 2012\u20132013\n| team14  = [[Los Angeles Slam]]\n| highlights = \n'''[[EuroLeague records since the 2000\u201301 season]]'''\n* Most steals in a game\n| bbr = trepaje01\n}}\n\n'''Jeffery Trepagnier''' (born July 11, 1979) is an American former professional [[basketball]] player.\n\n==High school==\nTrepagnier played basketball at [[Compton High School]], in [[Compton, California]].\n\n==College career==\nTrepagnier played [[college basketball]] for the [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC Trojans]].  He also took second place at the 2000 [[Pacific-10 Conference|Pac-10]] Championships for the second year in a row with a [[high jump]] of 7-foot-1, tying for the fifth-best jump in USC school history.\n\n==Professional career==\nTrepagnier was a second round draft pick of the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] in the [[2001 NBA draft]]. At 6'4\", Trepagnier was considered by some scouts to be undersized for the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] [[shooting guard]] position, his natural spot. In three seasons for the Cavaliers and the [[Denver Nuggets]], Trepagnier averaged 2.8 points per game.\n\nHe spent the 2004\u201305 season for [[Serie A (basketball)|Italian]] club [[Basket Napoli|Eldo Napoli]].\nHe signed with the Knights on June 25, 2006.\n\nTrepagnier signed a contract with French club [[\u00c9lan B\u00e9arnais Pau-Orthez]] in December 2007.\n\nIn 2009, Trepagnier was playing for the [[Iowa Energy]] of the NBA D-League.\n\nIn 2010, he joined [[Scaligera Verona]] of the Italian second league.\n\nIn 2011, he signed to play in Brazil.<ref>[http://www.atribuna.com.br/noticias.asp?idnoticia=129617&idDepartamento=2&idCategoria=0 Liga Sorocabana contrata Jeff Trepagnier, ex-atleta do Denver] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407093959/http://www.atribuna.com.br/noticias.asp?idnoticia=129617&idDepartamento=2&idCategoria=0 |date=2012-04-07 }}</ref>\n\nHe later joined the [[Los Angeles Slam]] of the ABA.<ref>[http://www.prlog.org/12054552-ubc-tv-network-broadcasts-aba-basketball-in-los-angeles-with-star-studded-line-up.html UBC-TV Network Broadcasts ABA Basketball in Los Angeles with a Star Studded Line Up]</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nBorn in [[Los Angeles]], Trepagnier is of African-American descent. <ref>[http://espn.go.com/magazine/curry_20010323.html Treat me like a fool ...] ''[[ESPN Magazine]]'', March 23, 2001</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nba.com/playerfile/jeff_trepagnier/index.html Jeff Trepagnier NBA player profile] @ NBA.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050404195406/http://www.nba.com/nbdl/players/jeff_trepagnier.html Jeff Trepagnier NBA D-League player profile] @ NBA.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090803181352/http://217.13.116.51/plantillas/jugador.jsp?id=KDU player profile] @ Euroleague.net\n*[http://195.56.77.208/player/?id=TRE-JEF-79&year=2006&team=1126 Player profile] @ Legabasket.it\n\n{{2001 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trepagnier, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Brazil]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in France]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Italy]]\n[[Category:American expatriate basketball people in Turkey]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American people of Creole descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Asheville Altitude players]]\n[[Category:Bakersfield Jam players]]\n[[Category:Basket Napoli players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from California]]\n[[Category:Charlotte Bobcats expansion draft picks]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Cavaliers draft picks]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Cavaliers players]]\n[[Category:Compton High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Denver Nuggets players]]\n[[Category:\u00c9lan B\u00e9arnais players]]\n[[Category:Iowa Energy players]]\n[[Category:Rio Grande Valley Vipers players]]\n[[Category:Scaligera Basket Verona players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:\u00dclker G.S.K. basketball players]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans men's track and field athletes]]\n", "name_user": "Zebuready", "label": "safe", "comment": "French club", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Trepagnier"}
{"title_page": "List of Hollyoaks spin-offs", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\nThe following is a list of late night, DVD and spin-off series of [[Channel 4]] [[soap-opera]] ''[[Hollyoaks]]''. Each has a brief summary of the plot.\n\n==Video/DVD specials==\n\n===Hollyoaks: Off on One===\nA [[VHS|video]] spin-off from 1998 which sees [[Rob Hawthorne (Hollyoaks)|Rob Hawthorne]] seek revenge against [[Kurt Benson]]. The storyline comes to a dramatic conclusion with Rob and Kurt fighting on a boat. Rob rushes at Kurt, however he moves out of the way and Rob falls into the sea, with everyone believing he is dead. Music composed and performed by Steve Wright.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Indecent Behaviour===\nA video/DVD spin-off released in 2001. [[Geri Hudson]] arrives with footballer boyfriend [[Jason Cunliffe (Hollyoaks)|Jason Cunliffe]]. In a club, [[Scott Anderson (Hollyoaks)|Scott Anderson]] begins to chat Geri up. [[Luke Morgan]] steps in to stop him taking it too far, however just as Scott and his friends are about to throw Luke into the river, Scott tells his friends that he has a better idea; Scott and his friends pull Luke's trousers down to make fun of Luke's rape from the previous year. [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]] and [[Beth Morgan (Hollyoaks)|Beth Morgan]] try to break Scott and Luke up before a fight breaks, which it does between Ben and Luke. Beth is later offered a lift by Scott, and then is raped. Music composed and performed by Steve Wright.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Late night specials==\n\n===Hollyoaks: Lost Weekend===\nFour episodes broadcast in 1999 centring on the kidnapping of [[Lucy Benson]] by Rob Hawthorne and the desperate search by [[Ruth Osborne]], [[Lewis Richardson (Hollyoaks)|Lewis Richardson]] and [[Tony Hutchinson]]. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Boys Do Barca===\nBroadcast in 2000, [[Alex Bell (Hollyoaks)|Alex Bell]], [[Max Cunningham]], [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]], [[Tony Hutchinson]], [[Luke Morgan]], [[Sam \"O.B.\" O'Brien]], [[Sol Patrick]] and [[Lewis Richardson (Hollyoaks)|Lewis Richardson]] make their way to [[Barcelona]] to celebrate [[Rory Finnigan]]'s stag party before Finn marries Tony's Mother. Tony, however, has secretly enlisted the help of [[Carol Groves]] to convince Finn not to go ahead with the marriage.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Breaking Boundaries===\nBroadcast in March 2000, the late night special involves a 90s disco at the club where [[Ruth Osborne]] discovers [[Lewis Richardson (Hollyoaks)|Lewis Richardson's]] gambling addiction. Ruth and Lewis eventually end up sleeping together, despite Ruth's marriage to [[Kurt Benson]]. Meanwhile, after a football match, [[Mark Gibbs]] beats up [[Luke Morgan]] before raping him.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Leap of Faith===\nOn 24 October 2003 late night special sees [[Ellie Mills]] try to kill herself before telling serial-killer husband [[Toby Mills|Toby]] to hand himself in to the police. Toby realises he could not live without Ellie and ends up holding her hostage on a rooftop. As Toby prepares to jump with Ellie, [[Dan Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Dan Hunter]] arrives and pushes Toby off the building, killing him.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: After Hours===\nA four-part late night series broadcast in 2004. [[Lisa Hunter]] is whisked away to Paris with a man she meets in a hotel where she worked. [[Joe Spencer (Hollyoaks)|Joe Spencer]] and his friends go on a night out that ends in disaster. Meanwhile, former character [[Matt Musgrove]] crosses over to the special.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: In Too Deep===\nIn a one off special aired on 31 May 2005, [[Steph Cunningham|Steph Dean]] is haunted by the ghost of one of [[Toby Mills]]' victims and she nearly drowns. Meanwhile, [[Lee Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Lee Hunter]] and Bombhead cause mayhem at the backstage of Steph's show.\n{{Clear}}\n\n'''Cast:'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Character\n! Actor\n|-\n| [[Bombhead]]\n| [[Lee Otway]]\n|-\n| [[Cameron Clark (Hollyoaks)|Cameron Clark]]\n| Ben Gerrard\n|-\n| [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]]\n| [[Marcus Patric]]\n|-\n| [[Craig Dean]]\n| [[Guy Burnett]]\n|-\n| [[Frankie Osborne|Frankie Dean]]\n| [[Helen Pearson]]\n|-\n| [[Steph Cunningham|Steph Dean]]\n| [[Carley Stenson]]\n|-\n| [[Lee Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Lee Hunter]]\n| [[Alex Carter (British actor)|Alex Carter]]\n|-\n| [[Lisa Hunter]]\n| [[Gemma Atkinson]]\n|-\n| [[Joe Spencer (Hollyoaks)|Joe Spencer]]\n| Matt Milburn\n|-\n| Lucy\n| [[Celena Cherry]]\n|-\n| Michelle\n| Lou Emmett\n|-\n| Simon\n| Sean Taylor\n|-\n| Vanessa\n| Lizzie Hills\n|}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Crossing the Line===\nThe late night special broadcast in 2005 sees [[Andy Holt (Hollyoaks)|Andy Holt]] spike [[Dannii Carbone]]'s drink with [[gamma-Hydroxybutyric acid|GHB]] before raping her. Andy then reveals his activities to his friend, [[Sam Owen]], who agrees to join Andy to drug and rape girls. Meanwhile, Chris tricks [[Lee Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Lee Hunter]] into sleeping with a transvestite called Aphrodite. Elsewhere, [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]] and [[Lisa Hunter]] make friends with siblings Ally and Alex.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: No Going Back===\nFollowing ''Crossing the Line'', [[Andy Holt (Hollyoaks)|Andy]] drugs [[Sophie Burton|Sophie]] and [[Mel Burton]]. He rapes Mel and leaves [[Sam Owen|Sam]] to rape Sophie, but he does not. Dannii tells [[Russ Owen]] that she was raped. He does not believe her so she attempts suicide. Mel, Sophie and [[Louise Summers]] stop her and report Andy to the police. Sam and Andy, both on the top of a cliff, are caught in a fight between themselves and Russ. Sam and Andy both fall over the cliff. Russ manages to grab the pair, however has to let one go, so lets Andy fall to his death. Meanwhile [[Rhys Ashworth]], [[Gilly Roach]], [[Jessica Harris (Hollyoaks)|Jessica Harris]] and [[Olivia Johnson]] go on a trip to a spiritrist camp.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Back from the Dead===\nIn 2006, Andy Holt returns after surviving the fall and seeks his revenge against Russ by kidnapping his sister [[Nicole Owen|Nicole]]. Sam and Russ come in to free Nicole but Andy attacks them with a metal pole and threatens to rape Nicole but then Mel bursts in and whacks him over the head with the metal pole and begins to laugh at him as she calls the police. Whilst tied up, Andy let's slip to Russ and Nicole about Sam's involvement in the rapes. Andy escapes, and  Mel chases after him and he runs into a metal spike and he starts to bleed from his mouth, he starts to talk but Mel can't understand what he says. He then dies moments later as Mel watches on. {{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: King of Hearts===\nA late night special called ''Hollyoaks: King of Hearts'' was announced in November 2010 and was broadcast on 15 December 2010 on Channel 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/news/a287673/hollyoaks-confirms-late-night-special.html |title=Hollyoaks confirms late-night special |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |first=Daniel |last=Kilkelly |accessdate=2010-11-14 |date=14 November 2010}}</ref> The episode followed events in the main series which saw [[Kathleen McQueen]] blackmailing her family. The episode features [[Rhys Ashworth]] and [[Jacqui McQueen]] attempting to cheat during a game of poker with [[Brendan Brady]] and [[Danny Houston]]. After their plan is discovered, Danny tells Jacqui she must sleep with him to save Rhys and wipe the debt they owe him. The episode was originally due to air on 16 December 2010. However, this was later changed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/scoop/a289629/schedule-change-for-hollyoaks-special.html |title=Schedule change for Hollyoaks special |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |first=Daniel |last=Kilkelly |date=24 November 2010|accessdate=2010-11-24}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Spin-off series==\n\n===Hollyoaks: Movin' On===\nA new sixteen part series. [[Tony Hutchinson]] and [[Rory Finnigan]] open their new business venture. Meanwhile, after beating [[Ruth Osborne]] up, [[Lewis Richardson (Hollyoaks)|Lewis]], racked by guilt, commits suicide. Ruth then leaves for [[London]]. Music composed and performed by Steve Wright  http://www.stevewrightcomposer.com\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Let Loose===\nA 2005 series following [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]] and [[Lisa Hunter]] as they depart Hollyoaks for a new life. Lisa and Ben's relationship is put to the test over Lisa's jealousy, however she agrees to give their relationship another go. Music composed and performed by Steve Wright  http://www.stevewrightcomposer.com\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: In the City===\n{{main|Hollyoaks: In the City}}\nLisa and Ben return to [[Liverpool]], where Lisa is set up with a modelling agency. Ben spends the pair's entire savings on a bar but is conned. Lisa delves further up the career path and Ben has an illicit affair and is involved in dodgy dealings with Burton Phillips including arson and murder. Finally, Lisa ended up accidentely shooting Ben as he tried to save her from being used in a snuff film. Ben's fate remains unknown.\n\n===Hollyoaks Later===\n{{main|Hollyoaks Later|Hollyoaks Later (series 1)}}\n2008 series following [[Niall Rafferty]] as he returns for revenge on [[Steph Cunningham]], [[Craig Dean]] and [[Tom Cunningham]], which leads to the dramatic death of Niall. Meanwhile, [[Kris Fisher|Kris]] and [[Malachy Fisher]] return to Ireland to attend their father's funeral as Malachy and [[Mercedes McQueen]] marry. [[Sarah Barnes]], [[Nancy Hayton]] and [[Zoe Carpenter]] head off on a \"girly\" road trip as the Dirty Diegos enter 'Battle of the Bands'.<ref name=\"ds\">{{ cite news | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/a134073/late-night-hollyoaks-to-get-c4-run.html | title='Late Night Hollyoaks' to get C4 run | first=Kris |last=Green | publisher=[[Digital Spy]] | date=30 October 2008 | accessdate=2008-10-30 }}</ref>\n\n{{main|Hollyoaks Later (series 2)}}\nA second series was commissioned and was broadcast in September 2009.<ref name=\"laterreturn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/07/090702.html |title=Hollyoaks Later To Return |publisher=Channel 4 |date=2 July 2009 |accessdate=2009-07-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704214849/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/07/090702.html |archivedate=4 July 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"kirkwood\">{{ cite news| url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/a153128/kirkwood-to-head-up-new-hollyoaks-later.html| title=Kirkwood to produce new Hollyoaks Later | publisher=Digital Spy |first=Kris |last=Green| date=17 April 2009 | accessdate=2009-04-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/04/090417pm.html |title=Hollyoaks Later returns! |publisher=Channel4 |date=17 April 2009 |accessdate=2009-07-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522080812/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/04/090417pm.html |archivedate=22 May 2009 }}</ref> It follows four main stories: [[Hannah Ashworth|Hannah]], [[Rhys Ashworth|Rhys]] and [[Josh Ashworth]] go off to a music festival, where they encounter a dangerous drug dealer, [[Tony Hutchinson]] marries [[Cindy Cunningham]] after several mishaps, [[McQueen family|the McQueens]] go to London for [[Theresa McQueen|Theresa's]] modelling and [[Sarah Barnes]] and [[Zoe Carpenter]] are joined by Sarah's jealous girlfriend [[Lydia Hart]] on a parachute jump which leads to Sarah's death after Lydia sabotages her parachute.\n\n{{main|Hollyoaks Later (series 3)}}\nIn April 2010, Channel 4 announced that the show would return for a third series, this time produced by Hollyoaks series producer Paul Marquess. The characters appearing included: [[Mitzeee Minniver]], [[Carl Costello]], [[Riley Costello]], [[Seth Costello]], [[Malachy Fisher]], [[Mercedes Fisher]], [[Theresa McQueen]] and [[Nancy Hayton]]. Filming took place in the summer of 2010, and in October 2010, it was revealed that the third series would begin on 25 October, and would closely interweave with the main Hollyoaks series, revolving around \"one fateful night\". UFC Fighter Michael Bisping guest starred.\n\n{{main|Hollyoaks Later (series 4)}}\nIt Was reported that a fourth series had been recommissioned due to the popularity of the last few series. Filming will take place in the summer of 2011. Characters rumoured to be involved in the storylines have included [[Mercedes McQueen]], [[Myra McQueen]], [[Michaela McQueen]], [[Texas Longford]], [[Silas Blissett]], [[Heidi Costello]], [[Riley Costello]], [[Lynsey Nolan]] and [[Mitzeee Minniver]]. New cast members include a new addition to the McQueen family played by Amy Walsh sister of Girls aloud star Kimberly Walsh and a new unnamed hunk to be played by ex-eastenders actor Chris Coghill. By early June scenes had begun filming in Ibiza with Mercedes McQueen, Myra McQueen, Michaela McQueen, [[Theresa McQueen]], [[Will Savage]], [[Rae Wilson]] and Mitzeee Minniver. Series 4 is set to be aired over the course of five nights from 5 September to 10 September 2011.\nIn the gripping final episode of the series, Rae Wilson was strangled by Silas Blissett after he heard that [[Brendan Brady]] wanted to kill her. He wanted Brendan to be arrested on suspicion of murder so that he could continue with his evil plans.\n\n===Hollyoaks Does Come Dine With Me===\n2015 Series based on the [[Channel 4]] evening show [[Come Dine With Me]]. The show aired at 7:30pm on [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] during the 20th Anniversary Week. [[Jimmy McKenna]] ([[Jack Osborne]]), [[Jessica Fox (actress)|Jessica Fox]] ([[Nancy Osborne]]), [[Kieron Richardson]] ([[Ste Hay]]), [[Kirsty Leigh Porter]] ([[Leela Lomax]]), Jessica Ellis ([[Tegan Lomax]]) and Jaqueline Boatswain ([[Simone Loveday]]) were the Hollyoaks stars that took part. \n\n'''''Ratings'''''\n*0.82\n*0.75\n*0.60\n*0.62\n*0.71\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Online spin-offs==\n\n===Hollyoaks: The Morning After the Night Before===\n{{main|Hollyoaks: The Morning After the Night Before}}\n\n[[Josh Ashworth]] heads off to party with [[Dave Colburn]] in [[Manchester]] in the on-line spin-off which features the down side to [[binge drinking]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/a159587/online-oaks-to-explore-binge-drinking.html |title=Online 'Oaks to explore binge drinking |publisher=Digital Spy|first=Kris|last=Green |date=12 June 2009|accessdate=2009-11-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/06/090608.html |title=Hollyoaks: The Morning After the Night Before |publisher=Channel 4 |date=8 June 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930203335/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/06/090608.html |archivedate=30 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Hollyoaks: Freshers===\nFreshers is a 2010 online drama following the lives of the fresher students before they begin at Hollyoaks Community College. Like ''The Morning After the Night Before'', several characters' social networking websites were created, this time using [[Facebook]]. The series featured the return of [[Lee Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Lee Hunter]], and debut of new characters [[Jamil Fadel]], [[Leanne Holiday]] and [[Doug Carter]]. It also starred [[Charlotte Lau]], [[India Longford]], [[Texas Longford]] and [[Dave Colburn]]. A return also featured [[David \"Bombhead\" Burke|Bombhead]].\n\n===Hollyoaks: Tom's Life===\nTom's finding life tough after Nancy and Darren's break up. When his plan to get them back together goes wrong he almost gives up completely... until he discovers an amazing new skill.\n\n===Hollyoaks: Access All Areas===\n\n{{col-begin}}\n\n{{col-3}}\n====Series 1====\n\n1. [[Amanda Clapham]] ([[Holly Cunningham]])<br>2. [[James Sutton (actor)|James Sutton]] ([[John Paul McQueen]]) <br>3. [[Jessica Fox (actress)|Jessica Fox]] ([[Nancy Hayton|Nancy Osborne]])<br>4. [[Jorgie Porter]] ([[Theresa McQueen]])<br>5. [[Parry Glasspool]] ([[Harry Thompson (Hollyoaks)|Harry Thompson]])<br>6. [[Jazmine Franks]] ([[Esther Bloom]])<br>7. [[Charlie Wernham]] ([[Robbie Roscoe]])<br>8. [[Anna Passey]] ([[Sienna Blake]])<br>9. Cameron Moore ([[Cameron Campbell]])<br>10. [[Tamara Wall]] ([[Grace Black]])<br>11. Fabrizo Santino ([[Ziggy Roscoe]])<br>12. [[Nikki Sanderson]] ([[Maxine Minniver]])\n\n====Series 2====\n\n1. Charlie Clapham ([[Freddie Roscoe]])<br>2. [[Stephanie Waring]] ([[Cindy Cunningham|Cindy Savage]])<br>3. [[Sophie Austin]] ([[Lindsey Butterfield|Lindsey Roscoe]])<br>4. [[Kieron Richardson]] ([[Ste Hay]])<br>5. [[Jacqueline Boatswain]] & [[Karl Collins]] ([[Simone Loveday|Simone]] & [[Louis Loveday]])<br>6. [[Daisy Wood-Davis]] ([[Kim Butterfield]])<br>7. [[Jamie Lomas]] ([[Warren Fox]])<br>8. [[Gregory Finnegan]] ([[James Nightingale (Hollyoaks)|James Nightingale]])<br>9. Richard Linnell & Kassuis Nelson ([[Alfie Nightingale]] & [[Jade Albright]])<br>10. [[Duncan James]] ([[Ryan Knight]])\n\n====Series 3====\n1. [[Kirsty-Leigh Porter]] ([[Leela Lomax]])<br>2. Duyane Boachie ([[Zack Loveday]])<br>3. Amy Conachan ([[Courtney Campbell (Hollyoaks)|Courtney Campbell]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Media Content==\n\n===Hollyoaks Highs: The Wicked Bits===\nHighlights show made in 1999 to mark Hollyoaks going three times a week.\n\n===Hollyoaks: Search for a star===\nA short series on channel 4 where hollyoaks held open auditions to cast a new character and showed the audition process\n\n===Hollyoaks: Access All Areas===\nThis 2000 documentary which features Hollyoaks cast discussing various sexual matters.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks on the Pull===\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Extreme Challenges===\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks Backstage===\nA weekly on-line documentary featuring various members of the ''Hollyoaks'' cast showing viewers behind the scenes of the show. Each 3 minute episode is shown broadcast weekly on the E4 website.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Summer's Got a Secret===\n{{Clear}}\n\n===''The Hollyoaks Music Show''===\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = The Hollyoaks Music Show\n| italic_title = no<!-- set below -->\n| language = English\n| num_episodes = 26\n| presenter = [[Rick Edwards]] <small>(2008\u20132010)</small><br /> [[Matt Littler]] <small>(2011)</small>\n| producer = Sarah Clarke\n| director = Chris Howe<br /> Dave Skinner\n| company = Conker Media<br /> [[Lime Pictures]]\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| website = http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/\n| production_website =http://www.limepictures.com/MusicShow.htm\n}}\n'''''The Hollyoaks Music Show''''' is a music television programme broadcast as part of [[T4 (Channel 4)|T4]] on [[Channel 4]]. The show began broadcasting on 17 October 2009, following a pilot episode in 2008, and features various recording artists performing and participating in the show. It is sponsored by British retailer [[Matalan]] and hosted by [[Rick Edwards]].\n\nThe series first began in 2008, when it was named ''Hollyoaks Music Special'', a one-off programme hosted by [[Rick Edwards]] and former ''Hollyoaks'' actor [[Matt Littler]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/news/a91635/hollyoaks-to-host-music-special.html |title='Hollyoaks' to host 'Music Special' |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |first=Dave |last=West |date=15 March 2008 |accessdate=2010-11-20}}</ref> Following its success, Channel 4 commissioned two series<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/news/a96807/c4-wants-hollyoaks-music-show-series.html |title=C4 wants 'Hollyoaks Music Show' series |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |first=Dave |last=West |date=15 March 2008 |accessdate=2010-11-20}}</ref> and retailer [[Matalan]] became the show's official sponsor, in order to reach the target audience of 16- to 34-year-olds. Repeats of the series have been shown on [[4Music]] since 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4music.com/article/ontv/the-hollyoaks-music-show-2010-06-05.html |title=The Hollyoaks Music Show |date=31 May 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |work=[[4Music]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205233747/http://www.4music.com/article/ontv/the-hollyoaks-music-show-2010-06-05.html |archivedate=5 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2009 the first series aired, retitled ''The Hollyoaks Music Show''. When the new series was broadcast, it was shown as part of T4 weekly on Channel 4, again presented by Rick Edwards. It is filmed within the ''Hollyoaks'' studios in [[Childwall]], [[Liverpool]]. The show features signed and unsigned acts performing in and around the ''Hollyoaks'' set. A Christmas special was announced in November 2010, due to air in December.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.e4.com/blog/hollyoaks/post/ajeki0bif2jxepkisgcz9n/view.e4 |title=Music Show with Matalan.co.uk - Xmas Special |work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |first=Ciaran |last=Varley |date=23 November 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016081542/http://www.e4.com/blog/hollyoaks/post/ajeki0bif2jxepkisgcz9n/view.e4 |archivedate=16 October 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nActs which have appeared include [[The Saturdays]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/interviews/thesaturdays.html|title=Saturdays To Disband For S Club Juniors Reunion?|work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |date=20 October 2009|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> [[Mr Hudson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/interviews/mrhudson.html|title=Mr Hudson Was Laughed At By Rihanna Shocker...|work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |date=20 October 2009|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/interviews/chipmunk.html|title=Chipmunk's Critical Thinking...|work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |date=20 October 2009|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> [[Tinchy Stryder]], [[N-Dubz]] and [[Calvin Harris]], [[Example (rapper)|Example]], [[Jason Derulo]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/blog/week07/index.shtml |title=Show Seven: Riding Solo |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |year=2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727032724/http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/blog/week07/index.shtml |archive-date=27 July 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Diana Vickers]], [[Olly Murs]], [[The Wanted]] and [[You Me at Six]]  as well as some unsigned acts including [[Vienna Ditto]], Minnie Londoner<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/enter/ |title=Holypops - The Hollyoaks Music Show |work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |year=2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20}}</ref> and The Palpitations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepalpitations.co.uk/hollyoaks-music/ |title=Hollyoaks Music |work=The Palpitations |publisher=(thepalpitations.co.uk) |date=24 May 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The show regularly features members of the ''Hollyoaks'' cast as part of the audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/about.html|title=About The Hollyoaks Music Show|work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |date=20 October 2009|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref>\n\nAlong with the performances, ''The Hollyoaks Music Show'' also features fashion awards in each episode from episode 11 onwards. The award is presented to an act from the same episode for their clothing style. Acts who won the award include Olly Murs, [[Rihanna]], [[Selena Gomez]], [[McFly]] and [[JLS]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/fashionaward/ |title=This Week's Fashion Award |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |date=11 June 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226182702/http://matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/fashionaward/ |archive-date=26 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nA competition was run online throughout the series, with the winner given the chance to appear performing in an episode of ''Hollyoaks''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/hollypops/ |title=Hollypops |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |year=2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226182708/http://matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/hollypops/ |archive-date=26 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The winner was Shide Boss.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/hollypops/week04/ |title=Show Four - Shide Boss |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |date=12 June 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720220017/http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/hollypops/week04/ |archive-date=20 July 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/exclusivevideo/ |title=Exclusive: Shide Boss on set |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |year=2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128120122/http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/exclusivevideo/ |archive-date=28 November 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Other related shows==\n\n===''Hollyoaks: The Good, the Bad and the Gorgeous''===\nA drama-documentary shown on [[E4 (channel)|E4]] on 2 October 2009, looking back at the past 14 years, showing classic clips from the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/09/090914.html|title=Hollyoaks: The Good, the Bad and the Gorgeous|publisher=Channel 4|date=14 September 2009|accessdate=2009-09-14}}</ref> [[Ste Hay]] and [[Cheryl Brady]] go to a cinema where old clips from ''Hollyoaks'' are being shown by a familiar face. It was presented by Bernard Latham who played [[Gordon Cunningham]]. For the episode, special sequences were filmed between old clips of the show. They parodied such films as [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' and [[Randal Kleiser]]'s ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]''.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===''Hollyoaks Best Bits 2011''===\nA sequel to the 2009 one-off compilation special. First shown on 23 December 2011, Will Best looks back at some of the biggest and best moments from Hollyoaks 2011. The show also includes some interviews from its main cast such as: [[Scarlett Bowman]], [[Dylan Llewellyn]], [[Tosin Cole]], [[Karen Hassan]] amongst many others. Unlike the recent show, this one had exclusive sketches from [[Alex Carter (British actor)|Alex Carter]] and [[Lee Otway]], plus a cheeky look of highlights for 2012.\n\n===''Hollyoaks: A Little Film About Love''===\nA special [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] only episode which aired on 11 November 2011 following characters [[Jason Costello]] and [[Bart McQueen]] travelling to London to stop [[Sinead O'Connor (Hollyoaks)|Sinead O'Connor]] from leaving with boyfriend [[Gaz Bennett]], during the journey Jason records on a camera as documentary, it also features pre-recorded clips of Jason interviewing characters such as [[Maddie Morrison]], [[Myra McQueen]] and [[Neil Cooper (Hollyoaks)|Neil Cooper]] . It also features [[Jono (Hollyoaks)|Jono]], [[Ruby Button]] and [[Duncan Button]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ie/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/spoilers/a348178/a-little-film-about-love-by-jason-costello.html|title='A Little Film About Love by Jason Costello'|date=1 November 2011|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===''Hollyoaks: Chasing Rainbows''===\nA Special E4 only episode which aired on 7 June 2012, that follows [[Dennis Savage]] on his journey with students [[Leanne Holiday]], [[Barney Harper-McBride]] and [[Scott Sabeka]] who travel to Liverpool to seek out musician [[Maverick Sabre]] to headline the Savage's Forest Party back in the village, Dennis struggles to prove throughout that he knows Maverick and will be able to find him in time for the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ie/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/spoilers/a382560/chasing-rainbows.html|title='Chasing Rainbows'|date=28 May 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===''Hollyoaks: The Story of''===\n[[Mercedes McQueen|Mercedes]] - [[Murder]], [[affair]]s and a LOT of bodycon...join [[Hollyoaks]] actress [[Jennifer Metcalfe]] as she looks back at the life of Mercedes McQueen. Features backstage secrets and clips from the show.\n{{Clear}}\n[[Darren Osborne|Darren]]'s '''''Biggest Dating Disasters''''' - [[Hollyoaks]] star [[Ashley Taylor Dawson]] takes us through Darren's biggest dating disasters.\n{{Clear}}\n[[Sinead O'Connor (Hollyoaks)|Sinead]]'s '''''Most Life-Changing Moments''''' - Revenge, tragedy, bombs... [[Stephanie Davis (actress)|Steph Davis]] takes us through some of Sinead's biggest moments!\n{{Clear}}\n[[Ste Hay|Ste]]'s '''''Greatest Shockers''''' - [[Hollyoaks]] actor [[Kieron Richardson]] relives his character's most shocking moments.\n{{Clear}}\n[[Tony Hutchinson|Tony]]'s '''''20 Years in Hollyoaks''''' - For [[Hollyoaks]]' 20th anniversary, actor [[Nick Pickard]] relives Tony's memorable storylines.\n{{Clear}}\n[[Sienna Blake|Sienna]]'s '''''Most WTH?! Moments''''' - A faked pregnancy, fancying her twin brother... relive Sienna's *slightly* unusual stories.\n\n===''Hollyoaks Favourites''===\nAn E4 series hosted by cast members [[Kieron Richardson]] and [[Jorgie Porter]].<ref name=\"Faves\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/hollyoaks/a32014576/hollyoaks-kieron-richardson-jorgie-porter-hollyoaks-favourites/|title=Hollyoaks stars Jorgie Porter and Kieron Richardson reveal their favourite episodes ahead of classic repeats|work=[[Digital Spy]]|access-date=3 April 2020|last=Houghton|first=Rianne}}</ref> Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], production on ''Hollyoaks'' was suspended until further notice, and episodes were cut down to two per week, rather than the usual five, to preserve content.<ref name=\"Faves\" /> ''Hollyoaks Favourites'' was broadcast on the three other nights instead of new episodes.<ref name=\"Faves\" /> The series shows Richardson and Porter showcasing popular past episodes of ''Hollyoaks''. Some favourites include Mercedes and Dr Browning\u2019s wedding, Cameron holding the Lomax\u2019s hostage and Silas\u2019s return. <ref name=\"Faves\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/index.html The official ''Hollyoaks'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/the-morning-after-the-night-before/ The official ''Hollyoaks: The Morning After the Night Before'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/tgtbtg/index.html The official ''Hollyoaks: The Good, the Bad and the Gorgeous'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/later/2009/ The official ''Hollyoaks Later'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/ The official ''Hollyoaks Music Show'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/freshers/index.html The official ''Hollyoaks Freshers'' website]\n\n{{Hollyoaks}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Hollyoaks'' spin-offs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Hollyoaks Spin-Offs}}\n[[Category:Lists of soap opera episodes|Hollyoaks]]\n[[Category:Hollyoaks spin-offs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\nThe following is a list of late night, DVD and spin-off series of [[Channel 4]] [[soap-opera]] ''[[Hollyoaks]]''. Each has a brief summary of the plot.\n\n==Video/DVD specials==\n\n===Hollyoaks: Off on One===\nA [[VHS|video]] spin-off from 1998 which sees [[Rob Hawthorne (Hollyoaks)|Rob Hawthorne]] seek revenge against [[Kurt Benson]]. The storyline comes to a dramatic conclusion with Rob and Kurt fighting on a boat. Rob rushes at Kurt, however he moves out of the way and Rob falls into the sea, with everyone believing he is dead. Music composed and performed by Steve Wright.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Indecent Behaviour===\nA video/DVD spin-off released in 2001. [[Geri Hudson]] arrives with footballer boyfriend [[Jason Cunliffe (Hollyoaks)|Jason Cunliffe]]. In a club, [[Scott Anderson (Hollyoaks)|Scott Anderson]] begins to chat Geri up. [[Luke Morgan]] steps in to stop him taking it too far, however just as Scott and his friends are about to throw Luke into the river, Scott tells his friends that he has a better idea; Scott and his friends pull Luke's trousers down to make fun of Luke's rape from the previous year. [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]] and [[Beth Morgan (Hollyoaks)|Beth Morgan]] try to break Scott and Luke up before a fight breaks, which it does between Ben and Luke. Beth is later offered a lift by Scott, and then is raped. Music composed and performed by Steve Wright.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Late night specials==\n\n===Hollyoaks: Lost Weekend===\nFour episodes broadcast in 1999 centring on the kidnapping of [[Lucy Benson]] by Rob Hawthorne and the desperate search by [[Ruth Osborne]], [[Lewis Richardson (Hollyoaks)|Lewis Richardson]] and [[Tony Hutchinson]]. \n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Boys Do Barca===\nBroadcast in 2000, [[Alex Bell (Hollyoaks)|Alex Bell]], [[Max Cunningham]], [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]], [[Tony Hutchinson]], [[Luke Morgan]], [[Sam \"O.B.\" O'Brien]], [[Sol Patrick]] and [[Lewis Richardson (Hollyoaks)|Lewis Richardson]] make their way to [[Barcelona]] to celebrate [[Rory Finnigan]]'s stag party before Finn marries Tony's Mother. Tony, however, has secretly enlisted the help of [[Carol Groves]] to convince Finn not to go ahead with the marriage.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Breaking Boundaries===\nBroadcast in March 2000, the late night special involves a 90s disco at the club where [[Ruth Osborne]] discovers [[Lewis Richardson (Hollyoaks)|Lewis Richardson's]] gambling addiction. Ruth and Lewis eventually end up sleeping together, despite Ruth's marriage to [[Kurt Benson]]. Meanwhile, after a football match, [[Mark Gibbs]] beats up [[Luke Morgan]] before raping him.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Leap of Faith===\nOn 24 October 2003 late night special sees [[Ellie Mills]] try to kill herself before telling serial-killer husband [[Toby Mills|Toby]] to hand himself in to the police. Toby realises he could not live without Ellie and ends up holding her hostage on a rooftop. As Toby prepares to jump with Ellie, [[Dan Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Dan Hunter]] arrives and pushes Toby off the building, killing him.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: After Hours===\nA four-part late night series broadcast in 2004. [[Lisa Hunter]] is whisked away to Paris with a man she meets in a hotel where she worked. [[Joe Spencer (Hollyoaks)|Joe Spencer]] and his friends go on a night out that ends in disaster. Meanwhile, former character [[Matt Musgrove]] crosses over to the special.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: In Too Deep===\nIn a one off special aired on 31 May 2005, [[Steph Cunningham|Steph Dean]] is haunted by the ghost of one of [[Toby Mills]]' victims and she nearly drowns. Meanwhile, [[Lee Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Lee Hunter]] and Bombhead cause mayhem at the backstage of Steph's show.\n{{Clear}}\n\n'''Cast:'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Character\n! Actor\n|-\n| [[Bombhead]]\n| [[Lee Otway]]\n|-\n| [[Cameron Clark (Hollyoaks)|Cameron Clark]]\n| Ben Gerrard\n|-\n| [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]]\n| [[Marcus Patric]]\n|-\n| [[Craig Dean]]\n| [[Guy Burnett]]\n|-\n| [[Frankie Osborne|Frankie Dean]]\n| [[Helen Pearson]]\n|-\n| [[Steph Cunningham|Steph Dean]]\n| [[Carley Stenson]]\n|-\n| [[Lee Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Lee Hunter]]\n| [[Alex Carter (British actor)|Alex Carter]]\n|-\n| [[Lisa Hunter]]\n| [[Gemma Atkinson]]\n|-\n| [[Joe Spencer (Hollyoaks)|Joe Spencer]]\n| Matt Milburn\n|-\n| Lucy\n| [[Celena Cherry]]\n|-\n| Michelle\n| Lou Emmett\n|-\n| Simon\n| Sean Taylor\n|-\n| Vanessa\n| Lizzie Hills\n|}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Crossing the Line===\nThe late night special broadcast in 2005 sees [[Andy Holt (Hollyoaks)|Andy Holt]] spike [[Dannii Carbone]]'s drink with [[gamma-Hydroxybutyric acid|GHB]] before raping her. Andy then reveals his activities to his friend, [[Sam Owen]], who agrees to join Andy to drug and rape girls. Meanwhile, Chris tricks [[Lee Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Lee Hunter]] into sleeping with a transvestite called Aphrodite. Elsewhere, [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]] and [[Lisa Hunter]] make friends with siblings Ally and Alex.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: No Going Back===\nFollowing ''Crossing the Line'', [[Andy Holt (Hollyoaks)|Andy]] drugs [[Sophie Burton|Sophie]] and [[Mel Burton]]. He rapes Mel and leaves [[Sam Owen|Sam]] to rape Sophie, but he does not. Dannii tells [[Russ Owen]] that she was raped. He does not believe her so she attempts suicide. Mel, Sophie and [[Louise Summers]] stop her and report Andy to the police. Sam and Andy, both on the top of a cliff, are caught in a fight between themselves and Russ. Sam and Andy both fall over the cliff. Russ manages to grab the pair, however has to let one go, so lets Andy fall to his death. Meanwhile [[Rhys Ashworth]], [[Gilly Roach]], [[Jessica Harris (Hollyoaks)|Jessica Harris]] and [[Olivia Johnson]] go on a trip to a spiritrist camp.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Back from the Dead===\nIn 2006, Andy Holt returns after surviving the fall and seeks his revenge against Russ by kidnapping his sister [[Nicole Owen|Nicole]]. Sam and Russ come in to free Nicole but Andy attacks them with a metal pole and threatens to rape Nicole but then Mel bursts in and whacks him over the head with the metal pole and begins to laugh at him as she calls the police. Whilst tied up, Andy let's slip to Russ and Nicole about Sam's involvement in the rapes. Andy escapes, and  Mel chases after him and he runs into a metal spike and he starts to bleed from his mouth, he starts to talk but Mel can't understand what he says. He then dies moments later as Mel watches on. {{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: King of Hearts===\nA late night special called ''Hollyoaks: King of Hearts'' was announced in November 2010 and was broadcast on 15 December 2010 on Channel 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/news/a287673/hollyoaks-confirms-late-night-special.html |title=Hollyoaks confirms late-night special |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |first=Daniel |last=Kilkelly |accessdate=2010-11-14 |date=14 November 2010}}</ref> The episode followed events in the main series which saw [[Kathleen McQueen]] blackmailing her family. The episode features [[Rhys Ashworth]] and [[Jacqui McQueen]] attempting to cheat during a game of poker with [[Brendan Brady]] and [[Danny Houston]]. After their plan is discovered, Danny tells Jacqui she must sleep with him to save Rhys and wipe the debt they owe him. The episode was originally due to air on 16 December 2010. However, this was later changed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/scoop/a289629/schedule-change-for-hollyoaks-special.html |title=Schedule change for Hollyoaks special |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |first=Daniel |last=Kilkelly |date=24 November 2010|accessdate=2010-11-24}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Spin-off series==\n\n===Hollyoaks: Movin' On===\nA new sixteen part series. [[Tony Hutchinson]] and [[Rory Finnigan]] open their new business venture. Meanwhile, after beating [[Ruth Osborne]] up, [[Lewis Richardson (Hollyoaks)|Lewis]], racked by guilt, commits suicide. Ruth then leaves for [[London]]. Music composed and performed by Steve Wright  http://www.stevewrightcomposer.com\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Let Loose===\nA 2005 series following [[Ben Davies (Hollyoaks)|Ben Davies]] and [[Lisa Hunter]] as they depart Hollyoaks for a new life. Lisa and Ben's relationship is put to the test over Lisa's jealousy, however she agrees to give their relationship another go. Music composed and performed by Steve Wright  http://www.stevewrightcomposer.com\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: In the City===\n{{main|Hollyoaks: In the City}}\nLisa and Ben return to [[Liverpool]], where Lisa is set up with a modelling agency. Ben spends the pair's entire savings on a bar but is conned. Lisa delves further up the career path and Ben has an illicit affair and is involved in dodgy dealings with Burton Phillips including arson and murder. Finally, Lisa ended up accidentely shooting Ben as he tried to save her from being used in a snuff film. Ben's fate remains unknown.\n\n===Hollyoaks Later===\n{{main|Hollyoaks Later|Hollyoaks Later (series 1)}}\n2008 series following [[Niall Rafferty]] as he returns for revenge on [[Steph Cunningham]], [[Craig Dean]] and [[Tom Cunningham]], which leads to the dramatic death of Niall. Meanwhile, [[Kris Fisher|Kris]] and [[Malachy Fisher]] return to Ireland to attend their father's funeral as Malachy and [[Mercedes McQueen]] marry. [[Sarah Barnes]], [[Nancy Hayton]] and [[Zoe Carpenter]] head off on a \"girly\" road trip as the Dirty Diegos enter 'Battle of the Bands'.<ref name=\"ds\">{{ cite news | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/a134073/late-night-hollyoaks-to-get-c4-run.html | title='Late Night Hollyoaks' to get C4 run | first=Kris |last=Green | publisher=[[Digital Spy]] | date=30 October 2008 | accessdate=2008-10-30 }}</ref>\n\n{{main|Hollyoaks Later (series 2)}}\nA second series was commissioned and was broadcast in September 2009.<ref name=\"laterreturn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/07/090702.html |title=Hollyoaks Later To Return |publisher=Channel 4 |date=2 July 2009 |accessdate=2009-07-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704214849/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/07/090702.html |archivedate=4 July 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"kirkwood\">{{ cite news| url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/a153128/kirkwood-to-head-up-new-hollyoaks-later.html| title=Kirkwood to produce new Hollyoaks Later | publisher=Digital Spy |first=Kris |last=Green| date=17 April 2009 | accessdate=2009-04-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/04/090417pm.html |title=Hollyoaks Later returns! |publisher=Channel4 |date=17 April 2009 |accessdate=2009-07-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522080812/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/04/090417pm.html |archivedate=22 May 2009 }}</ref> It follows four main stories: [[Hannah Ashworth|Hannah]], [[Rhys Ashworth|Rhys]] and [[Josh Ashworth]] go off to a music festival, where they encounter a dangerous drug dealer, [[Tony Hutchinson]] marries [[Cindy Cunningham]] after several mishaps, [[McQueen family|the McQueens]] go to London for [[Theresa McQueen|Theresa's]] modelling and [[Sarah Barnes]] and [[Zoe Carpenter]] are joined by Sarah's jealous girlfriend [[Lydia Hart]] on a parachute jump which leads to Sarah's death after Lydia sabotages her parachute.\n\n{{main|Hollyoaks Later (series 3)}}\nIn April 2010, Channel 4 announced that the show would return for a third series, this time produced by Hollyoaks series producer Paul Marquess. The characters appearing included: [[Mitzeee Minniver]], [[Carl Costello]], [[Riley Costello]], [[Seth Costello]], [[Malachy Fisher]], [[Mercedes Fisher]], [[Theresa McQueen]] and [[Nancy Hayton]]. Filming took place in the summer of 2010, and in October 2010, it was revealed that the third series would begin on 25 October, and would closely interweave with the main Hollyoaks series, revolving around \"one fateful night\". UFC Fighter Michael Bisping guest starred.\n\n{{main|Hollyoaks Later (series 4)}}\nIt Was reported that a fourth series had been recommissioned due to the popularity of the last few series. Filming will take place in the summer of 2011. Characters rumoured to be involved in the storylines have included [[Mercedes McQueen]], [[Myra McQueen]], [[Michaela McQueen]], [[Texas Longford]], [[Silas Blissett]], [[Heidi Costello]], [[Riley Costello]], [[Lynsey Nolan]] and [[Mitzeee Minniver]]. New cast members include a new addition to the McQueen family played by Amy Walsh sister of Girls aloud star Kimberly Walsh and a new unnamed hunk to be played by ex-eastenders actor Chris Coghill. By early June scenes had begun filming in Ibiza with Mercedes McQueen, Myra McQueen, Michaela McQueen, [[Theresa McQueen]], [[Will Savage]], [[Rae Wilson]] and Mitzeee Minniver. Series 4 is set to be aired over the course of five nights from 5 September to 10 September 2011.\nIn the gripping final episode of the series, Rae Wilson was strangled by Silas Blissett after he heard that [[Brendan Brady]] wanted to kill her. He wanted Brendan to be arrested on suspicion of murder so that he could continue with his evil plans.\n\n===Hollyoaks Does Come Dine With Me===\n2015 Series based on the [[Channel 4]] evening show [[Come Dine With Me]]. The show aired at 7:30pm on [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] during the 20th Anniversary Week. [[Jimmy McKenna]] ([[Jack Osborne]]), [[Jessica Fox (actress)|Jessica Fox]] ([[Nancy Osborne]]), [[Kieron Richardson]] ([[Ste Hay]]), [[Kirsty Leigh Porter]] ([[Leela Lomax]]), Jessica Ellis ([[Tegan Lomax]]) and Jaqueline Boatswain ([[Simone Loveday]]) were the Hollyoaks stars that took part. \n\n'''''Ratings'''''\n*0.82\n*0.75\n*0.60\n*0.62\n*0.71\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Online spin-offs==\n\n===Hollyoaks: The Morning After the Night Before===\n{{main|Hollyoaks: The Morning After the Night Before}}\n\n[[Josh Ashworth]] heads off to party with [[Dave Colburn]] in [[Manchester]] in the on-line spin-off which features the down side to [[binge drinking]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/a159587/online-oaks-to-explore-binge-drinking.html |title=Online 'Oaks to explore binge drinking |publisher=Digital Spy|first=Kris|last=Green |date=12 June 2009|accessdate=2009-11-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/06/090608.html |title=Hollyoaks: The Morning After the Night Before |publisher=Channel 4 |date=8 June 2009 |accessdate=2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930203335/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/06/090608.html |archivedate=30 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Hollyoaks: Freshers===\nFreshers is a 2010 online drama following the lives of the fresher students before they begin at Hollyoaks Community College. Like ''The Morning After the Night Before'', several characters' social networking websites were created, this time using [[Facebook]]. The series featured the return of [[Lee Hunter (Hollyoaks)|Lee Hunter]], and debut of new characters [[Jamil Fadel]], [[Leanne Holiday]] and [[Doug Carter]]. It also starred [[Charlotte Lau]], [[India Longford]], [[Texas Longford]] and [[Dave Colburn]]. A return also featured [[David \"Bombhead\" Burke|Bombhead]].\n\n===Hollyoaks: Tom's Life===\nTom's finding life tough after Nancy and Darren's break up. When his plan to get them back together goes wrong he almost gives up completely... until he discovers an amazing new skill.\n\n===Hollyoaks: Access All Areas===\n\n{{col-begin}}\n\n{{col-3}}\n====Series 1====\n\n1. [[Amanda Clapham]] ([[Holly Cunningham]])<br>2. [[James Sutton (actor)|James Sutton]] ([[John Paul McQueen]]) <br>3. [[Jessica Fox (actress)|Jessica Fox]] ([[Nancy Hayton|Nancy Osborne]])<br>4. [[Jorgie Porter]] ([[Theresa McQueen]])<br>5. [[Parry Glasspool]] ([[Harry Thompson (Hollyoaks)|Harry Thompson]])<br>6. [[Jazmine Franks]] ([[Esther Bloom]])<br>7. [[Charlie Wernham]] ([[Robbie Roscoe]])<br>8. [[Anna Passey]] ([[Sienna Blake]])<br>9. Cameron Moore ([[Cameron Campbell]])<br>10. [[Tamara Wall]] ([[Grace Black]])<br>11. Fabrizo Santino ([[Ziggy Roscoe]])<br>12. [[Nikki Sanderson]] ([[Maxine Minniver]])\n\n====Series 2====\n\n1. Charlie Clapham ([[Freddie Roscoe]])<br>2. [[Stephanie Waring]] ([[Cindy Cunningham|Cindy Savage]])<br>3. [[Sophie Austin]] ([[Lindsey Butterfield|Lindsey Roscoe]])<br>4. [[Kieron Richardson]] ([[Ste Hay]])<br>5. [[Jacqueline Boatswain]] & [[Karl Collins]] ([[Simone Loveday|Simone]] & [[Louis Loveday]])<br>6. [[Daisy Wood-Davis]] ([[Kim Butterfield]])<br>7. [[Jamie Lomas]] ([[Warren Fox]])<br>8. [[Gregory Finnegan]] ([[James Nightingale (Hollyoaks)|James Nightingale]])<br>9. Richard Linnell & Kassuis Nelson ([[Alfie Nightingale]] & [[Jade Albright]])<br>10. [[Duncan James]] ([[Ryan Knight]])\n\n====Series 3====\n1. [[Kirsty-Leigh Porter]] ([[Leela Lomax]])<br>2. Duyane Boachie ([[Zack Loveday]])<br>3. Amy Conachan ([[Courtney Campbell (Hollyoaks)|Courtney Campbell]])\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Media Content==\n\n===Hollyoaks Highs: The Wicked Bits===\nHighlights show made in 1999 to mark Hollyoaks going three times a week.\n\n===Hollyoaks: Search for a star===\nA short series on channel 4 where hollyoaks held open auditions to cast a new character and showed the audition process\n\n===Hollyoaks: Access All Areas===\nThis 2000 documentary which features Hollyoaks cast discussing various sexual matters.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks on the Pull===\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Extreme Challenges===\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks Backstage===\nA weekly on-line documentary featuring various members of the ''Hollyoaks'' cast showing viewers behind the scenes of the show. Each 3 minute episode is shown broadcast weekly on the E4 website.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Hollyoaks: Summer's Got a Secret===\n{{Clear}}\n\n===''The Hollyoaks Music Show''===\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = The Hollyoaks Music Show\n| italic_title = no<!-- set below -->\n| language = English\n| num_episodes = 26\n| presenter = [[Rick Edwards]] <small>(2008\u20132010)</small><br /> [[Matt Littler]] <small>(2011)</small>\n| producer = Sarah Clarke\n| director = Chris Howe<br /> Dave Skinner\n| company = Conker Media<br /> [[Lime Pictures]]\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| website = http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/\n| production_website =http://www.limepictures.com/MusicShow.htm\n}}\n'''''The Hollyoaks Music Show''''' is a music television programme broadcast as part of [[T4 (Channel 4)|T4]] on [[Channel 4]]. The show began broadcasting on 17 October 2009, following a pilot episode in 2008, and features various recording artists performing and participating in the show. It is sponsored by British retailer [[Matalan]] and hosted by [[Rick Edwards]].\n\nThe series first began in 2008, when it was named ''Hollyoaks Music Special'', a one-off programme hosted by [[Rick Edwards]] and former ''Hollyoaks'' actor [[Matt Littler]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/news/a91635/hollyoaks-to-host-music-special.html |title='Hollyoaks' to host 'Music Special' |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |first=Dave |last=West |date=15 March 2008 |accessdate=2010-11-20}}</ref> Following its success, Channel 4 commissioned two series<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/news/a96807/c4-wants-hollyoaks-music-show-series.html |title=C4 wants 'Hollyoaks Music Show' series |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |first=Dave |last=West |date=15 March 2008 |accessdate=2010-11-20}}</ref> and retailer [[Matalan]] became the show's official sponsor, in order to reach the target audience of 16- to 34-year-olds. Repeats of the series have been shown on [[4Music]] since 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4music.com/article/ontv/the-hollyoaks-music-show-2010-06-05.html |title=The Hollyoaks Music Show |date=31 May 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |work=[[4Music]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205233747/http://www.4music.com/article/ontv/the-hollyoaks-music-show-2010-06-05.html |archivedate=5 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2009 the first series aired, retitled ''The Hollyoaks Music Show''. When the new series was broadcast, it was shown as part of T4 weekly on Channel 4, again presented by Rick Edwards. It is filmed within the ''Hollyoaks'' studios in [[Childwall]], [[Liverpool]]. The show features signed and unsigned acts performing in and around the ''Hollyoaks'' set. A Christmas special was announced in November 2010, due to air in December.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.e4.com/blog/hollyoaks/post/ajeki0bif2jxepkisgcz9n/view.e4 |title=Music Show with Matalan.co.uk - Xmas Special |work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |first=Ciaran |last=Varley |date=23 November 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016081542/http://www.e4.com/blog/hollyoaks/post/ajeki0bif2jxepkisgcz9n/view.e4 |archivedate=16 October 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nActs which have appeared include [[The Saturdays]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/interviews/thesaturdays.html|title=Saturdays To Disband For S Club Juniors Reunion?|work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |date=20 October 2009|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> [[Mr Hudson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/interviews/mrhudson.html|title=Mr Hudson Was Laughed At By Rihanna Shocker...|work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |date=20 October 2009|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/interviews/chipmunk.html|title=Chipmunk's Critical Thinking...|work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |date=20 October 2009|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref> [[Tinchy Stryder]], [[N-Dubz]] and [[Calvin Harris]], [[Example (rapper)|Example]], [[Jason Derulo]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/blog/week07/index.shtml |title=Show Seven: Riding Solo |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |year=2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727032724/http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/blog/week07/index.shtml |archive-date=27 July 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Diana Vickers]], [[Olly Murs]], [[The Wanted]] and [[You Me at Six]]  as well as some unsigned acts including [[Vienna Ditto]], Minnie Londoner<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/enter/ |title=Holypops - The Hollyoaks Music Show |work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |year=2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20}}</ref> and The Palpitations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepalpitations.co.uk/hollyoaks-music/ |title=Hollyoaks Music |work=The Palpitations |publisher=(thepalpitations.co.uk) |date=24 May 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The show regularly features members of the ''Hollyoaks'' cast as part of the audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/about.html|title=About The Hollyoaks Music Show|work=[[E4 (channel)|E4]] |publisher=([[Channel 4 Television Corporation]]) |date=20 October 2009|accessdate=2009-10-20}}</ref>\n\nAlong with the performances, ''The Hollyoaks Music Show'' also features fashion awards in each episode from episode 11 onwards. The award is presented to an act from the same episode for their clothing style. Acts who won the award include Olly Murs, [[Rihanna]], [[Selena Gomez]], [[McFly]] and [[JLS]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/fashionaward/ |title=This Week's Fashion Award |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |date=11 June 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226182702/http://matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/fashionaward/ |archive-date=26 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nA competition was run online throughout the series, with the winner given the chance to appear performing in an episode of ''Hollyoaks''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/hollypops/ |title=Hollypops |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |year=2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226182708/http://matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/hollypops/ |archive-date=26 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The winner was Shide Boss.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/hollypops/week04/ |title=Show Four - Shide Boss |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |date=12 June 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720220017/http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/hollypops/week04/ |archive-date=20 July 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/exclusivevideo/ |title=Exclusive: Shide Boss on set |work=The Hollyoaks Music Show |publisher=([[Matalan]]) |year=2010 |accessdate=2010-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128120122/http://www.matalan-hollyoaksmusicshow.co.uk/exclusivevideo/ |archive-date=28 November 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Other related shows==\n\n===''Hollyoaks: The Good, the Bad and the Gorgeous''===\nA drama-documentary shown on [[E4 (channel)|E4]] on 2 October 2009, looking back at the past 14 years, showing classic clips from the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/H/hollyoaks/news/previous/09/09/090914.html|title=Hollyoaks: The Good, the Bad and the Gorgeous|publisher=Channel 4|date=14 September 2009|accessdate=2009-09-14}}</ref> [[Ste Hay]] and [[Cheryl Brady]] go to a cinema where old clips from ''Hollyoaks'' are being shown by a familiar face. It was presented by Bernard Latham who played [[Gordon Cunningham]]. For the episode, special sequences were filmed between old clips of the show. They parodied such films as [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' and [[Randal Kleiser]]'s ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]''.\n{{Clear}}\n\n===''Hollyoaks Best Bits 2011''===\nA sequel to the 2009 one-off compilation special. First shown on 23 December 2011, Will Best looks back at some of the biggest and best moments from Hollyoaks 2011. The show also includes some interviews from its main cast such as: [[Scarlett Bowman]], [[Dylan Llewellyn]], [[Tosin Cole]], [[Karen Hassan]] amongst many others. Unlike the recent show, this one had exclusive sketches from [[Alex Carter (British actor)|Alex Carter]] and [[Lee Otway]], plus a cheeky look of highlights for 2012.\n\n===''Hollyoaks: A Little Film About Love''===\nA special [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]] only episode which aired on 11 November 2011 following characters [[Jason Costello]] and [[Bart McQueen]] travelling to London to stop [[Sinead O'Connor (Hollyoaks)|Sinead O'Connor]] from leaving with boyfriend [[Gaz Bennett]], during the journey Jason records on a camera as documentary, it also features pre-recorded clips of Jason interviewing characters such as [[Maddie Morrison]], [[Myra McQueen]] and [[Neil Cooper (Hollyoaks)|Neil Cooper]] . It also features [[Jono (Hollyoaks)|Jono]], [[Ruby Button]] and [[Duncan Button]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ie/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/spoilers/a348178/a-little-film-about-love-by-jason-costello.html|title='A Little Film About Love by Jason Costello'|date=1 November 2011|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===''Hollyoaks: Chasing Rainbows''===\nA Special E4 only episode which aired on 7 June 2012, that follows [[Dennis Savage]] on his journey with students [[Leanne Holiday]], [[Barney Harper-McBride]] and [[Scott Sabeka]] who travel to Liverpool to seek out musician [[Maverick Sabre]] to headline the Savage's Forest Party back in the village, Dennis struggles to prove throughout that he knows Maverick and will be able to find him in time for the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.ie/soaps/s13/hollyoaks/spoilers/a382560/chasing-rainbows.html|title='Chasing Rainbows'|date=28 May 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===''Hollyoaks: The Story of''===\n[[Mercedes McQueen|Mercedes]] - [[Murder]], [[affair]]s and a LOT of bodycon...join [[Hollyoaks]] actress [[Jennifer Metcalfe]] as she looks back at the life of Mercedes McQueen. Features backstage secrets and clips from the show.\n{{Clear}}\n[[Darren Osborne|Darren]]'s '''''Biggest Dating Disasters''''' - [[Hollyoaks]] star [[Ashley Taylor Dawson]] takes us through Darren's biggest dating disasters.\n{{Clear}}\n[[Sinead O'Connor (Hollyoaks)|Sinead]]'s '''''Most Life-Changing Moments''''' - Revenge, tragedy, bombs... [[Stephanie Davis (actress)|Steph Davis]] takes us through some of Sinead's biggest moments!\n{{Clear}}\n[[Ste Hay|Ste]]'s '''''Greatest Shockers''''' - [[Hollyoaks]] actor [[Kieron Richardson]] relives his character's most shocking moments.\n{{Clear}}\n[[Tony Hutchinson|Tony]]'s '''''20 Years in Hollyoaks''''' - For [[Hollyoaks]]' 20th anniversary, actor [[Nick Pickard]] relives Tony's memorable storylines.\n{{Clear}}\n[[Sienna Blake|Sienna]]'s '''''Most WTH?! Moments''''' - A faked pregnancy, fancying her twin brother... relive Sienna's *slightly* unusual stories.\n\n===''Hollyoaks Favourites''===\nAn E4 series hosted by cast members [[Kieron Richardson]] and [[Jorgie Porter]].<ref name=\"Faves\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/hollyoaks/a32014576/hollyoaks-kieron-richardson-jorgie-porter-hollyoaks-favourites/|title=Hollyoaks stars Jorgie Porter and Kieron Richardson reveal their favourite episodes ahead of classic repeats|work=[[Digital Spy]]|access-date=3 April 2020|last=Houghton|first=Rianne}}</ref> Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], production on ''Hollyoaks'' was suspended until further notice, and episodes were cut down to two per week, rather than the usual five, to preserve content.<ref name=\"Faves\" /> ''Hollyoaks Favourites'' was broadcast on the three other nights instead of new episodes.<ref name=\"Faves\" /> The series shows Richardson and Porter showcasing popular past episodes of ''Hollyoaks''.<ref name=\"Faves\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/index.html The official ''Hollyoaks'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/the-morning-after-the-night-before/ The official ''Hollyoaks: The Morning After the Night Before'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/tgtbtg/index.html The official ''Hollyoaks: The Good, the Bad and the Gorgeous'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/later/2009/ The official ''Hollyoaks Later'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/hollyoaksmusicshowwithmatalan/ The official ''Hollyoaks Music Show'' website]\n* [http://www.e4.com/hollyoaks/freshers/index.html The official ''Hollyoaks Freshers'' website]\n\n{{Hollyoaks}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Hollyoaks'' spin-offs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Hollyoaks Spin-Offs}}\n[[Category:Lists of soap opera episodes|Hollyoaks]]\n[[Category:Hollyoaks spin-offs]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:b496:6200:b4dc:ec5c:7dc:5896", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHollyoaks Favourites)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hollyoaks_spin-offs"}
{"title_page": "Adline Castelino", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian model and beauty pageant titleholder}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name         = Adline Castelino\n| image        =\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = Adline Mewis Quadros Castelino\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1998|07|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Kuwait City]], Kuwait\n| occupation   = {{hlist|Model}}\n| hometown     = [[Udupi|Udupi, Karnataka]], India\n| height       = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Adline Castelino: Cast You Digital Casting Agency Profiles - |url=https://castyou.in/adline-castelino/}}</ref><!-- DO NOT CHANGE HEIGHT DETAILS. It has been established that she is 5'6\" cm, as per RS (reliable source). Thanks. -->\n| hair_color   = [[Black hair|Black]]\n| eye_color    = [[Eye color#Brown|Brown]]\n| alma_mater   = [[Wilson College, Mumbai]]\n| title        = Miss Cocoaberry Diva 2019<br>[[Miss Diva 2020|Miss Diva Universe 2020]]\n| competitions = [[Miss Diva 2020]]<br>(Winner)<br>[[Miss Universe 2020]]<br>(TBD)\n}}\n\n'''Adline Mewis Quadros Castelino''' (born 24 July 1998) is an Indian model and beauty pageant titleholder who was crowned [[Miss Diva 2020|Miss Diva Universe 2020]]. She will represent India at [[Miss Universe 2020]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nCastelino was born in [[Kuwait City]], Kuwait to [[Mangalorean Catholic]] parents Alphonsus and Meera Castelino. Her family is originally from [[Udyavara]] in the city of [[Udupi]], [[Karnataka]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/events/bangalore/a-grand-homecoming-for-liva-miss-diva-universe-2020-adline-castelino/amp_articleshow/74475590.cms|title=A grand homecoming for Miss Diva Universe 2020 Adline Castelino|work=The Times of India|date=5 March 2020|first1=Sunayana|last1=Suresh|first2=Tanvi|last2=PS}}</ref> In Kuwait, Castelino attended the [[Indian Central School (Kuwait)|Indian Central School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansinkuwait.com/news/Kuwait-born-Adline-Castelino-crowned-Miss-Diva-Universe-2020|title=Kuwait born Adline Castelino crowned Miss Diva Universe 2020|date=23 February 2020}}</ref> At age 15, Castelino returned to India and moved to [[Mumbai]], where she attended the St. Xavier High School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=660910|title=Adline Castelino first from city selected for Miss Diva Universe 2020|website=daijiworld.com}}</ref> She subsequently attended the [[Wilson College, Mumbai|Wilson College]] in Mumbai, where she graduated with a degree in business administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/life-style/spotlight/adline-castelino-im-grateful-to-my-college-for-making-me-who-i-am-today/amp_articleshow/74494825.cms|title=I\u2019m grateful to my college for making me who I am today:Adline Castelino|work=The Times of India|date=6 March 2020|first=Pooja|last=Raisinghani}}</ref>\n\n==Social work==\nCastelino works with a welfare organisation called ''Vikas Sahayog Pratishthan'' (VSP) which functions to provide a sustainable livelihood for framers to curb [[Farmers' suicides in India|farmers' suicides]] and inequality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zoomtventertainment.com/amp/celebrity/photo-gallery/photos-all-you-need-to-know-about-the-newly-crowned-miss-diva-universe-2020-adline-castelino/557632|title=All you need to know about the newly-crowned Miss Diva Universe 2020 Adline Castelino|date=25 February 2020|work=[[Zoom (Indian TV channel)|Zoom]]}}</ref> She has raised money for the Child Help Foundation (CHF), through a crowd funding platform called [[Ketto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ketto.org/amp/fundraiser/ADLINECASTELINOforCHFM2Q3M|title=Help Adline Castelino spread smiles for Child Help Foundation|publisher=www.ketto.org|accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref> During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus outbreak]] in 2020, she helped in providing essentials like food supplies, sanitizers and masks for 'Desire Society', a non-profit voluntary organization that cares for children infected with [[HIV]] in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-CKrNcBkEX/?igshid=1ngdjj3pvuxwo|title=Adline Castelino - Desire Society, Mumbai|date=22 March 2020}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-KclM-BJmJ/?igshid=o479ijdzmhfl|title=Adline Castelino - Supplies for Desire Society|date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://desiresociety.org/Default/Pages/Default.aspx|title=Desire Society - Official|publisher=desiresociety.org|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Pageantry==\nAside from working as a model, Castelino has participated in various trivial pageants in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikifolder.com/adline-castelino/|title=Adline Castelino - Pofile|accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref> She further commenced her training for pageants through the Cocoaberry Training Academy in Mumbai. In 2019, she was crowned as 'Miss Cocoberry Diva' by the institution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenewscrunch.com/everything-you-should-know-about-miss-diva-universe-winner-adline-castelino-career-relationships-education-biography-recipes-and-unknown-facts-revealed/16679/|title=Everything you should know about Miss Diva Universe 2020 winner Adline Castelino|last=Benjamin|first=Annalise|date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thegreatpageantcommunity.com/2020/02/24/adline-castelino-wins-miss-universe-india-crown-at-miss-diva-2020/|title=Adline Castelino wins Miss Universe India crown at Miss Diva 2020|date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n=== Miss Diva 2020 ===\nIn 2019, Castelino auditioned for the [[Miss Diva 2020]] contest, through the [[Chennai]] auditions, and was shortlisted as a city finalist. In the culminating round of selections in [[Mumbai]], she entered as one of the top 20 delegates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tkop.org/2019/12/22/miss-universe-india-2020-meet-the-finalists-of-miss-diva-2020/|title=Miss Universe India 2020: The Finalists of Miss Diva 2020||date=22 December 2019|access-date=22 February 2020|last=Mishra|first=Vagisha}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehansindia.com/amp/life-style/miss-diva-2020-is-back-for-all-the-talented-girls-to-make-their-grand-career-in-the-glamour-industry--582894|title=Miss Diva 2020 is back for all the talented girls to make their grand career in the Glamour Industry|work=The Hans India|date=20 November 2019}}</ref> During the contest's sports round held in [[Bennett University]], she won the \"Miss Smasher\" award, for her performance in [[badminton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/noida/miss-diva-finalists-turn-athletes-at-bennett-university/articleshow/74032939.cms|title=Miss Diva finalists turn athletes at Bennett University|date=9 February 2020|last1=Sharma|first1=Riya|last2=Kaushik|first2=Divya|work=The Times of India}}</ref> On 22 February 2020, she was eventually crowned as Miss Diva Universe 2020 by the outgoing titleholder [[Vartika Singh]] at [[Yash Raj Films|Yash Raj Studio]], [[Andheri]], Mumbai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mangalorean.com/miss-diva-universe-2020-adline-castelino-to-represent-india-at-miss-universe-pageant/?amp|title=Adline Castelino to represent India at Miss Universe 2020 pageant|date=23 February 2020|publisher=www.mangalorean.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/hindi/2020/feb/23/adline-castelino-wins-miss-diva-universe-2020-2107394.amp|title=Adline Castelino wins Miss Diva Universe 2020|date=23 February 2020|work=The New Indian Express}}</ref>\n\nDuring the final question and answer round, the top 5 contestants were each asked the same question by the host, [[Malaika Arora]]: \"Does religion unite or divide people?\" To which Castelino replied:\n<blockquote>\n{{quote|text=\u201cReligion definitely unites people. It has values that bring people together. People believing in the same things come together and stay in harmony. When I first came here from Kuwait, I really loved the fact that in India, all religions stay together in harmony. We celebrate Diwali, Christmas, Eid all together and what a beautiful scene that is! Here we can stay together, respect each other's beliefs and be in harmony. We can progress with each other and move forward to the future.\u201d}}\n</blockquote>\n\n=== Miss Universe 2020 ===\nAs the winner of Miss Diva 2020, Castelino will represent India at the [[Miss Universe 2020]] competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/wire-updates/entertainment/2020/02/25/ent11-adline-miss%20universe.html|title=\"Stakes are high but passion is stronger\" - Adline Castelino on Miss Universe|date=25 February 2020|work=The Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/lifestyle/style/article/miss-diva-universe-grand-finale-2020-adline-castelino-to-represent-india-at-miss-universe-pageant-this-year/556622|title=Miss Diva Universe grand finale 2020: Adline Castelino to represent India at Miss Universe pageant this year|work=Times Now|date=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/lifestyle/celebrity/story/adline-castelino-to-represent-india-at-miss-universe-pageant-2020-1649262-2020-02-23|title=Adline Castelino to represent India at Miss Universe pageant 2020|date=23 February 2020|author=Indo-Asian News Service|work=India Today}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{instagram|adline_castelinofficial}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Vartika Singh]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Miss Diva 2020|Miss Diva Universe]]\n|years=[[Miss Diva 2020|2020]]}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Miss Universe 2020 delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Castelino, Adline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Female models from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti female models]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:Indian female models]]\n[[Category:Miss Universe 2020 contestants]]\n[[Category:People from Udupi]]\n[[Category:People from Kuwait City]]\n[[Category:Indian people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:Indian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Mangalorean Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian model and beauty pageant titleholder}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name         = Adline Castelino\n| image        =\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = Adline Mewis Quadros Castelino\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1998|07|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Kuwait City]], Kuwait\n| occupation   = {{hlist|Model}}\n| hometown     = [[Udupi|Udupi, Karnataka]], India\n| height       = {{height|ft=5|in=6}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Adline Castelino: Cast You Digital Casting Agency Profiles - |url=https://castyou.in/adline-castelino/}}</ref><!-- DO NOT CHANGE HEIGHT DETAILS. It has been established that she is 5'6\" cm, as per RS (reliable source). Thanks. -->\n| hair_color   = [[Black hair|Black]]\n| eye_color    = [[Eye color#Brown|Brown]]\n| alma_mater   = [[Wilson College, Mumbai]]\n| title        = [[Miss Diva 2020|Miss Diva Universe 2020]]<br>Miss Cocoaberry Diva 2019\n| competitions = [[Miss Diva 2020]]<br>(Winner)<br>[[Miss Universe 2020]]<br>(TBD)\n}}\n\n'''Adline Mewis Quadros Castelino''' (born 24 July 1998) is an Indian model and beauty pageant titleholder who was crowned [[Miss Diva 2020|Miss Diva Universe 2020]]. She will represent India at [[Miss Universe 2020]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nCastelino was born in [[Kuwait City]], Kuwait to [[Mangalorean Catholic]] parents Alphonsus and Meera Castelino. Her family is originally from [[Udyavara]] in the city of [[Udupi]], [[Karnataka]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/events/bangalore/a-grand-homecoming-for-liva-miss-diva-universe-2020-adline-castelino/amp_articleshow/74475590.cms|title=A grand homecoming for Miss Diva Universe 2020 Adline Castelino|work=The Times of India|date=5 March 2020|first1=Sunayana|last1=Suresh|first2=Tanvi|last2=PS}}</ref> In Kuwait, Castelino attended the [[Indian Central School (Kuwait)|Indian Central School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansinkuwait.com/news/Kuwait-born-Adline-Castelino-crowned-Miss-Diva-Universe-2020|title=Kuwait born Adline Castelino crowned Miss Diva Universe 2020|date=23 February 2020}}</ref> At age 15, Castelino returned to India and moved to [[Mumbai]], where she attended the St. Xavier High School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=660910|title=Adline Castelino first from city selected for Miss Diva Universe 2020|website=daijiworld.com}}</ref> She subsequently attended the [[Wilson College, Mumbai|Wilson College]] in Mumbai, where she graduated with a degree in business administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/life-style/spotlight/adline-castelino-im-grateful-to-my-college-for-making-me-who-i-am-today/amp_articleshow/74494825.cms|title=I\u2019m grateful to my college for making me who I am today:Adline Castelino|work=The Times of India|date=6 March 2020|first=Pooja|last=Raisinghani}}</ref>\n\n==Social work==\nCastelino works with a welfare organisation called ''Vikas Sahayog Pratishthan'' (VSP) which functions to provide a sustainable livelihood for framers to curb [[Farmers' suicides in India|farmers' suicides]] and inequality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zoomtventertainment.com/amp/celebrity/photo-gallery/photos-all-you-need-to-know-about-the-newly-crowned-miss-diva-universe-2020-adline-castelino/557632|title=All you need to know about the newly-crowned Miss Diva Universe 2020 Adline Castelino|date=25 February 2020|work=[[Zoom (Indian TV channel)|Zoom]]}}</ref> She has raised money for the Child Help Foundation (CHF), through a crowd funding platform called [[Ketto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ketto.org/amp/fundraiser/ADLINECASTELINOforCHFM2Q3M|title=Help Adline Castelino spread smiles for Child Help Foundation|publisher=www.ketto.org|accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref> During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus outbreak]] in 2020, she helped in providing essentials like food supplies, sanitizers and masks for 'Desire Society', a non-profit voluntary organization that cares for children infected with [[HIV]] in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-CKrNcBkEX/?igshid=1ngdjj3pvuxwo|title=Adline Castelino - Desire Society, Mumbai|date=22 March 2020}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-KclM-BJmJ/?igshid=o479ijdzmhfl|title=Adline Castelino - Supplies for Desire Society|date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://desiresociety.org/Default/Pages/Default.aspx|title=Desire Society - Official|publisher=desiresociety.org|accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Pageantry==\nAside from working as a model, Castelino has participated in various trivial pageants in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikifolder.com/adline-castelino/|title=Adline Castelino - Pofile|accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref> She further commenced her training for pageants through the Cocoaberry Training Academy in Mumbai. In 2019, she was crowned as 'Miss Cocoberry Diva' by the institution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenewscrunch.com/everything-you-should-know-about-miss-diva-universe-winner-adline-castelino-career-relationships-education-biography-recipes-and-unknown-facts-revealed/16679/|title=Everything you should know about Miss Diva Universe 2020 winner Adline Castelino|last=Benjamin|first=Annalise|date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thegreatpageantcommunity.com/2020/02/24/adline-castelino-wins-miss-universe-india-crown-at-miss-diva-2020/|title=Adline Castelino wins Miss Universe India crown at Miss Diva 2020|date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n=== Miss Diva 2020 ===\nIn 2019, Castelino auditioned for the [[Miss Diva 2020]] contest, through the [[Chennai]] auditions, and was shortlisted as a city finalist. In the culminating round of selections in [[Mumbai]], she entered as one of the top 20 delegates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tkop.org/2019/12/22/miss-universe-india-2020-meet-the-finalists-of-miss-diva-2020/|title=Miss Universe India 2020: The Finalists of Miss Diva 2020||date=22 December 2019|access-date=22 February 2020|last=Mishra|first=Vagisha}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehansindia.com/amp/life-style/miss-diva-2020-is-back-for-all-the-talented-girls-to-make-their-grand-career-in-the-glamour-industry--582894|title=Miss Diva 2020 is back for all the talented girls to make their grand career in the Glamour Industry|work=The Hans India|date=20 November 2019}}</ref> During the contest's sports round held in [[Bennett University]], she won the \"Miss Smasher\" award, for her performance in [[badminton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/noida/miss-diva-finalists-turn-athletes-at-bennett-university/articleshow/74032939.cms|title=Miss Diva finalists turn athletes at Bennett University|date=9 February 2020|last1=Sharma|first1=Riya|last2=Kaushik|first2=Divya|work=The Times of India}}</ref> On 22 February 2020, she was eventually crowned as Miss Diva Universe 2020 by the outgoing titleholder [[Vartika Singh]] at [[Yash Raj Films|Yash Raj Studio]], [[Andheri]], Mumbai.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mangalorean.com/miss-diva-universe-2020-adline-castelino-to-represent-india-at-miss-universe-pageant/?amp|title=Adline Castelino to represent India at Miss Universe 2020 pageant|date=23 February 2020|publisher=www.mangalorean.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/hindi/2020/feb/23/adline-castelino-wins-miss-diva-universe-2020-2107394.amp|title=Adline Castelino wins Miss Diva Universe 2020|date=23 February 2020|work=The New Indian Express}}</ref>\n\nDuring the final question and answer round, the top 5 contestants were each asked the same question by the host, [[Malaika Arora]]: \"Does religion unite or divide people?\" To which Castelino replied:\n<blockquote>\n{{quote|text=\u201cReligion definitely unites people. It has values that bring people together. People believing in the same things come together and stay in harmony. When I first came here from Kuwait, I really loved the fact that in India, all religions stay together in harmony. We celebrate Diwali, Christmas, Eid all together and what a beautiful scene that is! Here we can stay together, respect each other's beliefs and be in harmony. We can progress with each other and move forward to the future.\u201d}}\n</blockquote>\n\n=== Miss Universe 2020 ===\nAs the winner of Miss Diva 2020, Castelino will represent India at the [[Miss Universe 2020]] competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/wire-updates/entertainment/2020/02/25/ent11-adline-miss%20universe.html|title=\"Stakes are high but passion is stronger\" - Adline Castelino on Miss Universe|date=25 February 2020|work=The Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/lifestyle/style/article/miss-diva-universe-grand-finale-2020-adline-castelino-to-represent-india-at-miss-universe-pageant-this-year/556622|title=Miss Diva Universe grand finale 2020: Adline Castelino to represent India at Miss Universe pageant this year|work=Times Now|date=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/amp/lifestyle/celebrity/story/adline-castelino-to-represent-india-at-miss-universe-pageant-2020-1649262-2020-02-23|title=Adline Castelino to represent India at Miss Universe pageant 2020|date=23 February 2020|author=Indo-Asian News Service|work=India Today}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{instagram|adline_castelinofficial}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Vartika Singh]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Miss Diva 2020|Miss Diva Universe]]\n|years=[[Miss Diva 2020|2020]]}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Miss Universe 2020 delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Castelino, Adline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\